(398, 1, '2013-08-28 13:23:02', '2013-08-28 13:23:02', '<style type="text/css"><!--\r\n@page { margin: 0.79in } 		P { margin-bottom: 0.08in }\r\n--></style>\r\n<table width="498" border="0">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td><a><img class="wp-image-439 alignleft" alt="pdf-logo" src="http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/pdf-logo.jpg" width="51" height="51" /></a></td>\r\n<td>\r\n<h3 style="text-align: left;"><strong>2009-2011 Information Security Strategy for securitysense</strong></h3>\r\n</td>\r\n<td><a href="http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2009-2011-Information-Security-Strategy-for-securitysense.pdf"><img class="wp-image-444 alignleft" alt="download_iamge" src="http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/download_iamge.jpg" width="176" height="103" /></a></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>How to develop a IT/Information security strategy for your company?</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;">An information security strategic plan should include, at a minimum, an assessment of the current state of the program, a defined target state that is achievable within the three-year strategic planning window, a gap analysis and a road map for closing the gaps.</span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><b>Key Findings</b></span>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY">• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">A consistent framework can be defined that supports risk mitigation control objectives, architecture and </span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">process objectives, but the framework varies in scale and by the maturity level of the organization it''s </span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">being applied to.</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY">• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Small or immature organizations should focus on very simple frameworks.</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY">• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Consistent, incremental improvements are much more likely to succeed than rapidly forced changes.</span></span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><b>Recommendations</b></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Develop and document an information security strategic plan and use it to generate annual tactical </span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">plans that, when executed, move the overall maturity of the security program upward.</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Develop a process to review and refine the strategic plan annually.</span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><b>ANALYSIS</b></span>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Many organizations and security officers are approaching the creation of a strategic plan for information security for the first time, or have expressed a desire to use previously unimplemented best practices in creating the next iteration of one. Although there is no industry standard for the contents of such a plan, Securitysense has recommended organizations by using a model that has proved to be an effective communication tool with the numerous interested parties (including senior management), as well as a reasonable tracking mechanism for multiyear progress reports. While the model can be applied by organizations of any size and in any industry, the details vary based on the scale of the organization and the starting maturity level of the various effected organizational units.</span></span></p>\r\n<!--nextpage-->\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The information security strategic plan should not be viewed as a stand-alone document. It should exist as one part of a set of planning documents that start with a charter and a vision statement, but that also extends beyond the strategic plan into tactical and communications plans. Each of these has a role in providing context and action ability for the strategic plan. Organizations that have an established enterprise architecture (EA) function should leverage the existing EA disciplines, processes and standards to ensure that the strategic plan for information security is aligned with the EA strategy (see "Architecting Security: Different Approaches"). Securitysense generally considers three years to be an appropriate window for strategic planning for information security. The charter and vision statements deal with longer-term directions, while the tactical and communications plans specify single-year operational considerations and projects.</span></span></p>\r\n<span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The basic layout of the strategic plan is:</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Introduction and executive summary</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Strategic plan framework description</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Current state</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Desired state</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Gap analysis</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Prioritization plan</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Roles and responsibilities</span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>Introduction and Executive Summary</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The introduction should be written first, setting the purpose and scope of the document. The executive summary should be written last, showing only the final points of the document. The combination of executive summary and introduction should not exceed three pages, and, for most organizations, should be no more than two pages.</span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>Strategic Plan Framework Description</b></span></span>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The framework is the method by which the current state, desired state and gap analysis will be documented. An appropriate framework is one that can show overview (summarized) and detail (planning) information. The summary information should be expressed graphically. Frameworks should encompass controls, architecture and process elements to be complete.</span></span></p>\r\n<span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">For organizations with an established EA practice, an enterprise information security architecture (EISA) framework (see "The Structure and Content of an Information Security Architecture Framework") that aligns with the EA framework can act as an effective overall strategic security planning framework. Frameworks for this purpose can be derived from industry standards, from Securitysense research or from a combination of the two. </span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Some sources for framework structure and contents are:</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Controls</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">International Organization for Standardization (ISO)/International Electro technical</span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Commission (IEC) 27002</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Control Objectives for Information and Related Technology (COBIT)</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">U.S. National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) SP800-53</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Architecture</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">ISO10181</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">ISO13335</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Processes</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">ISO/IEC 27001</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Information Technology Infrastructure Library (ITIL)</span></span>\r\n<!--nextpage-->\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">In addition, Securitysense research can provide significant examples and guidelines for constructing such a framework (see the Recommended Reading section below). Large, mature organizations will require more-complex, detailed frameworks that focus largely on processes. Smaller or less mature organizations will find that simple frameworks suffice, and that all details can be left to the tactical planning stage, but that balanced (perhaps, not equal) attention to the three areas of controls, architecture and processes is required. An example of a simple framework for a low maturity organization might be a three-by-four grid showing the state of controls, technical architecture and processes for data, infrastructure, applications and people/behavior. Each cell in the grid can be assessed or targeted (depending on whether it is the current state or desired state framework copy) on a typical numeric maturity scale of 0 through 5, or assigned a color code of red, yellow or green (see Figure 1).</span></span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nFig 1\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Larger or more-mature organizations will tend to focus more on process assessments, because controls and architecture tend to be well-defined, and the processes by which they are kept up to date will be defined and will be the primary lever for further maturation. </span></span><span style="color: #ff0000;"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Securitysense''s "Toolkit: Risk Program Maturity Assessment 1.0" provides a full process-oriented framework that includes graphical reporting of information security, privacy, regulatory compliance and business continuity</span></span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="color: #ff0000;"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">programs (see Figure 2).</span></span></span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Figure 2. Strategic Plan Contents: Current State</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Controls Architecture Process</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Data</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Infrastructure</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Applications</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>People</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPSMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">N/A</span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: xx-small;"><b>Source: Securitysense (September 2008)</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>Current State</b></span></span>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Use the framework described in the previous section to document the current state of each element contained within the framework. A brief text section describes each entry and justifies the assessment. Organizations with mature risk assessment processes may reference the current risk register to provide an assessment of existing controls.</span></span></p>\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>Desired State</b></span></span>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Document the desired state for each element within the framework. Three years is not a long time to achieve any sort of cultural change, nor for a significant reduction in the overall level of risk. Using a maturity scale from zero through five, with steps of one-half for each of the framework elements, allows sufficient granularity to show, at a strategic level, what degree of progress is being attempted. Brief text descriptions contain the background for each target value. Securitysense recommends that a change in maturity level of no more than a "2" be attempted for any framework element in a three-year period, unless exceptional resources and executive support can be assured (see Figure 3 for an example based on Figure 1).</span></span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Figure 3. Strategic Plan Contents: Target State</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Controls Architecture Process</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Data</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Infrastructure</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Applications</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>People</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPSMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">N/A</span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The desired state may also identify controls and technology areas that require change, retirement or replacement, if those have already been identified.</span></span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>Gap Analysis</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">This section describes those elements of the framework that demonstrate variation between current and desired states (see Figure 4).</span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Figure 4. Strategic Plan Contents: Gap Analysis</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Controls Architecture Process</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPSMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">+2 +1 +1</span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPSMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">+2</span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPSMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">+2 +1 +1</span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Data</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Infrastructure</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Applications</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>People</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPSMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">N/A +1</span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>Prioritization Plan</b></span></span>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">There may be a natural order to resolving many of the issues identified via the gap analysis. Part of the three-year strategic plan should be guidance to tactical planners on how to prioritize the closure of those gaps, such that any natural order is optimized. Controls determine what should be achieved, but controls become meaningful only if the governance structure is functional. The IT organization needs direction via technical architecture to be efficient, but architecture requires guidance from controls. Operational processes related to technologies that are already in place depend, to some degree, on controls (what processes and technologies are needed) and architecture (which process elements and technologies are automated). As a result, a normal prioritization plan might be to start with governance, move to controls, then architecture and finally process. But this is a "greenfield" approach, and it may not be appropriate for organizations with variable levels of maturity in the current information security program or IT organizations in general. For example, a lack of maturity in strategic processes, such as risk assessment and security communications, which are not technology-dependent may demand earlier prioritization.</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Therefore, the method by which priorities will be assigned in the tactical plans requires some</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">strategic guidance. More-granular prioritization of work should be included in tactical (annual) planning documents, and should be based on criteria such as the relative risk impact, the cost, the mean time to value and the availability of resources.</span></span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>Roles and Responsibilities</b></span></span>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">This section describes who is responsible for delivering and who is responsible for approving each strategic and tactical deliverable that results from this strategic plan. There are four sets of organizational areas that need to be mapped to deliverables and action plans:</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY">• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The security office</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY">• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Lines of business (LOBs) or federation issues (responsibilities that reside with persons or departments </span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">that are affiliated with, but not reporting to, the central information security function)</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY">• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The IT organization</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY">• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Other business areas (typically, the functions that go on in headquarters, such as legal, HR and finance)</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The security office''s responsibilities should be easily extracted from the security charter. The authority, rights and obligations of LOB management and the IT organization should have been negotiated via the governance structure prior to, or as part of, the creation of this strategic plan. These authorities, rights and obligations are typically governed via some kind of information security steering committee. Other business areas may be surprised by their inclusion or may have expressed a need for involvement on their own, typically as a response to regulatory compliance needs.</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">One approach to documenting these roles and responsibilities that has been widely accepted by organization is the use of a responsible, accountable, consulted and informed (RACI) matrix. Once all these steps have been outlined, the executive summary can be written.</span></span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;', 'Security Strategy', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'security-strategy', '', '', '2013-08-29 08:32:10', '2013-08-29 08:32:10', '', 0, 'http://localhost/wordpress/?page_id=398', 0, 'page', '', 0),
(383, 1, '2013-08-28 12:29:03', '2013-08-28 12:29:03', '<p style="text-align: center;"><a href="http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/BCM-Life-Cycle.jpg"><img class="size-medium wp-image-380 aligncenter" alt="BCM Life Cycle" src="http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/BCM-Life-Cycle-300x300.jpg" width="300" height="300" /></a></p>\r\n\r\n<style type="text/css"><!--\r\n@page { margin: 0.79in }\r\n		P { margin-bottom: 0.08in }\r\n--></style><span style="color: #403152;"><span style="font-family: Trebuchet MS,serif;"><span style="font-size: x-large;"><b>How will it benefit my organization?</b></span></span></span>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="color: #000000;"><span style="font-family: Trebuchet MS,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The main purpose of BCM is to ensure that the organization has a response to major disruptions that threaten its survival. Whilst this must be worthwhile in itself, there are other benefits that can be gained by embracing BCM as a management discipline. Some organizations have statutory and regulatory requirements either specifically for BCM or more generally for </span></span></span><span style="color: #000000;"><span style="font-family: Trebuchet MS,serif;"><span style="font-size: xx-small;">‘</span></span></span><span style="color: #000000;"><span style="font-family: Trebuchet MS,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">risk management</span></span></span><span style="color: #000000;"><span style="font-family: Trebuchet MS,serif;"><span style="font-size: xx-small;">’ </span></span></span><span style="color: #000000;"><span style="font-family: Trebuchet MS,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">as part of their corporate governance requirement. An appropriate BCM plan will satisfy both the specific requirements and contribute both a response to specific risks and to the overall </span></span></span><span style="color: #000000;"><span style="font-family: Trebuchet MS,serif;"><span style="font-size: xx-small;">‘</span></span></span><span style="color: #000000;"><span style="font-family: Trebuchet MS,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">risk awareness</span></span></span><span style="color: #000000;"><span style="font-family: Trebuchet MS,serif;"><span style="font-size: xx-small;">’ </span></span></span><span style="color: #000000;"><span style="font-family: Trebuchet MS,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">of an organization. However the primary driver for BCM should always be that it is undertaken because it adds value to an organization and the products and services it delivers rather than because of governance or regulatory considerations.</span></span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="color: #000000;">“</span><span style="color: #000000;"><span style="font-family: Trebuchet MS,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">For many companies, BCM will address some…key risks and help them achieve compliance</span></span></span><span style="color: #000000;"><span style="font-family: Trebuchet MS,serif;"><span style="font-size: xx-small;">"</span></span></span><span style="color: #000000;"><span style="font-family: Trebuchet MS,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">. Nigel Turnbull, Chairman of Turnbull Committee on UK Corporate Governance. Businesses selling to other businesses have used BCM as a competitive advantage to gain new customers and to improve margins by using it as a demonstration of </span></span></span><span style="color: #000000;"><span style="font-family: Trebuchet MS,serif;"><span style="font-size: xx-small;">‘</span></span></span><span style="color: #000000;"><span style="font-family: Trebuchet MS,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">customer care</span></span></span><span style="color: #000000;"><span style="font-family: Trebuchet MS,serif;"><span style="font-size: xx-small;">’</span></span></span><span style="color: #000000;"><span style="font-family: Trebuchet MS,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">. A thorough review of the business through Business Impact Assessment and Plan exercises can highlight business inefficiencies and focus on priorities that would not otherwise have come to light.</span></span></span></p>\r\n<span style="font-family: Verdana,serif;"><span style="font-size: x-large;"><b>Conclusion</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;">There is a lot of ground to cover in performing comprehensive Business Continuity Management.  This web site strives to provide information in most of these areas. Pages on many of the planning areas are provided that will describe the issues and provide information and resource to assist you in your BCM efforts.</span></span>', 'BCM Life Cycle', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '379-revision-v1', '', '', '2013-08-28 12:29:03', '2013-08-28 12:29:03', '', 379, 'http://localhost/wordpress/?p=383', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(384, 1, '2013-08-28 12:30:44', '2013-08-28 12:30:44', '<style type="text/css"><!--\r\n@page { margin: 0.79in }\r\n		H2 { margin-top: 0.02in; margin-bottom: 0.02in; line-height: 100%; page-break-after: auto }\r\n		H2.western { font-family: "Times New Roman", serif }\r\n		H2.cjk { font-family: "Times New Roman" }\r\n		H2.ctl { font-family: "Times New Roman" }\r\n		P { margin-bottom: 0.08in }\r\n		H4 { margin-top: 0.14in; margin-bottom: 0in; color: #4f81bd; page-break-inside: avoid }\r\n		H4.western { font-family: "Cambria", serif; font-size: 12pt; font-style: italic }\r\n		H4.cjk { font-family: "DejaVu Sans"; font-size: 12pt; font-style: italic }\r\n		H4.ctl { font-family: ; font-size: 12pt; font-style: italic }\r\n--></style><span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;">The first step in the planning process is to conduct a risk assessment and a business impact assessment.  The next step is to decide what measures can be put in place to prevent risks becoming reality and to minimize damage if a disaster does occur. Not all risks are preventable, but steps can be taken to minimize the likelihood that they will happen. </span></span>\r\n<h2>Business Continuity Plan Development</h2>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;">Typical approach to Business Continuity Plan (BCP) development is to work closely with the client organization''s staff to develop a comprehensive plan based on a five-phase project plan as follows:</span></span></p>\r\n<span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;">1. Business Impact Assessment (BIA)\r\n2. Business Continuity Plan development\r\n3. Staff Training\r\n4. Business Continuity Plan Validation: Drills and Exercises\r\n5. Program Effectiveness Evaluation &amp; Monitoring</span></span>\r\n<h2>Description of Project Phases</h2>\r\n<h4>Phase 1: Business Impact Assessment</h4>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;">BCM team will identify, review, evaluate and prioritize issues that pose potential crises and/or negative impact for the client''s business operations. The joint team will also analyze the client''s current overall business continuity management planning efforts. The BIA is a diagnostic survey that consists of issue analyses, risk identification, and assessment of potential business impacts and crisis situations. The diagnostic survey assists us to determine the client current capabilities, level of training, and categorization of potential business disruption situations. The review of current initiatives will include:</span></span></p>\r\n<span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;">1. Current Business Continuity Plan/Program Review\r\n2. Corporate Office Capabilities (Assignment of Responsibility)\r\n3. Identification of Resources (Internal, External)\r\n4. Categorization of Potential Issues, Threats, Risks, Business Impacts and Crisis Situations\r\n5. Crisis Communications Systems (including media &amp; security)\r\n6. Current Level of Training\r\n7. Interface Mechanisms</span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;">Our approach generally will be to:</span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;"><b>Interview Key Personnel</b>: The personnel interviews will review business operations, current business continuity initiatives, general information on business continuity management and emergency preparedness, incident scenarios, policy, compliance initiatives, crisis media response, internal/external interfaces (infrastructures), business risks, strategic direction, documentation and training.\r\n\r\n<b>Review Current Written Business Continuity Plans and Materials</b>: This review will consist of a comparison of the present Business Continuity Plan Manuals and Supporting Materials against applicable corporate policies, procedures and applicable requirements. Recommendations for improvements will be made as a part of this review.</span></span>\r\n<h4>Phase 2: Business Continuity Plan Development</h4>\r\n<span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;">Our approach is to assist the client''s management in designing, developing and implementing a Business Continuity Plan, as follows:</span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;">1. Develop draft BCP materials.\r\n2. Review the draft materials with key personnel.\r\n3. Prepare final BCP materials.</span></span>\r\n<h4>Phase 3: Key Staff Training</h4>\r\n<span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;">Development and implementation of staff training based on the Business Continuity Plan developed in Phase 2, as follows:</span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;">1. Develop draft BCP Training Program.\r\n2. Review the draft material with key client personnel.\r\n3. Develop final BCP Training Program.\r\n4. Schedule and Conduct BCP Training.</span></span>\r\n<h4>Phase 4: Plan Validation: Drills and Exercises</h4>\r\n<span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;">Validation of the Business Continuity Plan through the development and implementation of a comprehensive drill and exercise program, as follows:</span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;">1. Develop draft Business Continuity Plan Drill Scenarios.\r\n2. Review the draft material with key client personnel.\r\n3. Develop final Business Continuity Plan Drill Scenarios.\r\n4. Develop draft Drill Participant, Controller, Evaluator Training Program.\r\n5. Review the draft material with key client personnel.\r\n6. Develop Drill Participant, Controller, and Evaluator Training Program.\r\n7. Schedule and Conduct Drill Participant, Controller, Evaluator Training\r\n8. Schedule and Conduct Drills and Exercises.</span></span>\r\n<h4>Phase 5: Program Effectiveness Evaluation and Monitoring</h4>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;">Upon completion of the initial four phases of the Business Continuity Plan program, BCM team will do periodic third party assessment and monitoring of the effectiveness of the Business Continuity Plan, Level of Training and Plan Validation process. The evaluation program, presented herein, is designed to assess the ability of management and response personnel to complete the sequence of critical tasks, under a business disruption condition, using available resources as outlined in the plan and associated materials.</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;">The findings in relation to the organization''s ability to meet the criteria for "All Hazards" preparedness is based upon the evaluation of nine Essential Element of Analysis (EEA). These are:</span></span></p>\r\n<span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;">1. Administration (BCMP and Supporting Materials)\r\n2. Incident Management/Response Organization\r\n3. Training and Retraining Program\r\n4. BCMP Facilities and Equipment\r\n5. BCMP Implementing Protocols\r\n6. Coordination with External Entities\r\n7. BCMP Validation: Drills and Exercises\r\n8. Communications\r\n9. Ongoing Hazard/Vulnerability/Risk Evaluation</span></span>\r\n<h2>Summary</h2>\r\n<span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;">This plan is subject to revision based on client needs and preferences. The entire project plan is modular and can be modified as mutually agreed upon with the client. </span></span>', 'BCM Planning Process', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '382-revision-v1', '', '', '2013-08-28 12:30:44', '2013-08-28 12:30:44', '', 382, 'http://localhost/wordpress/?p=384', 0, 'revision', '', 0);
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` (`ID`, `post_author`, `post_date`, `post_date_gmt`, `post_content`, `post_title`, `post_excerpt`, `post_status`, `comment_status`, `ping_status`, `post_password`, `post_name`, `to_ping`, `pinged`, `post_modified`, `post_modified_gmt`, `post_content_filtered`, `post_parent`, `guid`, `menu_order`, `post_type`, `post_mime_type`, `comment_count`) VALUES
(385, 1, '2013-08-28 12:31:07', '2013-08-28 12:31:07', '<style type="text/css"><!--\r\n@page { margin: 0.79in }\r\n		H2 { margin-top: 0.02in; margin-bottom: 0.02in; line-height: 100%; page-break-after: auto }\r\n		H2.western { font-family: "Times New Roman", serif }\r\n		H2.cjk { font-family: "Times New Roman" }\r\n		H2.ctl { font-family: "Times New Roman" }\r\n		P { margin-bottom: 0.08in }\r\n		H4 { margin-top: 0.14in; margin-bottom: 0in; color: #4f81bd; page-break-inside: avoid }\r\n		H4.western { font-family: "Cambria", serif; font-size: 12pt; font-style: italic }\r\n		H4.cjk { font-family: "DejaVu Sans"; font-size: 12pt; font-style: italic }\r\n		H4.ctl { font-family: ; font-size: 12pt; font-style: italic }\r\n--></style><span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;">The first step in the planning process is to conduct a risk assessment and a business impact assessment.  The next step is to decide what measures can be put in place to prevent risks becoming reality and to minimize damage if a disaster does occur. Not all risks are preventable, but steps can be taken to minimize the likelihood that they will happen. </span></span>\r\n<h2>Business Continuity Plan Development</h2>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;">Typical approach to Business Continuity Plan (BCP) development is to work closely with the client organization''s staff to develop a comprehensive plan based on a five-phase project plan as follows:</span></span></p>\r\n<span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;">1. Business Impact Assessment (BIA)\r\n2. Business Continuity Plan development\r\n3. Staff Training\r\n4. Business Continuity Plan Validation: Drills and Exercises\r\n5. Program Effectiveness Evaluation &amp; Monitoring</span></span>\r\n<h2>Description of Project Phases</h2>\r\n<h4>Phase 1: Business Impact Assessment</h4>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;">BCM team will identify, review, evaluate and prioritize issues that pose potential crises and/or negative impact for the client''s business operations. The joint team will also analyze the client''s current overall business continuity management planning efforts. The BIA is a diagnostic survey that consists of issue analyses, risk identification, and assessment of potential business impacts and crisis situations. The diagnostic survey assists us to determine the client current capabilities, level of training, and categorization of potential business disruption situations. The review of current initiatives will include:</span></span></p>\r\n<span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;">1. Current Business Continuity Plan/Program Review\r\n2. Corporate Office Capabilities (Assignment of Responsibility)\r\n3. Identification of Resources (Internal, External)\r\n4. Categorization of Potential Issues, Threats, Risks, Business Impacts and Crisis Situations\r\n5. Crisis Communications Systems (including media &amp; security)\r\n6. Current Level of Training\r\n7. Interface Mechanisms</span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;">Our approach generally will be to:</span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;"><b>Interview Key Personnel</b>: The personnel interviews will review business operations, current business continuity initiatives, general information on business continuity management and emergency preparedness, incident scenarios, policy, compliance initiatives, crisis media response, internal/external interfaces (infrastructures), business risks, strategic direction, documentation and training.</span></span>\r\n\r\n<b>Review Current Written Business Continuity Plans and Materials</b>: This review will consist of a comparison of the present Business Continuity Plan Manuals and Supporting Materials against applicable corporate policies, procedures and applicable requirements. Recommendations for improvements will be made as a part of this review.\r\n<h4>Phase 2: Business Continuity Plan Development</h4>\r\n<span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;">Our approach is to assist the client''s management in designing, developing and implementing a Business Continuity Plan, as follows:</span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;">1. Develop draft BCP materials.\r\n2. Review the draft materials with key personnel.\r\n3. Prepare final BCP materials.</span></span>\r\n<h4>Phase 3: Key Staff Training</h4>\r\n<span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;">Development and implementation of staff training based on the Business Continuity Plan developed in Phase 2, as follows:</span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;">1. Develop draft BCP Training Program.\r\n2. Review the draft material with key client personnel.\r\n3. Develop final BCP Training Program.\r\n4. Schedule and Conduct BCP Training.</span></span>\r\n<h4>Phase 4: Plan Validation: Drills and Exercises</h4>\r\n<span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;">Validation of the Business Continuity Plan through the development and implementation of a comprehensive drill and exercise program, as follows:</span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;">1. Develop draft Business Continuity Plan Drill Scenarios.\r\n2. Review the draft material with key client personnel.\r\n3. Develop final Business Continuity Plan Drill Scenarios.\r\n4. Develop draft Drill Participant, Controller, Evaluator Training Program.\r\n5. Review the draft material with key client personnel.\r\n6. Develop Drill Participant, Controller, and Evaluator Training Program.\r\n7. Schedule and Conduct Drill Participant, Controller, Evaluator Training\r\n8. Schedule and Conduct Drills and Exercises.</span></span>\r\n<h4>Phase 5: Program Effectiveness Evaluation and Monitoring</h4>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;">Upon completion of the initial four phases of the Business Continuity Plan program, BCM team will do periodic third party assessment and monitoring of the effectiveness of the Business Continuity Plan, Level of Training and Plan Validation process. The evaluation program, presented herein, is designed to assess the ability of management and response personnel to complete the sequence of critical tasks, under a business disruption condition, using available resources as outlined in the plan and associated materials.</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;">The findings in relation to the organization''s ability to meet the criteria for "All Hazards" preparedness is based upon the evaluation of nine Essential Element of Analysis (EEA). These are:</span></span></p>\r\n<span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;">1. Administration (BCMP and Supporting Materials)\r\n2. Incident Management/Response Organization\r\n3. Training and Retraining Program\r\n4. BCMP Facilities and Equipment\r\n5. BCMP Implementing Protocols\r\n6. Coordination with External Entities\r\n7. BCMP Validation: Drills and Exercises\r\n8. Communications\r\n9. Ongoing Hazard/Vulnerability/Risk Evaluation</span></span>\r\n<h2>Summary</h2>\r\n<span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;">This plan is subject to revision based on client needs and preferences. The entire project plan is modular and can be modified as mutually agreed upon with the client. </span></span>', 'BCM Planning Process', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '382-revision-v1', '', '', '2013-08-28 12:31:07', '2013-08-28 12:31:07', '', 382, 'http://localhost/wordpress/?p=385', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(386, 1, '2013-08-28 12:32:06', '2013-08-28 12:32:06', '<style type="text/css"><!--\r\n@page { margin: 0.79in }\r\n		H2 { margin-top: 0.02in; margin-bottom: 0.02in; line-height: 100%; page-break-after: auto }\r\n		H2.western { font-family: "Times New Roman", serif }\r\n		H2.cjk { font-family: "Times New Roman" }\r\n		H2.ctl { font-family: "Times New Roman" }\r\n		P { margin-bottom: 0.08in }\r\n		H4 { margin-top: 0.14in; margin-bottom: 0in; color: #4f81bd; page-break-inside: avoid }\r\n		H4.western { font-family: "Cambria", serif; font-size: 12pt; font-style: italic }\r\n		H4.cjk { font-family: "DejaVu Sans"; font-size: 12pt; font-style: italic }\r\n		H4.ctl { font-family: ; font-size: 12pt; font-style: italic }\r\n--></style><span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;">The first step in the planning process is to conduct a risk assessment and a business impact assessment.  The next step is to decide what measures can be put in place to prevent risks becoming reality and to minimize damage if a disaster does occur. Not all risks are preventable, but steps can be taken to minimize the likelihood that they will happen. </span></span>\r\n<h2>Business Continuity Plan Development</h2>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;">Typical approach to Business Continuity Plan (BCP) development is to work closely with the client organization''s staff to develop a comprehensive plan based on a five-phase project plan as follows:</span></span></p>\r\n<span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;">1. Business Impact Assessment (BIA)\r\n2. Business Continuity Plan development\r\n3. Staff Training\r\n4. Business Continuity Plan Validation: Drills and Exercises\r\n5. Program Effectiveness Evaluation &amp; Monitoring</span></span>\r\n<h2>Description of Project Phases</h2>\r\n<h4>Phase 1: Business Impact Assessment</h4>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;">BCM team will identify, review, evaluate and prioritize issues that pose potential crises and/or negative impact for the client''s business operations. The joint team will also analyze the client''s current overall business continuity management planning efforts. The BIA is a diagnostic survey that consists of issue analyses, risk identification, and assessment of potential business impacts and crisis situations. The diagnostic survey assists us to determine the client current capabilities, level of training, and categorization of potential business disruption situations. The review of current initiatives will include:</span></span></p>\r\n<span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;">1. Current Business Continuity Plan/Program Review\r\n2. Corporate Office Capabilities (Assignment of Responsibility)\r\n3. Identification of Resources (Internal, External)\r\n4. Categorization of Potential Issues, Threats, Risks, Business Impacts and Crisis Situations\r\n5. Crisis Communications Systems (including media &amp; security)\r\n6. Current Level of Training\r\n7. Interface Mechanisms</span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;">Our approach generally will be to:</span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;"><b>Interview Key Personnel</b>: The personnel interviews will review business operations, current business continuity initiatives, general information on business continuity management and emergency preparedness, incident scenarios, policy, compliance initiatives, crisis media response, internal/external interfaces (infrastructures), business risks, strategic direction, documentation and training.</span></span>\r\n\r\n<b>Review Current Written Business Continuity Plans and Materials</b>: This review will consist of a comparison of the present Business Continuity Plan Manuals and Supporting Materials against applicable corporate policies, procedures and applicable requirements. Recommendations for improvements will be made as a part of this review.\r\n<h4>Phase 2: Business Continuity Plan Development</h4>\r\n<span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;">Our approach is to assist the client''s management in designing, developing and implementing a Business Continuity Plan, as follows:</span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;">1. Develop draft BCP materials.\r\n2. Review the draft materials with key personnel.\r\n3. Prepare final BCP materials.</span></span>\r\n<h4>Phase 3: Key Staff Training</h4>\r\n<span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;">Development and implementation of staff training based on the Business Continuity Plan developed in Phase 2, as follows:</span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;">1. Develop draft BCP Training Program.\r\n2. Review the draft material with key client personnel.\r\n3. Develop final BCP Training Program.\r\n4. Schedule and Conduct BCP Training.</span></span>\r\n<h4>Phase 4: Plan Validation: Drills and Exercises</h4>\r\n<span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;">Validation of the Business Continuity Plan through the development and implementation of a comprehensive drill and exercise program, as follows:</span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;">1. Develop draft Business Continuity Plan Drill Scenarios.\r\n2. Review the draft material with key client personnel.\r\n3. Develop final Business Continuity Plan Drill Scenarios.\r\n4. Develop draft Drill Participant, Controller, Evaluator Training Program.\r\n5. Review the draft material with key client personnel.\r\n6. Develop Drill Participant, Controller, and Evaluator Training Program.\r\n7. Schedule and Conduct Drill Participant, Controller, Evaluator Training\r\n8. Schedule and Conduct Drills and Exercises.</span></span>\r\n<h4>Phase 5: Program Effectiveness Evaluation and Monitoring</h4>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;">Upon completion of the initial four phases of the Business Continuity Plan program, BCM team will do periodic third party assessment and monitoring of the effectiveness of the Business Continuity Plan, Level of Training and Plan Validation process. The evaluation program, presented herein, is designed to assess the ability of management and response personnel to complete the sequence of critical tasks, under a business disruption condition, using available resources as outlined in the plan and associated materials.</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;">The findings in relation to the organization''s ability to meet the criteria for "All Hazards" preparedness is based upon the evaluation of nine Essential Element of Analysis (EEA). These are:</span></span></p>\r\n<span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;">1. Administration (BCMP and Supporting Materials)\r\n2. Incident Management/Response Organization\r\n3. Training and Retraining Program\r\n4. BCMP Facilities and Equipment\r\n5. BCMP Implementing Protocols\r\n6. Coordination with External Entities\r\n7. BCMP Validation: Drills and Exercises\r\n8. Communications\r\n9. Ongoing Hazard/Vulnerability/Risk Evaluation</span></span>\r\n<h2>Summary</h2>\r\n<span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;">This plan is subject to revision based on client needs and preferences. The entire project plan is modular and can be modified as mutually agreed upon with the client. </span></span>', 'BCM Planning Process', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '382-autosave-v1', '', '', '2013-08-28 12:32:06', '2013-08-28 12:32:06', '', 382, 'http://localhost/wordpress/?p=386', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(387, 1, '2013-08-28 12:32:31', '2013-08-28 12:32:31', '<style type="text/css"><!--\r\n@page { margin: 0.79in } 		P { margin-bottom: 0.08in }\r\n--></style>\r\n<table width="498" border="0">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td><a><img alt="pdf-logo" src="http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/pdf-logo.jpg" width="51" height="51" /></a></td>\r\n<td>\r\n<h3><strong>Securitysense  BCM Policy</strong></h3>\r\n</td>\r\n<td><a href="http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/Securitysense-BCM-Policy-v1.0.pdf"><img alt="download_iamge" src="http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/download_iamge.jpg" width="176" height="103" /></a></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td><a><img alt="pdf-logo" src="http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/pdf-logo.jpg" width="51" height="51" /></a></td>\r\n<td>\r\n<h3><strong>BCM Strategy</strong></h3>\r\n</td>\r\n<td><a href="http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2009-2011-Information-Security-Strategy-for-securitysense.pdf"><img alt="download_iamge" src="http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/download_iamge.jpg" width="176" height="103" /></a></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td><a><img alt="pdf-logo" src="http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/pdf-logo.jpg" width="51" height="51" /></a></td>\r\n<td>\r\n<h3><strong>BCM framework</strong></h3>\r\n</td>\r\n<td><a href="http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2009-2011-Information-Security-Strategy-for-securitysense.pdf"><img alt="download_iamge" src="http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/download_iamge.jpg" width="176" height="103" /></a></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td><a><img alt="pdf-logo" src="http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/pdf-logo.jpg" width="51" height="51" /></a></td>\r\n<td>\r\n<h3><strong>BIA</strong></h3>\r\n</td>\r\n<td><a href="http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2009-2011-Information-Security-Strategy-for-securitysense.pdf"><img alt="download_iamge" src="http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/download_iamge.jpg" width="176" height="103" /></a></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n&nbsp;', 'Practical sample', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'practical-sample', '', '', '2013-08-29 09:12:59', '2013-08-29 09:12:59', '', 0, 'http://localhost/wordpress/?page_id=387', 0, 'page', '', 0),
(388, 1, '2013-08-28 12:32:31', '2013-08-28 12:32:31', '<style type="text/css"><!--\r\n@page { margin: 0.79in }\r\n		P { margin-bottom: 0.08in }\r\n--></style><span style="color: #000000;">- BCM Policy</span>\r\n\r\n<span style="color: #000000;">- BCM Strategy </span>\r\n\r\n<span style="color: #000000;">- BCM framework</span>\r\n\r\n<span style="color: #000000;">- BIA</span>', 'Practical sample', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '387-revision-v1', '', '', '2013-08-28 12:32:31', '2013-08-28 12:32:31', '', 387, 'http://localhost/wordpress/?p=388', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(390, 1, '2013-08-28 12:37:06', '2013-08-28 12:37:06', ' ', '', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', '390', '', '', '2013-08-29 08:28:15', '2013-08-29 08:28:15', '', 0, 'http://localhost/wordpress/?p=390', 16, 'nav_menu_item', '', 0),
(391, 1, '2013-08-28 12:35:28', '2013-08-28 12:35:28', '<p align="JUSTIFY">The main purpose of BCM is to ensure that the organization has a response to major disruptions that threaten its survival. Whilst this must be worthwhile in itself, there are other benefits that can be gained by embracing BCM as a management discipline. Some organizations have statutory and regulatory requirements either specifically for BCM or more generally for ‘risk management’ as part of their corporate governance requirement. An appropriate BCM plan will satisfy both the specific requirements and contribute both a response to specific risks and to the overall ‘risk awareness’ of an organization. However the primary driver for BCM should always be that it is undertaken because it adds value to an organization and the products and services it delivers rather than because of governance or regulatory considerations.</p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY">“For many companies, BCM will address some…key risks and help them achieve compliance". Nigel Turnbull, Chairman of Turnbull Committee on UK Corporate Governance. Businesses selling to other businesses have used BCM as a competitive advantage to gain new customers and to improve margins by using it as a demonstration of ‘customer care’. A thorough review of the business through Business Impact Assessment and Plan exercises can highlight business inefficiencies and focus on priorities that would not otherwise have come to light.</p>\r\n<b>Conclusion</b>\r\n\r\nThere is a lot of ground to cover in performing comprehensive Business Continuity Management.  This web site strives to provide information in most of these areas. Pages on many of the planning areas are provided that will describe the issues and provide information and resource to assist you in your BCM efforts.', 'How will it benefit my organization?', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'how-will-it-benefit-my-organization', '', '', '2013-08-28 12:35:28', '2013-08-28 12:35:28', '', 0, 'http://localhost/wordpress/?page_id=391', 0, 'page', '', 0),
(399, 1, '2013-08-28 13:23:02', '2013-08-28 13:23:02', '<style type="text/css"><!--\r\n@page { margin: 0.79in }\r\n		P { margin-bottom: 0.08in }\r\n--></style><span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>How to develop a IT/Information security strategy for your company?</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;">An information security strategic plan should include, at a minimum, an assessment of the current state of the program, a defined target state that is achievable within the three-year strategic planning window, a gap analysis and a road map for closing the gaps.</span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><b>Key Findings</b></span>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY">• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">A consistent framework can be defined that supports risk mitigation control objectives, architecture and </span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">process objectives, but the framework varies in scale and by the maturity level of the organization it''s </span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">being applied to.</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY">• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Small or immature organizations should focus on very simple frameworks.</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY">• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Consistent, incremental improvements are much more likely to succeed than rapidly forced changes.</span></span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><b>Recommendations</b></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Develop and document an information security strategic plan and use it to generate annual tactical </span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">plans that, when executed, move the overall maturity of the security program upward.</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Develop a process to review and refine the strategic plan annually.</span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><b>ANALYSIS</b></span>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Many organizations and security officers are approaching the creation of a strategic plan for information security for the first time, or have expressed a desire to use previously unimplemented best practices in creating the next iteration of one. Although there is no industry standard for the contents of such a plan, Securitysense has recommended organizations by using a model that has proved to be an effective communication tool with the numerous interested parties (including senior management), as well as a reasonable tracking mechanism for multiyear progress reports. While the model can be applied by organizations of any size and in any industry, the details vary based on the scale of the organization and the starting maturity level of the various effected organizational units.</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The information security strategic plan should not be viewed as a stand-alone document. It should exist as one part of a set of planning documents that start with a charter and a vision statement, but that also extends beyond the strategic plan into tactical and communications plans. Each of these has a role in providing context and action ability for the strategic plan. Organizations that have an established enterprise architecture (EA) function should leverage the existing EA disciplines, processes and standards to ensure that the strategic plan for information security is aligned with the EA strategy (see "Architecting Security: Different Approaches"). Securitysense generally considers three years to be an appropriate window for strategic planning for information security. The charter and vision statements deal with longer-term directions, while the tactical and communications plans specify single-year operational considerations and projects.</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"></p>\r\n<span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The basic layout of the strategic plan is:</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Introduction and executive summary</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Strategic plan framework description</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Current state</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Desired state</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Gap analysis</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Prioritization plan</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Roles and responsibilities</span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>Introduction and Executive Summary</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The introduction should be written first, setting the purpose and scope of the document. The executive summary should be written last, showing only the final points of the document. The combination of executive summary and introduction should not exceed three pages, and, for most organizations, should be no more than two pages.</span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>Strategic Plan Framework Description</b></span></span>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The framework is the method by which the current state, desired state and gap analysis will be documented. An appropriate framework is one that can show overview (summarized) and detail (planning) information. The summary information should be expressed graphically. Frameworks should encompass controls, architecture and process elements to be complete.</span></span></p>\r\n<span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">For organizations with an established EA practice, an enterprise information security architecture (EISA) framework (see "The Structure and Content of an Information Security Architecture Framework") that aligns with the EA framework can act as an effective overall strategic security planning framework. Frameworks for this purpose can be derived from industry standards, from Securitysense research or from a combination of the two. </span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Some sources for framework structure and contents are:</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Controls</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">International Organization for Standardization (ISO)/International Electro technical</span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Commission (IEC) 27002</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Control Objectives for Information and Related Technology (COBIT)</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">U.S. National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) SP800-53</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Architecture</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">ISO10181</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">ISO13335</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Processes</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">ISO/IEC 27001</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Information Technology Infrastructure Library (ITIL)</span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">In addition, Securitysense research can provide significant examples and guidelines for constructing such a framework (see the Recommended Reading section below). Large, mature organizations will require more-complex, detailed frameworks that focus largely on processes. Smaller or less mature organizations will find that simple frameworks suffice, and that all details can be left to the tactical planning stage, but that balanced (perhaps, not equal) attention to the three areas of controls, architecture and processes is required. An example of a simple framework for a low maturity organization might be a three-by-four grid showing the state of controls, technical architecture and processes for data, infrastructure, applications and people/behavior. Each cell in the grid can be assessed or targeted (depending on whether it is the current state or desired state framework copy) on a typical numeric maturity scale of 0 through 5, or assigned a color code of red, yellow or green (see Figure 1).</span></span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nFig 1\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Larger or more-mature organizations will tend to focus more on process assessments, because controls and architecture tend to be well-defined, and the processes by which they are kept up to date will be defined and will be the primary lever for further maturation. </span></span><span style="color: #ff0000;"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Securitysense''s "Toolkit: Risk Program Maturity Assessment 1.0" provides a full process-oriented framework that includes graphical reporting of information security, privacy, regulatory compliance and business continuity</span></span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="color: #ff0000;"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">programs (see Figure 2).</span></span></span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Figure 2. Strategic Plan Contents: Current State</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Controls Architecture Process</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Data</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Infrastructure</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Applications</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>People</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPSMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">N/A</span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: xx-small;"><b>Source: Securitysense (September 2008)</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>Current State</b></span></span>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Use the framework described in the previous section to document the current state of each element contained within the framework. A brief text section describes each entry and justifies the assessment. Organizations with mature risk assessment processes may reference the current risk register to provide an assessment of existing controls.</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"></p>\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>Desired State</b></span></span>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Document the desired state for each element within the framework. Three years is not a long time to achieve any sort of cultural change, nor for a significant reduction in the overall level of risk. Using a maturity scale from zero through five, with steps of one-half for each of the framework elements, allows sufficient granularity to show, at a strategic level, what degree of progress is being attempted. Brief text descriptions contain the background for each target value. Securitysense recommends that a change in maturity level of no more than a "2" be attempted for any framework element in a three-year period, unless exceptional resources and executive support can be assured (see Figure 3 for an example based on Figure 1).</span></span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Figure 3. Strategic Plan Contents: Target State</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Controls Architecture Process</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Data</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Infrastructure</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Applications</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>People</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPSMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">N/A</span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The desired state may also identify controls and technology areas that require change, retirement or replacement, if those have already been identified.</span></span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>Gap Analysis</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">This section describes those elements of the framework that demonstrate variation between current and desired states (see Figure 4).</span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Figure 4. Strategic Plan Contents: Gap Analysis</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Controls Architecture Process</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPSMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">+2 +1 +1</span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPSMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">+2</span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPSMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">+2 +1 +1</span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Data</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Infrastructure</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Applications</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>People</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPSMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">N/A +1</span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>Prioritization Plan</b></span></span>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">There may be a natural order to resolving many of the issues identified via the gap analysis. Part of the three-year strategic plan should be guidance to tactical planners on how to prioritize the closure of those gaps, such that any natural order is optimized. Controls determine what should be achieved, but controls become meaningful only if the governance structure is functional. The IT organization needs direction via technical architecture to be efficient, but architecture requires guidance from controls. Operational processes related to technologies that are already in place depend, to some degree, on controls (what processes and technologies are needed) and architecture (which process elements and technologies are automated). As a result, a normal prioritization plan might be to start with governance, move to controls, then architecture and finally process. But this is a "greenfield" approach, and it may not be appropriate for organizations with variable levels of maturity in the current information security program or IT organizations in general. For example, a lack of maturity in strategic processes, such as risk assessment and security communications, which are not technology-dependent may demand earlier prioritization.</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Therefore, the method by which priorities will be assigned in the tactical plans requires some</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">strategic guidance. More-granular prioritization of work should be included in tactical (annual) planning documents, and should be based on criteria such as the relative risk impact, the cost, the mean time to value and the availability of resources.</span></span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>Roles and Responsibilities</b></span></span>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">This section describes who is responsible for delivering and who is responsible for approving each strategic and tactical deliverable that results from this strategic plan. There are four sets of organizational areas that need to be mapped to deliverables and action plans:</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY">• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The security office</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY">• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Lines of business (LOBs) or federation issues (responsibilities that reside with persons or departments </span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">that are affiliated with, but not reporting to, the central information security function)</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY">• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The IT organization</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY">• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Other business areas (typically, the functions that go on in headquarters, such as legal, HR and finance)</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The security office''s responsibilities should be easily extracted from the security charter. The authority, rights and obligations of LOB management and the IT organization should have been negotiated via the governance structure prior to, or as part of, the creation of this strategic plan. These authorities, rights and obligations are typically governed via some kind of information security steering committee. Other business areas may be surprised by their inclusion or may have expressed a need for involvement on their own, typically as a response to regulatory compliance needs.</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">One approach to documenting these roles and responsibilities that has been widely accepted by organization is the use of a responsible, accountable, consulted and informed (RACI) matrix. Once all these steps have been outlined, the executive summary can be written.</span></span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;', 'Security Strategy', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '398-revision-v1', '', '', '2013-08-28 13:23:02', '2013-08-28 13:23:02', '', 398, 'http://localhost/wordpress/?p=399', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(400, 1, '2013-08-28 13:23:41', '2013-08-28 13:23:41', ' ', '', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', '400', '', '', '2013-08-29 08:28:14', '2013-08-29 08:28:14', '', 0, 'http://localhost/wordpress/?p=400', 1, 'nav_menu_item', '', 0);
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` (`ID`, `post_author`, `post_date`, `post_date_gmt`, `post_content`, `post_title`, `post_excerpt`, `post_status`, `comment_status`, `ping_status`, `post_password`, `post_name`, `to_ping`, `pinged`, `post_modified`, `post_modified_gmt`, `post_content_filtered`, `post_parent`, `guid`, `menu_order`, `post_type`, `post_mime_type`, `comment_count`) VALUES
(402, 1, '2013-08-28 13:29:03', '2013-08-28 13:29:03', '<style type="text/css"><!--\r\n@page { margin: 0.79in } 		P { margin-bottom: 0.08in }\r\n--></style>\r\n<h2 style="text-align: center;"><strong>2009-2011 Information Security Strategy for securitysense</strong></h2>\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>Download PDF File</strong></p>\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>How to develop a IT/Information security strategy for your company?</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;">An information security strategic plan should include, at a minimum, an assessment of the current state of the program, a defined target state that is achievable within the three-year strategic planning window, a gap analysis and a road map for closing the gaps.</span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><b>Key Findings</b></span>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY">• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">A consistent framework can be defined that supports risk mitigation control objectives, architecture and </span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">process objectives, but the framework varies in scale and by the maturity level of the organization it''s </span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">being applied to.</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY">• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Small or immature organizations should focus on very simple frameworks.</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY">• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Consistent, incremental improvements are much more likely to succeed than rapidly forced changes.</span></span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><b>Recommendations</b></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Develop and document an information security strategic plan and use it to generate annual tactical </span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">plans that, when executed, move the overall maturity of the security program upward.</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Develop a process to review and refine the strategic plan annually.</span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><b>ANALYSIS</b></span>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Many organizations and security officers are approaching the creation of a strategic plan for information security for the first time, or have expressed a desire to use previously unimplemented best practices in creating the next iteration of one. Although there is no industry standard for the contents of such a plan, Securitysense has recommended organizations by using a model that has proved to be an effective communication tool with the numerous interested parties (including senior management), as well as a reasonable tracking mechanism for multiyear progress reports. While the model can be applied by organizations of any size and in any industry, the details vary based on the scale of the organization and the starting maturity level of the various effected organizational units.</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The information security strategic plan should not be viewed as a stand-alone document. It should exist as one part of a set of planning documents that start with a charter and a vision statement, but that also extends beyond the strategic plan into tactical and communications plans. Each of these has a role in providing context and action ability for the strategic plan. Organizations that have an established enterprise architecture (EA) function should leverage the existing EA disciplines, processes and standards to ensure that the strategic plan for information security is aligned with the EA strategy (see "Architecting Security: Different Approaches"). Securitysense generally considers three years to be an appropriate window for strategic planning for information security. The charter and vision statements deal with longer-term directions, while the tactical and communications plans specify single-year operational considerations and projects.</span></span></p>\r\n<span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The basic layout of the strategic plan is:</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Introduction and executive summary</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Strategic plan framework description</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Current state</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Desired state</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Gap analysis</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Prioritization plan</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Roles and responsibilities</span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>Introduction and Executive Summary</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The introduction should be written first, setting the purpose and scope of the document. The executive summary should be written last, showing only the final points of the document. The combination of executive summary and introduction should not exceed three pages, and, for most organizations, should be no more than two pages.</span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>Strategic Plan Framework Description</b></span></span>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The framework is the method by which the current state, desired state and gap analysis will be documented. An appropriate framework is one that can show overview (summarized) and detail (planning) information. The summary information should be expressed graphically. Frameworks should encompass controls, architecture and process elements to be complete.</span></span></p>\r\n<span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">For organizations with an established EA practice, an enterprise information security architecture (EISA) framework (see "The Structure and Content of an Information Security Architecture Framework") that aligns with the EA framework can act as an effective overall strategic security planning framework. Frameworks for this purpose can be derived from industry standards, from Securitysense research or from a combination of the two. </span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Some sources for framework structure and contents are:</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Controls</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">International Organization for Standardization (ISO)/International Electro technical</span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Commission (IEC) 27002</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Control Objectives for Information and Related Technology (COBIT)</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">U.S. National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) SP800-53</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Architecture</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">ISO10181</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">ISO13335</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Processes</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">ISO/IEC 27001</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Information Technology Infrastructure Library (ITIL)</span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">In addition, Securitysense research can provide significant examples and guidelines for constructing such a framework (see the Recommended Reading section below). Large, mature organizations will require more-complex, detailed frameworks that focus largely on processes. Smaller or less mature organizations will find that simple frameworks suffice, and that all details can be left to the tactical planning stage, but that balanced (perhaps, not equal) attention to the three areas of controls, architecture and processes is required. An example of a simple framework for a low maturity organization might be a three-by-four grid showing the state of controls, technical architecture and processes for data, infrastructure, applications and people/behavior. Each cell in the grid can be assessed or targeted (depending on whether it is the current state or desired state framework copy) on a typical numeric maturity scale of 0 through 5, or assigned a color code of red, yellow or green (see Figure 1).</span></span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nFig 1\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Larger or more-mature organizations will tend to focus more on process assessments, because controls and architecture tend to be well-defined, and the processes by which they are kept up to date will be defined and will be the primary lever for further maturation. </span></span><span style="color: #ff0000;"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Securitysense''s "Toolkit: Risk Program Maturity Assessment 1.0" provides a full process-oriented framework that includes graphical reporting of information security, privacy, regulatory compliance and business continuity</span></span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="color: #ff0000;"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">programs (see Figure 2).</span></span></span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Figure 2. Strategic Plan Contents: Current State</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Controls Architecture Process</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Data</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Infrastructure</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Applications</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>People</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPSMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">N/A</span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: xx-small;"><b>Source: Securitysense (September 2008)</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>Current State</b></span></span>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Use the framework described in the previous section to document the current state of each element contained within the framework. A brief text section describes each entry and justifies the assessment. Organizations with mature risk assessment processes may reference the current risk register to provide an assessment of existing controls.</span></span></p>\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>Desired State</b></span></span>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Document the desired state for each element within the framework. Three years is not a long time to achieve any sort of cultural change, nor for a significant reduction in the overall level of risk. Using a maturity scale from zero through five, with steps of one-half for each of the framework elements, allows sufficient granularity to show, at a strategic level, what degree of progress is being attempted. Brief text descriptions contain the background for each target value. Securitysense recommends that a change in maturity level of no more than a "2" be attempted for any framework element in a three-year period, unless exceptional resources and executive support can be assured (see Figure 3 for an example based on Figure 1).</span></span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Figure 3. Strategic Plan Contents: Target State</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Controls Architecture Process</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Data</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Infrastructure</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Applications</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>People</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPSMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">N/A</span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The desired state may also identify controls and technology areas that require change, retirement or replacement, if those have already been identified.</span></span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>Gap Analysis</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">This section describes those elements of the framework that demonstrate variation between current and desired states (see Figure 4).</span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Figure 4. Strategic Plan Contents: Gap Analysis</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Controls Architecture Process</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPSMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">+2 +1 +1</span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPSMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">+2</span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPSMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">+2 +1 +1</span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Data</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Infrastructure</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Applications</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>People</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPSMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">N/A +1</span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>Prioritization Plan</b></span></span>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">There may be a natural order to resolving many of the issues identified via the gap analysis. Part of the three-year strategic plan should be guidance to tactical planners on how to prioritize the closure of those gaps, such that any natural order is optimized. Controls determine what should be achieved, but controls become meaningful only if the governance structure is functional. The IT organization needs direction via technical architecture to be efficient, but architecture requires guidance from controls. Operational processes related to technologies that are already in place depend, to some degree, on controls (what processes and technologies are needed) and architecture (which process elements and technologies are automated). As a result, a normal prioritization plan might be to start with governance, move to controls, then architecture and finally process. But this is a "greenfield" approach, and it may not be appropriate for organizations with variable levels of maturity in the current information security program or IT organizations in general. For example, a lack of maturity in strategic processes, such as risk assessment and security communications, which are not technology-dependent may demand earlier prioritization.</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Therefore, the method by which priorities will be assigned in the tactical plans requires some</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">strategic guidance. More-granular prioritization of work should be included in tactical (annual) planning documents, and should be based on criteria such as the relative risk impact, the cost, the mean time to value and the availability of resources.</span></span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>Roles and Responsibilities</b></span></span>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">This section describes who is responsible for delivering and who is responsible for approving each strategic and tactical deliverable that results from this strategic plan. There are four sets of organizational areas that need to be mapped to deliverables and action plans:</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY">• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The security office</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY">• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Lines of business (LOBs) or federation issues (responsibilities that reside with persons or departments </span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">that are affiliated with, but not reporting to, the central information security function)</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY">• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The IT organization</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY">• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Other business areas (typically, the functions that go on in headquarters, such as legal, HR and finance)</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The security office''s responsibilities should be easily extracted from the security charter. The authority, rights and obligations of LOB management and the IT organization should have been negotiated via the governance structure prior to, or as part of, the creation of this strategic plan. These authorities, rights and obligations are typically governed via some kind of information security steering committee. Other business areas may be surprised by their inclusion or may have expressed a need for involvement on their own, typically as a response to regulatory compliance needs.</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">One approach to documenting these roles and responsibilities that has been widely accepted by organization is the use of a responsible, accountable, consulted and informed (RACI) matrix. Once all these steps have been outlined, the executive summary can be written.</span></span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;', 'Security Strategy', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '398-revision-v1', '', '', '2013-08-28 13:29:03', '2013-08-28 13:29:03', '', 398, 'http://localhost/wordpress/?p=402', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(403, 1, '2013-08-28 13:37:43', '2013-08-28 13:37:43', '', '2009-2011 Information Security Strategy for securitysense', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '2009-2011-information-security-strategy-for-securitysense', '', '', '2013-08-28 13:37:43', '2013-08-28 13:37:43', '', 0, 'http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2009-2011-Information-Security-Strategy-for-securitysense.pdf', 0, 'attachment', 'application/pdf', 0),
(405, 1, '2013-08-28 13:40:48', '2013-08-28 13:40:48', '<style type="text/css"><!--\r\n@page { margin: 0.79in } 		P { margin-bottom: 0.08in }\r\n--></style>\r\n<h3 style="text-align: center;"><strong>2009-2011 Information Security Strategy for securitysense</strong></h3>\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><a href="http://localhost/wordpress/?attachment_id=403" target="_blank"><strong>Download PDF File</strong></a></p>\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>How to develop a IT/Information security strategy for your company?</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;">An information security strategic plan should include, at a minimum, an assessment of the current state of the program, a defined target state that is achievable within the three-year strategic planning window, a gap analysis and a road map for closing the gaps.</span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><b>Key Findings</b></span>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY">• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">A consistent framework can be defined that supports risk mitigation control objectives, architecture and </span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">process objectives, but the framework varies in scale and by the maturity level of the organization it''s </span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">being applied to.</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY">• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Small or immature organizations should focus on very simple frameworks.</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY">• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Consistent, incremental improvements are much more likely to succeed than rapidly forced changes.</span></span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><b>Recommendations</b></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Develop and document an information security strategic plan and use it to generate annual tactical </span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">plans that, when executed, move the overall maturity of the security program upward.</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Develop a process to review and refine the strategic plan annually.</span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><b>ANALYSIS</b></span>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Many organizations and security officers are approaching the creation of a strategic plan for information security for the first time, or have expressed a desire to use previously unimplemented best practices in creating the next iteration of one. Although there is no industry standard for the contents of such a plan, Securitysense has recommended organizations by using a model that has proved to be an effective communication tool with the numerous interested parties (including senior management), as well as a reasonable tracking mechanism for multiyear progress reports. While the model can be applied by organizations of any size and in any industry, the details vary based on the scale of the organization and the starting maturity level of the various effected organizational units.</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The information security strategic plan should not be viewed as a stand-alone document. It should exist as one part of a set of planning documents that start with a charter and a vision statement, but that also extends beyond the strategic plan into tactical and communications plans. Each of these has a role in providing context and action ability for the strategic plan. Organizations that have an established enterprise architecture (EA) function should leverage the existing EA disciplines, processes and standards to ensure that the strategic plan for information security is aligned with the EA strategy (see "Architecting Security: Different Approaches"). Securitysense generally considers three years to be an appropriate window for strategic planning for information security. The charter and vision statements deal with longer-term directions, while the tactical and communications plans specify single-year operational considerations and projects.</span></span></p>\r\n<span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The basic layout of the strategic plan is:</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Introduction and executive summary</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Strategic plan framework description</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Current state</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Desired state</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Gap analysis</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Prioritization plan</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Roles and responsibilities</span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>Introduction and Executive Summary</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The introduction should be written first, setting the purpose and scope of the document. The executive summary should be written last, showing only the final points of the document. The combination of executive summary and introduction should not exceed three pages, and, for most organizations, should be no more than two pages.</span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>Strategic Plan Framework Description</b></span></span>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The framework is the method by which the current state, desired state and gap analysis will be documented. An appropriate framework is one that can show overview (summarized) and detail (planning) information. The summary information should be expressed graphically. Frameworks should encompass controls, architecture and process elements to be complete.</span></span></p>\r\n<span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">For organizations with an established EA practice, an enterprise information security architecture (EISA) framework (see "The Structure and Content of an Information Security Architecture Framework") that aligns with the EA framework can act as an effective overall strategic security planning framework. Frameworks for this purpose can be derived from industry standards, from Securitysense research or from a combination of the two. </span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Some sources for framework structure and contents are:</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Controls</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">International Organization for Standardization (ISO)/International Electro technical</span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Commission (IEC) 27002</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Control Objectives for Information and Related Technology (COBIT)</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">U.S. National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) SP800-53</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Architecture</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">ISO10181</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">ISO13335</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Processes</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">ISO/IEC 27001</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Information Technology Infrastructure Library (ITIL)</span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">In addition, Securitysense research can provide significant examples and guidelines for constructing such a framework (see the Recommended Reading section below). Large, mature organizations will require more-complex, detailed frameworks that focus largely on processes. Smaller or less mature organizations will find that simple frameworks suffice, and that all details can be left to the tactical planning stage, but that balanced (perhaps, not equal) attention to the three areas of controls, architecture and processes is required. An example of a simple framework for a low maturity organization might be a three-by-four grid showing the state of controls, technical architecture and processes for data, infrastructure, applications and people/behavior. Each cell in the grid can be assessed or targeted (depending on whether it is the current state or desired state framework copy) on a typical numeric maturity scale of 0 through 5, or assigned a color code of red, yellow or green (see Figure 1).</span></span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nFig 1\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Larger or more-mature organizations will tend to focus more on process assessments, because controls and architecture tend to be well-defined, and the processes by which they are kept up to date will be defined and will be the primary lever for further maturation. </span></span><span style="color: #ff0000;"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Securitysense''s "Toolkit: Risk Program Maturity Assessment 1.0" provides a full process-oriented framework that includes graphical reporting of information security, privacy, regulatory compliance and business continuity</span></span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="color: #ff0000;"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">programs (see Figure 2).</span></span></span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Figure 2. Strategic Plan Contents: Current State</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Controls Architecture Process</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Data</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Infrastructure</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Applications</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>People</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPSMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">N/A</span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: xx-small;"><b>Source: Securitysense (September 2008)</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>Current State</b></span></span>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Use the framework described in the previous section to document the current state of each element contained within the framework. A brief text section describes each entry and justifies the assessment. Organizations with mature risk assessment processes may reference the current risk register to provide an assessment of existing controls.</span></span></p>\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>Desired State</b></span></span>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Document the desired state for each element within the framework. Three years is not a long time to achieve any sort of cultural change, nor for a significant reduction in the overall level of risk. Using a maturity scale from zero through five, with steps of one-half for each of the framework elements, allows sufficient granularity to show, at a strategic level, what degree of progress is being attempted. Brief text descriptions contain the background for each target value. Securitysense recommends that a change in maturity level of no more than a "2" be attempted for any framework element in a three-year period, unless exceptional resources and executive support can be assured (see Figure 3 for an example based on Figure 1).</span></span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Figure 3. Strategic Plan Contents: Target State</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Controls Architecture Process</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Data</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Infrastructure</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Applications</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>People</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPSMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">N/A</span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The desired state may also identify controls and technology areas that require change, retirement or replacement, if those have already been identified.</span></span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>Gap Analysis</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">This section describes those elements of the framework that demonstrate variation between current and desired states (see Figure 4).</span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Figure 4. Strategic Plan Contents: Gap Analysis</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Controls Architecture Process</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPSMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">+2 +1 +1</span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPSMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">+2</span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPSMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">+2 +1 +1</span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Data</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Infrastructure</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Applications</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>People</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPSMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">N/A +1</span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>Prioritization Plan</b></span></span>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">There may be a natural order to resolving many of the issues identified via the gap analysis. Part of the three-year strategic plan should be guidance to tactical planners on how to prioritize the closure of those gaps, such that any natural order is optimized. Controls determine what should be achieved, but controls become meaningful only if the governance structure is functional. The IT organization needs direction via technical architecture to be efficient, but architecture requires guidance from controls. Operational processes related to technologies that are already in place depend, to some degree, on controls (what processes and technologies are needed) and architecture (which process elements and technologies are automated). As a result, a normal prioritization plan might be to start with governance, move to controls, then architecture and finally process. But this is a "greenfield" approach, and it may not be appropriate for organizations with variable levels of maturity in the current information security program or IT organizations in general. For example, a lack of maturity in strategic processes, such as risk assessment and security communications, which are not technology-dependent may demand earlier prioritization.</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Therefore, the method by which priorities will be assigned in the tactical plans requires some</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">strategic guidance. More-granular prioritization of work should be included in tactical (annual) planning documents, and should be based on criteria such as the relative risk impact, the cost, the mean time to value and the availability of resources.</span></span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>Roles and Responsibilities</b></span></span>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">This section describes who is responsible for delivering and who is responsible for approving each strategic and tactical deliverable that results from this strategic plan. There are four sets of organizational areas that need to be mapped to deliverables and action plans:</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY">• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The security office</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY">• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Lines of business (LOBs) or federation issues (responsibilities that reside with persons or departments </span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">that are affiliated with, but not reporting to, the central information security function)</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY">• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The IT organization</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY">• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Other business areas (typically, the functions that go on in headquarters, such as legal, HR and finance)</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The security office''s responsibilities should be easily extracted from the security charter. The authority, rights and obligations of LOB management and the IT organization should have been negotiated via the governance structure prior to, or as part of, the creation of this strategic plan. These authorities, rights and obligations are typically governed via some kind of information security steering committee. Other business areas may be surprised by their inclusion or may have expressed a need for involvement on their own, typically as a response to regulatory compliance needs.</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">One approach to documenting these roles and responsibilities that has been widely accepted by organization is the use of a responsible, accountable, consulted and informed (RACI) matrix. Once all these steps have been outlined, the executive summary can be written.</span></span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;', 'Security Strategy', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '398-revision-v1', '', '', '2013-08-28 13:40:48', '2013-08-28 13:40:48', '', 398, 'http://localhost/wordpress/?p=405', 0, 'revision', '', 0);
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` (`ID`, `post_author`, `post_date`, `post_date_gmt`, `post_content`, `post_title`, `post_excerpt`, `post_status`, `comment_status`, `ping_status`, `post_password`, `post_name`, `to_ping`, `pinged`, `post_modified`, `post_modified_gmt`, `post_content_filtered`, `post_parent`, `guid`, `menu_order`, `post_type`, `post_mime_type`, `comment_count`) VALUES
(404, 1, '2013-08-28 13:39:30', '2013-08-28 13:39:30', '<style type="text/css"><!--\r\n@page { margin: 0.79in } 		P { margin-bottom: 0.08in }\r\n--></style>\r\n<h3 style="text-align: center;"><strong>2009-2011 Information Security Strategy for securitysense</strong></h3>\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><a title="2009-2011 Information Security Strategy for securitysense" href="http://localhost/wordpress/?attachment_id=403" target="_blank"><strong>Download PDF File</strong></a></p>\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>How to develop a IT/Information security strategy for your company?</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;">An information security strategic plan should include, at a minimum, an assessment of the current state of the program, a defined target state that is achievable within the three-year strategic planning window, a gap analysis and a road map for closing the gaps.</span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><b>Key Findings</b></span>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY">• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">A consistent framework can be defined that supports risk mitigation control objectives, architecture and </span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">process objectives, but the framework varies in scale and by the maturity level of the organization it''s </span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">being applied to.</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY">• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Small or immature organizations should focus on very simple frameworks.</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY">• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Consistent, incremental improvements are much more likely to succeed than rapidly forced changes.</span></span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><b>Recommendations</b></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Develop and document an information security strategic plan and use it to generate annual tactical </span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">plans that, when executed, move the overall maturity of the security program upward.</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Develop a process to review and refine the strategic plan annually.</span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><b>ANALYSIS</b></span>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Many organizations and security officers are approaching the creation of a strategic plan for information security for the first time, or have expressed a desire to use previously unimplemented best practices in creating the next iteration of one. Although there is no industry standard for the contents of such a plan, Securitysense has recommended organizations by using a model that has proved to be an effective communication tool with the numerous interested parties (including senior management), as well as a reasonable tracking mechanism for multiyear progress reports. While the model can be applied by organizations of any size and in any industry, the details vary based on the scale of the organization and the starting maturity level of the various effected organizational units.</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The information security strategic plan should not be viewed as a stand-alone document. It should exist as one part of a set of planning documents that start with a charter and a vision statement, but that also extends beyond the strategic plan into tactical and communications plans. Each of these has a role in providing context and action ability for the strategic plan. Organizations that have an established enterprise architecture (EA) function should leverage the existing EA disciplines, processes and standards to ensure that the strategic plan for information security is aligned with the EA strategy (see "Architecting Security: Different Approaches"). Securitysense generally considers three years to be an appropriate window for strategic planning for information security. The charter and vision statements deal with longer-term directions, while the tactical and communications plans specify single-year operational considerations and projects.</span></span></p>\r\n<span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The basic layout of the strategic plan is:</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Introduction and executive summary</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Strategic plan framework description</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Current state</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Desired state</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Gap analysis</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Prioritization plan</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Roles and responsibilities</span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>Introduction and Executive Summary</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The introduction should be written first, setting the purpose and scope of the document. The executive summary should be written last, showing only the final points of the document. The combination of executive summary and introduction should not exceed three pages, and, for most organizations, should be no more than two pages.</span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>Strategic Plan Framework Description</b></span></span>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The framework is the method by which the current state, desired state and gap analysis will be documented. An appropriate framework is one that can show overview (summarized) and detail (planning) information. The summary information should be expressed graphically. Frameworks should encompass controls, architecture and process elements to be complete.</span></span></p>\r\n<span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">For organizations with an established EA practice, an enterprise information security architecture (EISA) framework (see "The Structure and Content of an Information Security Architecture Framework") that aligns with the EA framework can act as an effective overall strategic security planning framework. Frameworks for this purpose can be derived from industry standards, from Securitysense research or from a combination of the two. </span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Some sources for framework structure and contents are:</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Controls</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">International Organization for Standardization (ISO)/International Electro technical</span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Commission (IEC) 27002</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Control Objectives for Information and Related Technology (COBIT)</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">U.S. National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) SP800-53</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Architecture</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">ISO10181</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">ISO13335</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Processes</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">ISO/IEC 27001</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Information Technology Infrastructure Library (ITIL)</span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">In addition, Securitysense research can provide significant examples and guidelines for constructing such a framework (see the Recommended Reading section below). Large, mature organizations will require more-complex, detailed frameworks that focus largely on processes. Smaller or less mature organizations will find that simple frameworks suffice, and that all details can be left to the tactical planning stage, but that balanced (perhaps, not equal) attention to the three areas of controls, architecture and processes is required. An example of a simple framework for a low maturity organization might be a three-by-four grid showing the state of controls, technical architecture and processes for data, infrastructure, applications and people/behavior. Each cell in the grid can be assessed or targeted (depending on whether it is the current state or desired state framework copy) on a typical numeric maturity scale of 0 through 5, or assigned a color code of red, yellow or green (see Figure 1).</span></span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nFig 1\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Larger or more-mature organizations will tend to focus more on process assessments, because controls and architecture tend to be well-defined, and the processes by which they are kept up to date will be defined and will be the primary lever for further maturation. </span></span><span style="color: #ff0000;"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Securitysense''s "Toolkit: Risk Program Maturity Assessment 1.0" provides a full process-oriented framework that includes graphical reporting of information security, privacy, regulatory compliance and business continuity</span></span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="color: #ff0000;"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">programs (see Figure 2).</span></span></span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Figure 2. Strategic Plan Contents: Current State</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Controls Architecture Process</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Data</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Infrastructure</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Applications</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>People</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPSMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">N/A</span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: xx-small;"><b>Source: Securitysense (September 2008)</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>Current State</b></span></span>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Use the framework described in the previous section to document the current state of each element contained within the framework. A brief text section describes each entry and justifies the assessment. Organizations with mature risk assessment processes may reference the current risk register to provide an assessment of existing controls.</span></span></p>\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>Desired State</b></span></span>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Document the desired state for each element within the framework. Three years is not a long time to achieve any sort of cultural change, nor for a significant reduction in the overall level of risk. Using a maturity scale from zero through five, with steps of one-half for each of the framework elements, allows sufficient granularity to show, at a strategic level, what degree of progress is being attempted. Brief text descriptions contain the background for each target value. Securitysense recommends that a change in maturity level of no more than a "2" be attempted for any framework element in a three-year period, unless exceptional resources and executive support can be assured (see Figure 3 for an example based on Figure 1).</span></span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Figure 3. Strategic Plan Contents: Target State</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Controls Architecture Process</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Data</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Infrastructure</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Applications</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>People</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPSMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">N/A</span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The desired state may also identify controls and technology areas that require change, retirement or replacement, if those have already been identified.</span></span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>Gap Analysis</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">This section describes those elements of the framework that demonstrate variation between current and desired states (see Figure 4).</span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Figure 4. Strategic Plan Contents: Gap Analysis</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Controls Architecture Process</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPSMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">+2 +1 +1</span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPSMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">+2</span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPSMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">+2 +1 +1</span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Data</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Infrastructure</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Applications</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>People</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPSMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">N/A +1</span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>Prioritization Plan</b></span></span>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">There may be a natural order to resolving many of the issues identified via the gap analysis. Part of the three-year strategic plan should be guidance to tactical planners on how to prioritize the closure of those gaps, such that any natural order is optimized. Controls determine what should be achieved, but controls become meaningful only if the governance structure is functional. The IT organization needs direction via technical architecture to be efficient, but architecture requires guidance from controls. Operational processes related to technologies that are already in place depend, to some degree, on controls (what processes and technologies are needed) and architecture (which process elements and technologies are automated). As a result, a normal prioritization plan might be to start with governance, move to controls, then architecture and finally process. But this is a "greenfield" approach, and it may not be appropriate for organizations with variable levels of maturity in the current information security program or IT organizations in general. For example, a lack of maturity in strategic processes, such as risk assessment and security communications, which are not technology-dependent may demand earlier prioritization.</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Therefore, the method by which priorities will be assigned in the tactical plans requires some</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">strategic guidance. More-granular prioritization of work should be included in tactical (annual) planning documents, and should be based on criteria such as the relative risk impact, the cost, the mean time to value and the availability of resources.</span></span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>Roles and Responsibilities</b></span></span>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">This section describes who is responsible for delivering and who is responsible for approving each strategic and tactical deliverable that results from this strategic plan. There are four sets of organizational areas that need to be mapped to deliverables and action plans:</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY">• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The security office</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY">• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Lines of business (LOBs) or federation issues (responsibilities that reside with persons or departments </span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">that are affiliated with, but not reporting to, the central information security function)</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY">• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The IT organization</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY">• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Other business areas (typically, the functions that go on in headquarters, such as legal, HR and finance)</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The security office''s responsibilities should be easily extracted from the security charter. The authority, rights and obligations of LOB management and the IT organization should have been negotiated via the governance structure prior to, or as part of, the creation of this strategic plan. These authorities, rights and obligations are typically governed via some kind of information security steering committee. Other business areas may be surprised by their inclusion or may have expressed a need for involvement on their own, typically as a response to regulatory compliance needs.</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">One approach to documenting these roles and responsibilities that has been widely accepted by organization is the use of a responsible, accountable, consulted and informed (RACI) matrix. Once all these steps have been outlined, the executive summary can be written.</span></span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;', 'Security Strategy', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '398-revision-v1', '', '', '2013-08-28 13:39:30', '2013-08-28 13:39:30', '', 398, 'http://localhost/wordpress/?p=404', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(406, 1, '2013-08-28 13:41:30', '2013-08-28 13:41:30', '<style type="text/css"><!--\r\n@page { margin: 0.79in } 		P { margin-bottom: 0.08in }\r\n--></style>\r\n<h3 style="text-align: center;"><strong>2009-2011 Information Security Strategy for securitysense</strong></h3>\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><a href="http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2009-2011-Information-Security-Strategy-for-securitysense.pdf"><strong>Download PDF File</strong></a></p>\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>How to develop a IT/Information security strategy for your company?</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;">An information security strategic plan should include, at a minimum, an assessment of the current state of the program, a defined target state that is achievable within the three-year strategic planning window, a gap analysis and a road map for closing the gaps.</span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><b>Key Findings</b></span>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY">• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">A consistent framework can be defined that supports risk mitigation control objectives, architecture and </span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">process objectives, but the framework varies in scale and by the maturity level of the organization it''s </span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">being applied to.</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY">• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Small or immature organizations should focus on very simple frameworks.</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY">• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Consistent, incremental improvements are much more likely to succeed than rapidly forced changes.</span></span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><b>Recommendations</b></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Develop and document an information security strategic plan and use it to generate annual tactical </span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">plans that, when executed, move the overall maturity of the security program upward.</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Develop a process to review and refine the strategic plan annually.</span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><b>ANALYSIS</b></span>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Many organizations and security officers are approaching the creation of a strategic plan for information security for the first time, or have expressed a desire to use previously unimplemented best practices in creating the next iteration of one. Although there is no industry standard for the contents of such a plan, Securitysense has recommended organizations by using a model that has proved to be an effective communication tool with the numerous interested parties (including senior management), as well as a reasonable tracking mechanism for multiyear progress reports. While the model can be applied by organizations of any size and in any industry, the details vary based on the scale of the organization and the starting maturity level of the various effected organizational units.</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The information security strategic plan should not be viewed as a stand-alone document. It should exist as one part of a set of planning documents that start with a charter and a vision statement, but that also extends beyond the strategic plan into tactical and communications plans. Each of these has a role in providing context and action ability for the strategic plan. Organizations that have an established enterprise architecture (EA) function should leverage the existing EA disciplines, processes and standards to ensure that the strategic plan for information security is aligned with the EA strategy (see "Architecting Security: Different Approaches"). Securitysense generally considers three years to be an appropriate window for strategic planning for information security. The charter and vision statements deal with longer-term directions, while the tactical and communications plans specify single-year operational considerations and projects.</span></span></p>\r\n<span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The basic layout of the strategic plan is:</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Introduction and executive summary</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Strategic plan framework description</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Current state</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Desired state</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Gap analysis</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Prioritization plan</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Roles and responsibilities</span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>Introduction and Executive Summary</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The introduction should be written first, setting the purpose and scope of the document. The executive summary should be written last, showing only the final points of the document. The combination of executive summary and introduction should not exceed three pages, and, for most organizations, should be no more than two pages.</span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>Strategic Plan Framework Description</b></span></span>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The framework is the method by which the current state, desired state and gap analysis will be documented. An appropriate framework is one that can show overview (summarized) and detail (planning) information. The summary information should be expressed graphically. Frameworks should encompass controls, architecture and process elements to be complete.</span></span></p>\r\n<span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">For organizations with an established EA practice, an enterprise information security architecture (EISA) framework (see "The Structure and Content of an Information Security Architecture Framework") that aligns with the EA framework can act as an effective overall strategic security planning framework. Frameworks for this purpose can be derived from industry standards, from Securitysense research or from a combination of the two. </span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Some sources for framework structure and contents are:</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Controls</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">International Organization for Standardization (ISO)/International Electro technical</span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Commission (IEC) 27002</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Control Objectives for Information and Related Technology (COBIT)</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">U.S. National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) SP800-53</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Architecture</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">ISO10181</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">ISO13335</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Processes</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">ISO/IEC 27001</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Information Technology Infrastructure Library (ITIL)</span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">In addition, Securitysense research can provide significant examples and guidelines for constructing such a framework (see the Recommended Reading section below). Large, mature organizations will require more-complex, detailed frameworks that focus largely on processes. Smaller or less mature organizations will find that simple frameworks suffice, and that all details can be left to the tactical planning stage, but that balanced (perhaps, not equal) attention to the three areas of controls, architecture and processes is required. An example of a simple framework for a low maturity organization might be a three-by-four grid showing the state of controls, technical architecture and processes for data, infrastructure, applications and people/behavior. Each cell in the grid can be assessed or targeted (depending on whether it is the current state or desired state framework copy) on a typical numeric maturity scale of 0 through 5, or assigned a color code of red, yellow or green (see Figure 1).</span></span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nFig 1\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Larger or more-mature organizations will tend to focus more on process assessments, because controls and architecture tend to be well-defined, and the processes by which they are kept up to date will be defined and will be the primary lever for further maturation. </span></span><span style="color: #ff0000;"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Securitysense''s "Toolkit: Risk Program Maturity Assessment 1.0" provides a full process-oriented framework that includes graphical reporting of information security, privacy, regulatory compliance and business continuity</span></span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="color: #ff0000;"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">programs (see Figure 2).</span></span></span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Figure 2. Strategic Plan Contents: Current State</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Controls Architecture Process</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Data</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Infrastructure</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Applications</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>People</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPSMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">N/A</span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: xx-small;"><b>Source: Securitysense (September 2008)</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>Current State</b></span></span>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Use the framework described in the previous section to document the current state of each element contained within the framework. A brief text section describes each entry and justifies the assessment. Organizations with mature risk assessment processes may reference the current risk register to provide an assessment of existing controls.</span></span></p>\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>Desired State</b></span></span>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Document the desired state for each element within the framework. Three years is not a long time to achieve any sort of cultural change, nor for a significant reduction in the overall level of risk. Using a maturity scale from zero through five, with steps of one-half for each of the framework elements, allows sufficient granularity to show, at a strategic level, what degree of progress is being attempted. Brief text descriptions contain the background for each target value. Securitysense recommends that a change in maturity level of no more than a "2" be attempted for any framework element in a three-year period, unless exceptional resources and executive support can be assured (see Figure 3 for an example based on Figure 1).</span></span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Figure 3. Strategic Plan Contents: Target State</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Controls Architecture Process</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Data</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Infrastructure</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Applications</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>People</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPSMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">N/A</span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The desired state may also identify controls and technology areas that require change, retirement or replacement, if those have already been identified.</span></span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>Gap Analysis</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">This section describes those elements of the framework that demonstrate variation between current and desired states (see Figure 4).</span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Figure 4. Strategic Plan Contents: Gap Analysis</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Controls Architecture Process</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPSMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">+2 +1 +1</span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPSMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">+2</span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPSMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">+2 +1 +1</span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Data</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Infrastructure</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Applications</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>People</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPSMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">N/A +1</span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>Prioritization Plan</b></span></span>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">There may be a natural order to resolving many of the issues identified via the gap analysis. Part of the three-year strategic plan should be guidance to tactical planners on how to prioritize the closure of those gaps, such that any natural order is optimized. Controls determine what should be achieved, but controls become meaningful only if the governance structure is functional. The IT organization needs direction via technical architecture to be efficient, but architecture requires guidance from controls. Operational processes related to technologies that are already in place depend, to some degree, on controls (what processes and technologies are needed) and architecture (which process elements and technologies are automated). As a result, a normal prioritization plan might be to start with governance, move to controls, then architecture and finally process. But this is a "greenfield" approach, and it may not be appropriate for organizations with variable levels of maturity in the current information security program or IT organizations in general. For example, a lack of maturity in strategic processes, such as risk assessment and security communications, which are not technology-dependent may demand earlier prioritization.</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Therefore, the method by which priorities will be assigned in the tactical plans requires some</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">strategic guidance. More-granular prioritization of work should be included in tactical (annual) planning documents, and should be based on criteria such as the relative risk impact, the cost, the mean time to value and the availability of resources.</span></span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>Roles and Responsibilities</b></span></span>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">This section describes who is responsible for delivering and who is responsible for approving each strategic and tactical deliverable that results from this strategic plan. There are four sets of organizational areas that need to be mapped to deliverables and action plans:</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY">• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The security office</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY">• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Lines of business (LOBs) or federation issues (responsibilities that reside with persons or departments </span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">that are affiliated with, but not reporting to, the central information security function)</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY">• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The IT organization</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY">• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Other business areas (typically, the functions that go on in headquarters, such as legal, HR and finance)</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The security office''s responsibilities should be easily extracted from the security charter. The authority, rights and obligations of LOB management and the IT organization should have been negotiated via the governance structure prior to, or as part of, the creation of this strategic plan. These authorities, rights and obligations are typically governed via some kind of information security steering committee. Other business areas may be surprised by their inclusion or may have expressed a need for involvement on their own, typically as a response to regulatory compliance needs.</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">One approach to documenting these roles and responsibilities that has been widely accepted by organization is the use of a responsible, accountable, consulted and informed (RACI) matrix. Once all these steps have been outlined, the executive summary can be written.</span></span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;', 'Security Strategy', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '398-revision-v1', '', '', '2013-08-28 13:41:30', '2013-08-28 13:41:30', '', 398, 'http://localhost/wordpress/?p=406', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(407, 1, '2013-08-28 13:47:37', '2013-08-28 13:47:37', '<style type="text/css"><!--\r\n@page { margin: 0.79in }\r\n		P { margin-bottom: 0.08in }\r\n--></style><span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: x-large;"><b>What is IT Security Framework?</b></span></span>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;">Security framework is a code of practice and principles that includes process, policy and procedures used here at the company that protect and govern information security. The framework is a method of establishing, implementing, reviewing, maintaining and improving the security programs throughout the enterprise.</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;">An IT Security framework is the foundation for an effective, enterprise wide security program. Many organization has adopted the International Standards Organization'' s (ISO) Information Security Framework documented as ISO 27001 and 27002.This framework outlines many actions and controls needed to ensure the organizations appropriately protects the information assets it owns and creates.</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;">The implementation of IT Security Framework is a multi-year project. Completing the initial work for implementing the various controls required to address information security concerns across an organizations varies as work must be parceled and planned to make the most gains using allocated resources.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<style type="text/css"><!--\r\n@page { margin: 0.79in }\r\n		P { margin-bottom: 0.08in }\r\n--></style>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: x-large;"><b>Purpose of Security framework:</b></span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;">The purpose of this procedure is to achieve and maintain confidentiality, integrity and availability of Information and Information Processing Facilities.</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;">This procedure applies to, but is not limited to, safeguarding of the following assets:</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><span style="font-size: medium;">Physical assets (e.g. Network &amp; Telco equipment computer hardware, communication facilities, information processing facilities).</span></span></span></p>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><span style="font-size: medium;">Information/data (e.g. documents, databases, IT/Telecom- GSM Systems, Software).</span></span></span></p>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><span style="font-size: medium;">Organization/Management.</span></span></span></p>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><span style="font-size: medium;">The ability to provide a product or service.</span></span></span></p>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><span style="font-size: medium;">People (knowledge, experience, skills).</span></span></span></p>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><span style="font-size: medium;">Intangibles (e.g., goodwill, image).</span></span></span></p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>', 'IT Security Framework – what is it ?', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'it-security-framework-what-is-it', '', '', '2013-08-29 03:26:22', '2013-08-29 03:26:22', '', 0, 'http://localhost/wordpress/?page_id=407', 0, 'page', '', 0);
