(443, 1, '2013-08-28 16:33:39', '2013-08-28 16:33:39', '<style type="text/css"><!--\r\n@page { margin: 0.79in } 		P { margin-bottom: 0.08in }\r\n--></style>\r\n<h3 style="text-align: center;"><strong>2009-2011 Information Security Strategy for securitysense</strong></h3>\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><a href="http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2009-2011-Information-Security-Strategy-for-securitysense.pdf"><strong>Download PDF File</strong></a></p>\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>How to develop a IT/Information security strategy for your company?</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;">An information security strategic plan should include, at a minimum, an assessment of the current state of the program, a defined target state that is achievable within the three-year strategic planning window, a gap analysis and a road map for closing the gaps.</span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><b>Key Findings</b></span>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY">• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">A consistent framework can be defined that supports risk mitigation control objectives, architecture and </span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">process objectives, but the framework varies in scale and by the maturity level of the organization it''s </span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">being applied to.</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY">• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Small or immature organizations should focus on very simple frameworks.</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY">• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Consistent, incremental improvements are much more likely to succeed than rapidly forced changes.</span></span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><b>Recommendations</b></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Develop and document an information security strategic plan and use it to generate annual tactical </span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">plans that, when executed, move the overall maturity of the security program upward.</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Develop a process to review and refine the strategic plan annually.</span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><b>ANALYSIS</b></span>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Many organizations and security officers are approaching the creation of a strategic plan for information security for the first time, or have expressed a desire to use previously unimplemented best practices in creating the next iteration of one. Although there is no industry standard for the contents of such a plan, Securitysense has recommended organizations by using a model that has proved to be an effective communication tool with the numerous interested parties (including senior management), as well as a reasonable tracking mechanism for multiyear progress reports. While the model can be applied by organizations of any size and in any industry, the details vary based on the scale of the organization and the starting maturity level of the various effected organizational units.</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The information security strategic plan should not be viewed as a stand-alone document. It should exist as one part of a set of planning documents that start with a charter and a vision statement, but that also extends beyond the strategic plan into tactical and communications plans. Each of these has a role in providing context and action ability for the strategic plan. Organizations that have an established enterprise architecture (EA) function should leverage the existing EA disciplines, processes and standards to ensure that the strategic plan for information security is aligned with the EA strategy (see "Architecting Security: Different Approaches"). Securitysense generally considers three years to be an appropriate window for strategic planning for information security. The charter and vision statements deal with longer-term directions, while the tactical and communications plans specify single-year operational considerations and projects.</span></span></p>\r\n<span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The basic layout of the strategic plan is:</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Introduction and executive summary</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Strategic plan framework description</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Current state</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Desired state</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Gap analysis</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Prioritization plan</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Roles and responsibilities</span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>Introduction and Executive Summary</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The introduction should be written first, setting the purpose and scope of the document. The executive summary should be written last, showing only the final points of the document. The combination of executive summary and introduction should not exceed three pages, and, for most organizations, should be no more than two pages.</span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>Strategic Plan Framework Description</b></span></span>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The framework is the method by which the current state, desired state and gap analysis will be documented. An appropriate framework is one that can show overview (summarized) and detail (planning) information. The summary information should be expressed graphically. Frameworks should encompass controls, architecture and process elements to be complete.</span></span></p>\r\n<span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">For organizations with an established EA practice, an enterprise information security architecture (EISA) framework (see "The Structure and Content of an Information Security Architecture Framework") that aligns with the EA framework can act as an effective overall strategic security planning framework. Frameworks for this purpose can be derived from industry standards, from Securitysense research or from a combination of the two. </span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Some sources for framework structure and contents are:</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Controls</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">International Organization for Standardization (ISO)/International Electro technical</span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Commission (IEC) 27002</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Control Objectives for Information and Related Technology (COBIT)</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">U.S. National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) SP800-53</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Architecture</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">ISO10181</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">ISO13335</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Processes</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">ISO/IEC 27001</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Information Technology Infrastructure Library (ITIL)</span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">In addition, Securitysense research can provide significant examples and guidelines for constructing such a framework (see the Recommended Reading section below). Large, mature organizations will require more-complex, detailed frameworks that focus largely on processes. Smaller or less mature organizations will find that simple frameworks suffice, and that all details can be left to the tactical planning stage, but that balanced (perhaps, not equal) attention to the three areas of controls, architecture and processes is required. An example of a simple framework for a low maturity organization might be a three-by-four grid showing the state of controls, technical architecture and processes for data, infrastructure, applications and people/behavior. Each cell in the grid can be assessed or targeted (depending on whether it is the current state or desired state framework copy) on a typical numeric maturity scale of 0 through 5, or assigned a color code of red, yellow or green (see Figure 1).</span></span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nFig 1\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Larger or more-mature organizations will tend to focus more on process assessments, because controls and architecture tend to be well-defined, and the processes by which they are kept up to date will be defined and will be the primary lever for further maturation. </span></span><span style="color: #ff0000;"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Securitysense''s "Toolkit: Risk Program Maturity Assessment 1.0" provides a full process-oriented framework that includes graphical reporting of information security, privacy, regulatory compliance and business continuity</span></span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="color: #ff0000;"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">programs (see Figure 2).</span></span></span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Figure 2. Strategic Plan Contents: Current State</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Controls Architecture Process</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Data</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Infrastructure</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Applications</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>People</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPSMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">N/A</span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: xx-small;"><b>Source: Securitysense (September 2008)</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>Current State</b></span></span>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Use the framework described in the previous section to document the current state of each element contained within the framework. A brief text section describes each entry and justifies the assessment. Organizations with mature risk assessment processes may reference the current risk register to provide an assessment of existing controls.</span></span></p>\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>Desired State</b></span></span>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Document the desired state for each element within the framework. Three years is not a long time to achieve any sort of cultural change, nor for a significant reduction in the overall level of risk. Using a maturity scale from zero through five, with steps of one-half for each of the framework elements, allows sufficient granularity to show, at a strategic level, what degree of progress is being attempted. Brief text descriptions contain the background for each target value. Securitysense recommends that a change in maturity level of no more than a "2" be attempted for any framework element in a three-year period, unless exceptional resources and executive support can be assured (see Figure 3 for an example based on Figure 1).</span></span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Figure 3. Strategic Plan Contents: Target State</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Controls Architecture Process</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Data</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Infrastructure</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Applications</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>People</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPSMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">N/A</span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The desired state may also identify controls and technology areas that require change, retirement or replacement, if those have already been identified.</span></span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>Gap Analysis</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">This section describes those elements of the framework that demonstrate variation between current and desired states (see Figure 4).</span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Figure 4. Strategic Plan Contents: Gap Analysis</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Controls Architecture Process</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPSMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">+2 +1 +1</span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPSMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">+2</span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPSMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">+2 +1 +1</span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Data</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Infrastructure</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Applications</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>People</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPSMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">N/A +1</span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>Prioritization Plan</b></span></span>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">There may be a natural order to resolving many of the issues identified via the gap analysis. Part of the three-year strategic plan should be guidance to tactical planners on how to prioritize the closure of those gaps, such that any natural order is optimized. Controls determine what should be achieved, but controls become meaningful only if the governance structure is functional. The IT organization needs direction via technical architecture to be efficient, but architecture requires guidance from controls. Operational processes related to technologies that are already in place depend, to some degree, on controls (what processes and technologies are needed) and architecture (which process elements and technologies are automated). As a result, a normal prioritization plan might be to start with governance, move to controls, then architecture and finally process. But this is a "greenfield" approach, and it may not be appropriate for organizations with variable levels of maturity in the current information security program or IT organizations in general. For example, a lack of maturity in strategic processes, such as risk assessment and security communications, which are not technology-dependent may demand earlier prioritization.</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Therefore, the method by which priorities will be assigned in the tactical plans requires some</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">strategic guidance. More-granular prioritization of work should be included in tactical (annual) planning documents, and should be based on criteria such as the relative risk impact, the cost, the mean time to value and the availability of resources.</span></span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>Roles and Responsibilities</b></span></span>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">This section describes who is responsible for delivering and who is responsible for approving each strategic and tactical deliverable that results from this strategic plan. There are four sets of organizational areas that need to be mapped to deliverables and action plans:</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY">• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The security office</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY">• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Lines of business (LOBs) or federation issues (responsibilities that reside with persons or departments </span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">that are affiliated with, but not reporting to, the central information security function)</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY">• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The IT organization</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY">• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Other business areas (typically, the functions that go on in headquarters, such as legal, HR and finance)</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The security office''s responsibilities should be easily extracted from the security charter. The authority, rights and obligations of LOB management and the IT organization should have been negotiated via the governance structure prior to, or as part of, the creation of this strategic plan. These authorities, rights and obligations are typically governed via some kind of information security steering committee. Other business areas may be surprised by their inclusion or may have expressed a need for involvement on their own, typically as a response to regulatory compliance needs.</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">One approach to documenting these roles and responsibilities that has been widely accepted by organization is the use of a responsible, accountable, consulted and informed (RACI) matrix. Once all these steps have been outlined, the executive summary can be written.</span></span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;', 'Security Strategy', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '398-revision-v1', '', '', '2013-08-28 16:33:39', '2013-08-28 16:33:39', '', 398, 'http://localhost/wordpress/?p=443', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(442, 1, '2013-08-28 16:33:21', '2013-08-28 16:33:21', '<style type="text/css"><!--\r\n@page { margin: 0.79in } 		P { margin-bottom: 0.08in }\r\n--></style>\r\n<div><span><img style="margin-right: 10px;" alt="" src="http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/pdf-logo.jpg" width="20" height="20" /></span>\r\n<span><strong>2009-2011 Information Security Strategy for securitysense</strong></span>\r\n<span><a href="http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2009-2011-Information-Security-Strategy-for-securitysense.pdf"><img alt="" src="http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/pdfDownload.jpg" width="73" height="89" /></a></span></div>\r\n<div style="clear: both;"></div>\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>How to develop a IT/Information security strategy for your company?</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;">An information security strategic plan should include, at a minimum, an assessment of the current state of the program, a defined target state that is achievable within the three-year strategic planning window, a gap analysis and a road map for closing the gaps.</span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><b>Key Findings</b></span>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY">• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">A consistent framework can be defined that supports risk mitigation control objectives, architecture and </span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">process objectives, but the framework varies in scale and by the maturity level of the organization it''s </span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">being applied to.</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY">• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Small or immature organizations should focus on very simple frameworks.</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY">• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Consistent, incremental improvements are much more likely to succeed than rapidly forced changes.</span></span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><b>Recommendations</b></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Develop and document an information security strategic plan and use it to generate annual tactical </span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">plans that, when executed, move the overall maturity of the security program upward.</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Develop a process to review and refine the strategic plan annually.</span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><b>ANALYSIS</b></span>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Many organizations and security officers are approaching the creation of a strategic plan for information security for the first time, or have expressed a desire to use previously unimplemented best practices in creating the next iteration of one. Although there is no industry standard for the contents of such a plan, Securitysense has recommended organizations by using a model that has proved to be an effective communication tool with the numerous interested parties (including senior management), as well as a reasonable tracking mechanism for multiyear progress reports. While the model can be applied by organizations of any size and in any industry, the details vary based on the scale of the organization and the starting maturity level of the various effected organizational units.</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The information security strategic plan should not be viewed as a stand-alone document. It should exist as one part of a set of planning documents that start with a charter and a vision statement, but that also extends beyond the strategic plan into tactical and communications plans. Each of these has a role in providing context and action ability for the strategic plan. Organizations that have an established enterprise architecture (EA) function should leverage the existing EA disciplines, processes and standards to ensure that the strategic plan for information security is aligned with the EA strategy (see "Architecting Security: Different Approaches"). Securitysense generally considers three years to be an appropriate window for strategic planning for information security. The charter and vision statements deal with longer-term directions, while the tactical and communications plans specify single-year operational considerations and projects.</span></span></p>\r\n<span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The basic layout of the strategic plan is:</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Introduction and executive summary</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Strategic plan framework description</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Current state</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Desired state</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Gap analysis</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Prioritization plan</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Roles and responsibilities</span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>Introduction and Executive Summary</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The introduction should be written first, setting the purpose and scope of the document. The executive summary should be written last, showing only the final points of the document. The combination of executive summary and introduction should not exceed three pages, and, for most organizations, should be no more than two pages.</span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>Strategic Plan Framework Description</b></span></span>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The framework is the method by which the current state, desired state and gap analysis will be documented. An appropriate framework is one that can show overview (summarized) and detail (planning) information. The summary information should be expressed graphically. Frameworks should encompass controls, architecture and process elements to be complete.</span></span></p>\r\n<span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">For organizations with an established EA practice, an enterprise information security architecture (EISA) framework (see "The Structure and Content of an Information Security Architecture Framework") that aligns with the EA framework can act as an effective overall strategic security planning framework. Frameworks for this purpose can be derived from industry standards, from Securitysense research or from a combination of the two. </span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Some sources for framework structure and contents are:</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Controls</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">International Organization for Standardization (ISO)/International Electro technical</span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Commission (IEC) 27002</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Control Objectives for Information and Related Technology (COBIT)</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">U.S. National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) SP800-53</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Architecture</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">ISO10181</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">ISO13335</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Processes</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">ISO/IEC 27001</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Information Technology Infrastructure Library (ITIL)</span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">In addition, Securitysense research can provide significant examples and guidelines for constructing such a framework (see the Recommended Reading section below). Large, mature organizations will require more-complex, detailed frameworks that focus largely on processes. Smaller or less mature organizations will find that simple frameworks suffice, and that all details can be left to the tactical planning stage, but that balanced (perhaps, not equal) attention to the three areas of controls, architecture and processes is required. An example of a simple framework for a low maturity organization might be a three-by-four grid showing the state of controls, technical architecture and processes for data, infrastructure, applications and people/behavior. Each cell in the grid can be assessed or targeted (depending on whether it is the current state or desired state framework copy) on a typical numeric maturity scale of 0 through 5, or assigned a color code of red, yellow or green (see Figure 1).</span></span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nFig 1\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Larger or more-mature organizations will tend to focus more on process assessments, because controls and architecture tend to be well-defined, and the processes by which they are kept up to date will be defined and will be the primary lever for further maturation. </span></span><span style="color: #ff0000;"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Securitysense''s "Toolkit: Risk Program Maturity Assessment 1.0" provides a full process-oriented framework that includes graphical reporting of information security, privacy, regulatory compliance and business continuity</span></span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="color: #ff0000;"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">programs (see Figure 2).</span></span></span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Figure 2. Strategic Plan Contents: Current State</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Controls Architecture Process</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Data</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Infrastructure</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Applications</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>People</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPSMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">N/A</span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: xx-small;"><b>Source: Securitysense (September 2008)</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>Current State</b></span></span>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Use the framework described in the previous section to document the current state of each element contained within the framework. A brief text section describes each entry and justifies the assessment. Organizations with mature risk assessment processes may reference the current risk register to provide an assessment of existing controls.</span></span></p>\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>Desired State</b></span></span>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Document the desired state for each element within the framework. Three years is not a long time to achieve any sort of cultural change, nor for a significant reduction in the overall level of risk. Using a maturity scale from zero through five, with steps of one-half for each of the framework elements, allows sufficient granularity to show, at a strategic level, what degree of progress is being attempted. Brief text descriptions contain the background for each target value. Securitysense recommends that a change in maturity level of no more than a "2" be attempted for any framework element in a three-year period, unless exceptional resources and executive support can be assured (see Figure 3 for an example based on Figure 1).</span></span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Figure 3. Strategic Plan Contents: Target State</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Controls Architecture Process</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Data</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Infrastructure</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Applications</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>People</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPSMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">N/A</span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The desired state may also identify controls and technology areas that require change, retirement or replacement, if those have already been identified.</span></span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>Gap Analysis</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">This section describes those elements of the framework that demonstrate variation between current and desired states (see Figure 4).</span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Figure 4. Strategic Plan Contents: Gap Analysis</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Controls Architecture Process</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPSMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">+2 +1 +1</span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPSMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">+2</span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPSMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">+2 +1 +1</span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Data</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Infrastructure</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Applications</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>People</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPSMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">N/A +1</span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>Prioritization Plan</b></span></span>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">There may be a natural order to resolving many of the issues identified via the gap analysis. Part of the three-year strategic plan should be guidance to tactical planners on how to prioritize the closure of those gaps, such that any natural order is optimized. Controls determine what should be achieved, but controls become meaningful only if the governance structure is functional. The IT organization needs direction via technical architecture to be efficient, but architecture requires guidance from controls. Operational processes related to technologies that are already in place depend, to some degree, on controls (what processes and technologies are needed) and architecture (which process elements and technologies are automated). As a result, a normal prioritization plan might be to start with governance, move to controls, then architecture and finally process. But this is a "greenfield" approach, and it may not be appropriate for organizations with variable levels of maturity in the current information security program or IT organizations in general. For example, a lack of maturity in strategic processes, such as risk assessment and security communications, which are not technology-dependent may demand earlier prioritization.</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Therefore, the method by which priorities will be assigned in the tactical plans requires some</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">strategic guidance. More-granular prioritization of work should be included in tactical (annual) planning documents, and should be based on criteria such as the relative risk impact, the cost, the mean time to value and the availability of resources.</span></span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>Roles and Responsibilities</b></span></span>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">This section describes who is responsible for delivering and who is responsible for approving each strategic and tactical deliverable that results from this strategic plan. There are four sets of organizational areas that need to be mapped to deliverables and action plans:</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY">• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The security office</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY">• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Lines of business (LOBs) or federation issues (responsibilities that reside with persons or departments </span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">that are affiliated with, but not reporting to, the central information security function)</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY">• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The IT organization</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY">• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Other business areas (typically, the functions that go on in headquarters, such as legal, HR and finance)</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The security office''s responsibilities should be easily extracted from the security charter. The authority, rights and obligations of LOB management and the IT organization should have been negotiated via the governance structure prior to, or as part of, the creation of this strategic plan. These authorities, rights and obligations are typically governed via some kind of information security steering committee. Other business areas may be surprised by their inclusion or may have expressed a need for involvement on their own, typically as a response to regulatory compliance needs.</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">One approach to documenting these roles and responsibilities that has been widely accepted by organization is the use of a responsible, accountable, consulted and informed (RACI) matrix. Once all these steps have been outlined, the executive summary can be written.</span></span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;', 'Security Strategy', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '398-revision-v1', '', '', '2013-08-28 16:33:21', '2013-08-28 16:33:21', '', 398, 'http://localhost/wordpress/?p=442', 0, 'revision', '', 0);
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` (`ID`, `post_author`, `post_date`, `post_date_gmt`, `post_content`, `post_title`, `post_excerpt`, `post_status`, `comment_status`, `ping_status`, `post_password`, `post_name`, `to_ping`, `pinged`, `post_modified`, `post_modified_gmt`, `post_content_filtered`, `post_parent`, `guid`, `menu_order`, `post_type`, `post_mime_type`, `comment_count`) VALUES
(441, 1, '2013-08-28 16:28:08', '2013-08-28 16:28:08', '<style type="text/css"><!--\r\n@page { margin: 0.79in } 		P { margin-bottom: 0.08in }\r\n--></style>\r\n<ul style="list-style-type: none;">\r\n	<li style="float: left;"><img style="margin-right: 10px;" alt="" src="http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/pdf-logo.jpg" width="20" height="20" /></li>\r\n	<li style="float: left;"><strong>2009-2011 Information Security Strategy for securitysense</strong></li>\r\n	<li style="float: left;"><a href="http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2009-2011-Information-Security-Strategy-for-securitysense.pdf"><img alt="" src="http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/pdfDownload.jpg" width="73" height="89" /></a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<div style="clear: both;"></div>\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>How to develop a IT/Information security strategy for your company?</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;">An information security strategic plan should include, at a minimum, an assessment of the current state of the program, a defined target state that is achievable within the three-year strategic planning window, a gap analysis and a road map for closing the gaps.</span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><b>Key Findings</b></span>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY">• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">A consistent framework can be defined that supports risk mitigation control objectives, architecture and </span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">process objectives, but the framework varies in scale and by the maturity level of the organization it''s </span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">being applied to.</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY">• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Small or immature organizations should focus on very simple frameworks.</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY">• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Consistent, incremental improvements are much more likely to succeed than rapidly forced changes.</span></span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><b>Recommendations</b></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Develop and document an information security strategic plan and use it to generate annual tactical </span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">plans that, when executed, move the overall maturity of the security program upward.</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Develop a process to review and refine the strategic plan annually.</span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><b>ANALYSIS</b></span>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Many organizations and security officers are approaching the creation of a strategic plan for information security for the first time, or have expressed a desire to use previously unimplemented best practices in creating the next iteration of one. Although there is no industry standard for the contents of such a plan, Securitysense has recommended organizations by using a model that has proved to be an effective communication tool with the numerous interested parties (including senior management), as well as a reasonable tracking mechanism for multiyear progress reports. While the model can be applied by organizations of any size and in any industry, the details vary based on the scale of the organization and the starting maturity level of the various effected organizational units.</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The information security strategic plan should not be viewed as a stand-alone document. It should exist as one part of a set of planning documents that start with a charter and a vision statement, but that also extends beyond the strategic plan into tactical and communications plans. Each of these has a role in providing context and action ability for the strategic plan. Organizations that have an established enterprise architecture (EA) function should leverage the existing EA disciplines, processes and standards to ensure that the strategic plan for information security is aligned with the EA strategy (see "Architecting Security: Different Approaches"). Securitysense generally considers three years to be an appropriate window for strategic planning for information security. The charter and vision statements deal with longer-term directions, while the tactical and communications plans specify single-year operational considerations and projects.</span></span></p>\r\n<span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The basic layout of the strategic plan is:</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Introduction and executive summary</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Strategic plan framework description</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Current state</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Desired state</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Gap analysis</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Prioritization plan</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Roles and responsibilities</span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>Introduction and Executive Summary</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The introduction should be written first, setting the purpose and scope of the document. The executive summary should be written last, showing only the final points of the document. The combination of executive summary and introduction should not exceed three pages, and, for most organizations, should be no more than two pages.</span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>Strategic Plan Framework Description</b></span></span>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The framework is the method by which the current state, desired state and gap analysis will be documented. An appropriate framework is one that can show overview (summarized) and detail (planning) information. The summary information should be expressed graphically. Frameworks should encompass controls, architecture and process elements to be complete.</span></span></p>\r\n<span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">For organizations with an established EA practice, an enterprise information security architecture (EISA) framework (see "The Structure and Content of an Information Security Architecture Framework") that aligns with the EA framework can act as an effective overall strategic security planning framework. Frameworks for this purpose can be derived from industry standards, from Securitysense research or from a combination of the two. </span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Some sources for framework structure and contents are:</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Controls</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">International Organization for Standardization (ISO)/International Electro technical</span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Commission (IEC) 27002</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Control Objectives for Information and Related Technology (COBIT)</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">U.S. National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) SP800-53</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Architecture</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">ISO10181</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">ISO13335</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Processes</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">ISO/IEC 27001</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Information Technology Infrastructure Library (ITIL)</span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">In addition, Securitysense research can provide significant examples and guidelines for constructing such a framework (see the Recommended Reading section below). Large, mature organizations will require more-complex, detailed frameworks that focus largely on processes. Smaller or less mature organizations will find that simple frameworks suffice, and that all details can be left to the tactical planning stage, but that balanced (perhaps, not equal) attention to the three areas of controls, architecture and processes is required. An example of a simple framework for a low maturity organization might be a three-by-four grid showing the state of controls, technical architecture and processes for data, infrastructure, applications and people/behavior. Each cell in the grid can be assessed or targeted (depending on whether it is the current state or desired state framework copy) on a typical numeric maturity scale of 0 through 5, or assigned a color code of red, yellow or green (see Figure 1).</span></span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nFig 1\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Larger or more-mature organizations will tend to focus more on process assessments, because controls and architecture tend to be well-defined, and the processes by which they are kept up to date will be defined and will be the primary lever for further maturation. </span></span><span style="color: #ff0000;"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Securitysense''s "Toolkit: Risk Program Maturity Assessment 1.0" provides a full process-oriented framework that includes graphical reporting of information security, privacy, regulatory compliance and business continuity</span></span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="color: #ff0000;"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">programs (see Figure 2).</span></span></span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Figure 2. Strategic Plan Contents: Current State</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Controls Architecture Process</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Data</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Infrastructure</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Applications</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>People</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPSMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">N/A</span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: xx-small;"><b>Source: Securitysense (September 2008)</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>Current State</b></span></span>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Use the framework described in the previous section to document the current state of each element contained within the framework. A brief text section describes each entry and justifies the assessment. Organizations with mature risk assessment processes may reference the current risk register to provide an assessment of existing controls.</span></span></p>\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>Desired State</b></span></span>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Document the desired state for each element within the framework. Three years is not a long time to achieve any sort of cultural change, nor for a significant reduction in the overall level of risk. Using a maturity scale from zero through five, with steps of one-half for each of the framework elements, allows sufficient granularity to show, at a strategic level, what degree of progress is being attempted. Brief text descriptions contain the background for each target value. Securitysense recommends that a change in maturity level of no more than a "2" be attempted for any framework element in a three-year period, unless exceptional resources and executive support can be assured (see Figure 3 for an example based on Figure 1).</span></span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Figure 3. Strategic Plan Contents: Target State</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Controls Architecture Process</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Data</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Infrastructure</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Applications</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>People</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPSMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">N/A</span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The desired state may also identify controls and technology areas that require change, retirement or replacement, if those have already been identified.</span></span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>Gap Analysis</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">This section describes those elements of the framework that demonstrate variation between current and desired states (see Figure 4).</span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Figure 4. Strategic Plan Contents: Gap Analysis</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Controls Architecture Process</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPSMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">+2 +1 +1</span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPSMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">+2</span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPSMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">+2 +1 +1</span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Data</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Infrastructure</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Applications</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>People</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPSMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">N/A +1</span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>Prioritization Plan</b></span></span>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">There may be a natural order to resolving many of the issues identified via the gap analysis. Part of the three-year strategic plan should be guidance to tactical planners on how to prioritize the closure of those gaps, such that any natural order is optimized. Controls determine what should be achieved, but controls become meaningful only if the governance structure is functional. The IT organization needs direction via technical architecture to be efficient, but architecture requires guidance from controls. Operational processes related to technologies that are already in place depend, to some degree, on controls (what processes and technologies are needed) and architecture (which process elements and technologies are automated). As a result, a normal prioritization plan might be to start with governance, move to controls, then architecture and finally process. But this is a "greenfield" approach, and it may not be appropriate for organizations with variable levels of maturity in the current information security program or IT organizations in general. For example, a lack of maturity in strategic processes, such as risk assessment and security communications, which are not technology-dependent may demand earlier prioritization.</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Therefore, the method by which priorities will be assigned in the tactical plans requires some</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">strategic guidance. More-granular prioritization of work should be included in tactical (annual) planning documents, and should be based on criteria such as the relative risk impact, the cost, the mean time to value and the availability of resources.</span></span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>Roles and Responsibilities</b></span></span>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">This section describes who is responsible for delivering and who is responsible for approving each strategic and tactical deliverable that results from this strategic plan. There are four sets of organizational areas that need to be mapped to deliverables and action plans:</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY">• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The security office</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY">• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Lines of business (LOBs) or federation issues (responsibilities that reside with persons or departments </span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">that are affiliated with, but not reporting to, the central information security function)</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY">• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The IT organization</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY">• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Other business areas (typically, the functions that go on in headquarters, such as legal, HR and finance)</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The security office''s responsibilities should be easily extracted from the security charter. The authority, rights and obligations of LOB management and the IT organization should have been negotiated via the governance structure prior to, or as part of, the creation of this strategic plan. These authorities, rights and obligations are typically governed via some kind of information security steering committee. Other business areas may be surprised by their inclusion or may have expressed a need for involvement on their own, typically as a response to regulatory compliance needs.</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">One approach to documenting these roles and responsibilities that has been widely accepted by organization is the use of a responsible, accountable, consulted and informed (RACI) matrix. Once all these steps have been outlined, the executive summary can be written.</span></span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;', 'Security Strategy', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '398-revision-v1', '', '', '2013-08-28 16:28:08', '2013-08-28 16:28:08', '', 398, 'http://localhost/wordpress/?p=441', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(445, 1, '2013-08-29 00:36:04', '2013-08-29 00:36:04', '<style type="text/css"><!--\r\n@page { margin: 0.79in } 		P { margin-bottom: 0.08in }\r\n--></style>\r\n<table border="0">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td><a href="http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/pdf-logo.jpg"><img class="alignnone  wp-image-439" alt="pdf-logo" src="http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/pdf-logo-300x300.jpg" width="30" height="30" /></a></td>\r\n<td>\r\n<h2><strong>2009-2011 Information Security Strategy for securitysense</strong></h2>\r\n</td>\r\n<td><a href="http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2009-2011-Information-Security-Strategy-for-securitysense.pdf"><img class="alignnone  wp-image-444" alt="download_iamge" src="http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/download_iamge.jpg" width="176" height="103" /></a></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>How to develop a IT/Information security strategy for your company?</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;">An information security strategic plan should include, at a minimum, an assessment of the current state of the program, a defined target state that is achievable within the three-year strategic planning window, a gap analysis and a road map for closing the gaps.</span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><b>Key Findings</b></span>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY">• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">A consistent framework can be defined that supports risk mitigation control objectives, architecture and </span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">process objectives, but the framework varies in scale and by the maturity level of the organization it''s </span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">being applied to.</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY">• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Small or immature organizations should focus on very simple frameworks.</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY">• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Consistent, incremental improvements are much more likely to succeed than rapidly forced changes.</span></span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><b>Recommendations</b></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Develop and document an information security strategic plan and use it to generate annual tactical </span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">plans that, when executed, move the overall maturity of the security program upward.</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Develop a process to review and refine the strategic plan annually.</span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><b>ANALYSIS</b></span>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Many organizations and security officers are approaching the creation of a strategic plan for information security for the first time, or have expressed a desire to use previously unimplemented best practices in creating the next iteration of one. Although there is no industry standard for the contents of such a plan, Securitysense has recommended organizations by using a model that has proved to be an effective communication tool with the numerous interested parties (including senior management), as well as a reasonable tracking mechanism for multiyear progress reports. While the model can be applied by organizations of any size and in any industry, the details vary based on the scale of the organization and the starting maturity level of the various effected organizational units.</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The information security strategic plan should not be viewed as a stand-alone document. It should exist as one part of a set of planning documents that start with a charter and a vision statement, but that also extends beyond the strategic plan into tactical and communications plans. Each of these has a role in providing context and action ability for the strategic plan. Organizations that have an established enterprise architecture (EA) function should leverage the existing EA disciplines, processes and standards to ensure that the strategic plan for information security is aligned with the EA strategy (see "Architecting Security: Different Approaches"). Securitysense generally considers three years to be an appropriate window for strategic planning for information security. The charter and vision statements deal with longer-term directions, while the tactical and communications plans specify single-year operational considerations and projects.</span></span></p>\r\n<span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The basic layout of the strategic plan is:</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Introduction and executive summary</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Strategic plan framework description</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Current state</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Desired state</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Gap analysis</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Prioritization plan</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Roles and responsibilities</span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>Introduction and Executive Summary</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The introduction should be written first, setting the purpose and scope of the document. The executive summary should be written last, showing only the final points of the document. The combination of executive summary and introduction should not exceed three pages, and, for most organizations, should be no more than two pages.</span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>Strategic Plan Framework Description</b></span></span>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The framework is the method by which the current state, desired state and gap analysis will be documented. An appropriate framework is one that can show overview (summarized) and detail (planning) information. The summary information should be expressed graphically. Frameworks should encompass controls, architecture and process elements to be complete.</span></span></p>\r\n<span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">For organizations with an established EA practice, an enterprise information security architecture (EISA) framework (see "The Structure and Content of an Information Security Architecture Framework") that aligns with the EA framework can act as an effective overall strategic security planning framework. Frameworks for this purpose can be derived from industry standards, from Securitysense research or from a combination of the two. </span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Some sources for framework structure and contents are:</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Controls</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">International Organization for Standardization (ISO)/International Electro technical</span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Commission (IEC) 27002</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Control Objectives for Information and Related Technology (COBIT)</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">U.S. National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) SP800-53</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Architecture</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">ISO10181</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">ISO13335</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Processes</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">ISO/IEC 27001</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Information Technology Infrastructure Library (ITIL)</span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">In addition, Securitysense research can provide significant examples and guidelines for constructing such a framework (see the Recommended Reading section below). Large, mature organizations will require more-complex, detailed frameworks that focus largely on processes. Smaller or less mature organizations will find that simple frameworks suffice, and that all details can be left to the tactical planning stage, but that balanced (perhaps, not equal) attention to the three areas of controls, architecture and processes is required. An example of a simple framework for a low maturity organization might be a three-by-four grid showing the state of controls, technical architecture and processes for data, infrastructure, applications and people/behavior. Each cell in the grid can be assessed or targeted (depending on whether it is the current state or desired state framework copy) on a typical numeric maturity scale of 0 through 5, or assigned a color code of red, yellow or green (see Figure 1).</span></span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nFig 1\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Larger or more-mature organizations will tend to focus more on process assessments, because controls and architecture tend to be well-defined, and the processes by which they are kept up to date will be defined and will be the primary lever for further maturation. </span></span><span style="color: #ff0000;"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Securitysense''s "Toolkit: Risk Program Maturity Assessment 1.0" provides a full process-oriented framework that includes graphical reporting of information security, privacy, regulatory compliance and business continuity</span></span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="color: #ff0000;"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">programs (see Figure 2).</span></span></span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Figure 2. Strategic Plan Contents: Current State</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Controls Architecture Process</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Data</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Infrastructure</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Applications</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>People</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPSMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">N/A</span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: xx-small;"><b>Source: Securitysense (September 2008)</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>Current State</b></span></span>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Use the framework described in the previous section to document the current state of each element contained within the framework. A brief text section describes each entry and justifies the assessment. Organizations with mature risk assessment processes may reference the current risk register to provide an assessment of existing controls.</span></span></p>\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>Desired State</b></span></span>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Document the desired state for each element within the framework. Three years is not a long time to achieve any sort of cultural change, nor for a significant reduction in the overall level of risk. Using a maturity scale from zero through five, with steps of one-half for each of the framework elements, allows sufficient granularity to show, at a strategic level, what degree of progress is being attempted. Brief text descriptions contain the background for each target value. Securitysense recommends that a change in maturity level of no more than a "2" be attempted for any framework element in a three-year period, unless exceptional resources and executive support can be assured (see Figure 3 for an example based on Figure 1).</span></span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Figure 3. Strategic Plan Contents: Target State</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Controls Architecture Process</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Data</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Infrastructure</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Applications</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>People</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPSMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">N/A</span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The desired state may also identify controls and technology areas that require change, retirement or replacement, if those have already been identified.</span></span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>Gap Analysis</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">This section describes those elements of the framework that demonstrate variation between current and desired states (see Figure 4).</span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Figure 4. Strategic Plan Contents: Gap Analysis</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Controls Architecture Process</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPSMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">+2 +1 +1</span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPSMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">+2</span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPSMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">+2 +1 +1</span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Data</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Infrastructure</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Applications</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>People</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPSMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">N/A +1</span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>Prioritization Plan</b></span></span>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">There may be a natural order to resolving many of the issues identified via the gap analysis. Part of the three-year strategic plan should be guidance to tactical planners on how to prioritize the closure of those gaps, such that any natural order is optimized. Controls determine what should be achieved, but controls become meaningful only if the governance structure is functional. The IT organization needs direction via technical architecture to be efficient, but architecture requires guidance from controls. Operational processes related to technologies that are already in place depend, to some degree, on controls (what processes and technologies are needed) and architecture (which process elements and technologies are automated). As a result, a normal prioritization plan might be to start with governance, move to controls, then architecture and finally process. But this is a "greenfield" approach, and it may not be appropriate for organizations with variable levels of maturity in the current information security program or IT organizations in general. For example, a lack of maturity in strategic processes, such as risk assessment and security communications, which are not technology-dependent may demand earlier prioritization.</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Therefore, the method by which priorities will be assigned in the tactical plans requires some</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">strategic guidance. More-granular prioritization of work should be included in tactical (annual) planning documents, and should be based on criteria such as the relative risk impact, the cost, the mean time to value and the availability of resources.</span></span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>Roles and Responsibilities</b></span></span>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">This section describes who is responsible for delivering and who is responsible for approving each strategic and tactical deliverable that results from this strategic plan. There are four sets of organizational areas that need to be mapped to deliverables and action plans:</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY">• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The security office</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY">• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Lines of business (LOBs) or federation issues (responsibilities that reside with persons or departments </span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">that are affiliated with, but not reporting to, the central information security function)</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY">• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The IT organization</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY">• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Other business areas (typically, the functions that go on in headquarters, such as legal, HR and finance)</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The security office''s responsibilities should be easily extracted from the security charter. The authority, rights and obligations of LOB management and the IT organization should have been negotiated via the governance structure prior to, or as part of, the creation of this strategic plan. These authorities, rights and obligations are typically governed via some kind of information security steering committee. Other business areas may be surprised by their inclusion or may have expressed a need for involvement on their own, typically as a response to regulatory compliance needs.</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">One approach to documenting these roles and responsibilities that has been widely accepted by organization is the use of a responsible, accountable, consulted and informed (RACI) matrix. Once all these steps have been outlined, the executive summary can be written.</span></span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;', 'Security Strategy', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '398-revision-v1', '', '', '2013-08-29 00:36:04', '2013-08-29 00:36:04', '', 398, 'http://localhost/wordpress/?p=445', 0, 'revision', '', 0);
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` (`ID`, `post_author`, `post_date`, `post_date_gmt`, `post_content`, `post_title`, `post_excerpt`, `post_status`, `comment_status`, `ping_status`, `post_password`, `post_name`, `to_ping`, `pinged`, `post_modified`, `post_modified_gmt`, `post_content_filtered`, `post_parent`, `guid`, `menu_order`, `post_type`, `post_mime_type`, `comment_count`) VALUES
(446, 1, '2013-08-29 00:37:29', '2013-08-29 00:37:29', '<style type="text/css"><!--\r\n@page { margin: 0.79in } 		P { margin-bottom: 0.08in }\r\n--></style>\r\n<table border="0">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td><a href="http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/pdf-logo.jpg"><img class="alignnone  wp-image-439" alt="pdf-logo" src="http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/pdf-logo-300x300.jpg" width="51" height="51" /></a></td>\r\n<td>\r\n<h3><strong>2009-2011 Information Security Strategy for securitysense</strong></h3>\r\n</td>\r\n<td><a href="http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2009-2011-Information-Security-Strategy-for-securitysense.pdf"><img class="alignnone  wp-image-444" alt="download_iamge" src="http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/download_iamge.jpg" width="176" height="103" /></a></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>How to develop a IT/Information security strategy for your company?</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;">An information security strategic plan should include, at a minimum, an assessment of the current state of the program, a defined target state that is achievable within the three-year strategic planning window, a gap analysis and a road map for closing the gaps.</span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><b>Key Findings</b></span>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY">• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">A consistent framework can be defined that supports risk mitigation control objectives, architecture and </span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">process objectives, but the framework varies in scale and by the maturity level of the organization it''s </span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">being applied to.</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY">• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Small or immature organizations should focus on very simple frameworks.</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY">• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Consistent, incremental improvements are much more likely to succeed than rapidly forced changes.</span></span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><b>Recommendations</b></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Develop and document an information security strategic plan and use it to generate annual tactical </span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">plans that, when executed, move the overall maturity of the security program upward.</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Develop a process to review and refine the strategic plan annually.</span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><b>ANALYSIS</b></span>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Many organizations and security officers are approaching the creation of a strategic plan for information security for the first time, or have expressed a desire to use previously unimplemented best practices in creating the next iteration of one. Although there is no industry standard for the contents of such a plan, Securitysense has recommended organizations by using a model that has proved to be an effective communication tool with the numerous interested parties (including senior management), as well as a reasonable tracking mechanism for multiyear progress reports. While the model can be applied by organizations of any size and in any industry, the details vary based on the scale of the organization and the starting maturity level of the various effected organizational units.</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The information security strategic plan should not be viewed as a stand-alone document. It should exist as one part of a set of planning documents that start with a charter and a vision statement, but that also extends beyond the strategic plan into tactical and communications plans. Each of these has a role in providing context and action ability for the strategic plan. Organizations that have an established enterprise architecture (EA) function should leverage the existing EA disciplines, processes and standards to ensure that the strategic plan for information security is aligned with the EA strategy (see "Architecting Security: Different Approaches"). Securitysense generally considers three years to be an appropriate window for strategic planning for information security. The charter and vision statements deal with longer-term directions, while the tactical and communications plans specify single-year operational considerations and projects.</span></span></p>\r\n<span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The basic layout of the strategic plan is:</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Introduction and executive summary</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Strategic plan framework description</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Current state</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Desired state</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Gap analysis</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Prioritization plan</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Roles and responsibilities</span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>Introduction and Executive Summary</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The introduction should be written first, setting the purpose and scope of the document. The executive summary should be written last, showing only the final points of the document. The combination of executive summary and introduction should not exceed three pages, and, for most organizations, should be no more than two pages.</span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>Strategic Plan Framework Description</b></span></span>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The framework is the method by which the current state, desired state and gap analysis will be documented. An appropriate framework is one that can show overview (summarized) and detail (planning) information. The summary information should be expressed graphically. Frameworks should encompass controls, architecture and process elements to be complete.</span></span></p>\r\n<span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">For organizations with an established EA practice, an enterprise information security architecture (EISA) framework (see "The Structure and Content of an Information Security Architecture Framework") that aligns with the EA framework can act as an effective overall strategic security planning framework. Frameworks for this purpose can be derived from industry standards, from Securitysense research or from a combination of the two. </span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Some sources for framework structure and contents are:</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Controls</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">International Organization for Standardization (ISO)/International Electro technical</span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Commission (IEC) 27002</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Control Objectives for Information and Related Technology (COBIT)</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">U.S. National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) SP800-53</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Architecture</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">ISO10181</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">ISO13335</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Processes</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">ISO/IEC 27001</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Information Technology Infrastructure Library (ITIL)</span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">In addition, Securitysense research can provide significant examples and guidelines for constructing such a framework (see the Recommended Reading section below). Large, mature organizations will require more-complex, detailed frameworks that focus largely on processes. Smaller or less mature organizations will find that simple frameworks suffice, and that all details can be left to the tactical planning stage, but that balanced (perhaps, not equal) attention to the three areas of controls, architecture and processes is required. An example of a simple framework for a low maturity organization might be a three-by-four grid showing the state of controls, technical architecture and processes for data, infrastructure, applications and people/behavior. Each cell in the grid can be assessed or targeted (depending on whether it is the current state or desired state framework copy) on a typical numeric maturity scale of 0 through 5, or assigned a color code of red, yellow or green (see Figure 1).</span></span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nFig 1\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Larger or more-mature organizations will tend to focus more on process assessments, because controls and architecture tend to be well-defined, and the processes by which they are kept up to date will be defined and will be the primary lever for further maturation. </span></span><span style="color: #ff0000;"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Securitysense''s "Toolkit: Risk Program Maturity Assessment 1.0" provides a full process-oriented framework that includes graphical reporting of information security, privacy, regulatory compliance and business continuity</span></span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="color: #ff0000;"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">programs (see Figure 2).</span></span></span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Figure 2. Strategic Plan Contents: Current State</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Controls Architecture Process</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Data</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Infrastructure</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Applications</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>People</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPSMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">N/A</span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: xx-small;"><b>Source: Securitysense (September 2008)</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>Current State</b></span></span>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Use the framework described in the previous section to document the current state of each element contained within the framework. A brief text section describes each entry and justifies the assessment. Organizations with mature risk assessment processes may reference the current risk register to provide an assessment of existing controls.</span></span></p>\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>Desired State</b></span></span>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Document the desired state for each element within the framework. Three years is not a long time to achieve any sort of cultural change, nor for a significant reduction in the overall level of risk. Using a maturity scale from zero through five, with steps of one-half for each of the framework elements, allows sufficient granularity to show, at a strategic level, what degree of progress is being attempted. Brief text descriptions contain the background for each target value. Securitysense recommends that a change in maturity level of no more than a "2" be attempted for any framework element in a three-year period, unless exceptional resources and executive support can be assured (see Figure 3 for an example based on Figure 1).</span></span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Figure 3. Strategic Plan Contents: Target State</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Controls Architecture Process</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Data</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Infrastructure</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Applications</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>People</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPSMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">N/A</span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The desired state may also identify controls and technology areas that require change, retirement or replacement, if those have already been identified.</span></span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>Gap Analysis</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">This section describes those elements of the framework that demonstrate variation between current and desired states (see Figure 4).</span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Figure 4. Strategic Plan Contents: Gap Analysis</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Controls Architecture Process</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPSMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">+2 +1 +1</span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPSMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">+2</span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPSMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">+2 +1 +1</span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Data</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Infrastructure</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Applications</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>People</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPSMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">N/A +1</span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>Prioritization Plan</b></span></span>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">There may be a natural order to resolving many of the issues identified via the gap analysis. Part of the three-year strategic plan should be guidance to tactical planners on how to prioritize the closure of those gaps, such that any natural order is optimized. Controls determine what should be achieved, but controls become meaningful only if the governance structure is functional. The IT organization needs direction via technical architecture to be efficient, but architecture requires guidance from controls. Operational processes related to technologies that are already in place depend, to some degree, on controls (what processes and technologies are needed) and architecture (which process elements and technologies are automated). As a result, a normal prioritization plan might be to start with governance, move to controls, then architecture and finally process. But this is a "greenfield" approach, and it may not be appropriate for organizations with variable levels of maturity in the current information security program or IT organizations in general. For example, a lack of maturity in strategic processes, such as risk assessment and security communications, which are not technology-dependent may demand earlier prioritization.</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Therefore, the method by which priorities will be assigned in the tactical plans requires some</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">strategic guidance. More-granular prioritization of work should be included in tactical (annual) planning documents, and should be based on criteria such as the relative risk impact, the cost, the mean time to value and the availability of resources.</span></span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>Roles and Responsibilities</b></span></span>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">This section describes who is responsible for delivering and who is responsible for approving each strategic and tactical deliverable that results from this strategic plan. There are four sets of organizational areas that need to be mapped to deliverables and action plans:</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY">• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The security office</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY">• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Lines of business (LOBs) or federation issues (responsibilities that reside with persons or departments </span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">that are affiliated with, but not reporting to, the central information security function)</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY">• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The IT organization</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY">• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Other business areas (typically, the functions that go on in headquarters, such as legal, HR and finance)</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The security office''s responsibilities should be easily extracted from the security charter. The authority, rights and obligations of LOB management and the IT organization should have been negotiated via the governance structure prior to, or as part of, the creation of this strategic plan. These authorities, rights and obligations are typically governed via some kind of information security steering committee. Other business areas may be surprised by their inclusion or may have expressed a need for involvement on their own, typically as a response to regulatory compliance needs.</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">One approach to documenting these roles and responsibilities that has been widely accepted by organization is the use of a responsible, accountable, consulted and informed (RACI) matrix. Once all these steps have been outlined, the executive summary can be written.</span></span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;', 'Security Strategy', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '398-revision-v1', '', '', '2013-08-29 00:37:29', '2013-08-29 00:37:29', '', 398, 'http://localhost/wordpress/?p=446', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(453, 1, '2013-08-29 00:53:38', '2013-08-29 00:53:38', '<style type="text/css"><!--\r\n@page { margin: 0.79in } 		P { margin-bottom: 0.08in }\r\n--></style>\r\n<table width="498" border="0">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td><a><img class="wp-image-439 alignleft" alt="pdf-logo" src="http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/pdf-logo.jpg" width="51" height="51" /></a></td>\r\n<td>\r\n<h3 style="text-align: center;"><strong>2009-2011 Information Security Strategy for securitysense</strong></h3>\r\n</td>\r\n<td><a href="http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2009-2011-Information-Security-Strategy-for-securitysense.pdf"><img class="wp-image-444 alignleft" alt="download_iamge" src="http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/download_iamge.jpg" width="176" height="103" /></a></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>How to develop a IT/Information security strategy for your company?</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;">An information security strategic plan should include, at a minimum, an assessment of the current state of the program, a defined target state that is achievable within the three-year strategic planning window, a gap analysis and a road map for closing the gaps.</span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><b>Key Findings</b></span>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY">• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">A consistent framework can be defined that supports risk mitigation control objectives, architecture and </span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">process objectives, but the framework varies in scale and by the maturity level of the organization it''s </span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">being applied to.</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY">• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Small or immature organizations should focus on very simple frameworks.</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY">• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Consistent, incremental improvements are much more likely to succeed than rapidly forced changes.</span></span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><b>Recommendations</b></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Develop and document an information security strategic plan and use it to generate annual tactical </span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">plans that, when executed, move the overall maturity of the security program upward.</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Develop a process to review and refine the strategic plan annually.</span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><b>ANALYSIS</b></span>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Many organizations and security officers are approaching the creation of a strategic plan for information security for the first time, or have expressed a desire to use previously unimplemented best practices in creating the next iteration of one. Although there is no industry standard for the contents of such a plan, Securitysense has recommended organizations by using a model that has proved to be an effective communication tool with the numerous interested parties (including senior management), as well as a reasonable tracking mechanism for multiyear progress reports. While the model can be applied by organizations of any size and in any industry, the details vary based on the scale of the organization and the starting maturity level of the various effected organizational units.</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The information security strategic plan should not be viewed as a stand-alone document. It should exist as one part of a set of planning documents that start with a charter and a vision statement, but that also extends beyond the strategic plan into tactical and communications plans. Each of these has a role in providing context and action ability for the strategic plan. Organizations that have an established enterprise architecture (EA) function should leverage the existing EA disciplines, processes and standards to ensure that the strategic plan for information security is aligned with the EA strategy (see "Architecting Security: Different Approaches"). Securitysense generally considers three years to be an appropriate window for strategic planning for information security. The charter and vision statements deal with longer-term directions, while the tactical and communications plans specify single-year operational considerations and projects.</span></span></p>\r\n<span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The basic layout of the strategic plan is:</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Introduction and executive summary</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Strategic plan framework description</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Current state</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Desired state</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Gap analysis</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Prioritization plan</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Roles and responsibilities</span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>Introduction and Executive Summary</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The introduction should be written first, setting the purpose and scope of the document. The executive summary should be written last, showing only the final points of the document. The combination of executive summary and introduction should not exceed three pages, and, for most organizations, should be no more than two pages.</span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>Strategic Plan Framework Description</b></span></span>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The framework is the method by which the current state, desired state and gap analysis will be documented. An appropriate framework is one that can show overview (summarized) and detail (planning) information. The summary information should be expressed graphically. Frameworks should encompass controls, architecture and process elements to be complete.</span></span></p>\r\n<span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">For organizations with an established EA practice, an enterprise information security architecture (EISA) framework (see "The Structure and Content of an Information Security Architecture Framework") that aligns with the EA framework can act as an effective overall strategic security planning framework. Frameworks for this purpose can be derived from industry standards, from Securitysense research or from a combination of the two. </span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Some sources for framework structure and contents are:</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Controls</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">International Organization for Standardization (ISO)/International Electro technical</span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Commission (IEC) 27002</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Control Objectives for Information and Related Technology (COBIT)</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">U.S. National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) SP800-53</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Architecture</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">ISO10181</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">ISO13335</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Processes</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">ISO/IEC 27001</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Information Technology Infrastructure Library (ITIL)</span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">In addition, Securitysense research can provide significant examples and guidelines for constructing such a framework (see the Recommended Reading section below). Large, mature organizations will require more-complex, detailed frameworks that focus largely on processes. Smaller or less mature organizations will find that simple frameworks suffice, and that all details can be left to the tactical planning stage, but that balanced (perhaps, not equal) attention to the three areas of controls, architecture and processes is required. An example of a simple framework for a low maturity organization might be a three-by-four grid showing the state of controls, technical architecture and processes for data, infrastructure, applications and people/behavior. Each cell in the grid can be assessed or targeted (depending on whether it is the current state or desired state framework copy) on a typical numeric maturity scale of 0 through 5, or assigned a color code of red, yellow or green (see Figure 1).</span></span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nFig 1\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Larger or more-mature organizations will tend to focus more on process assessments, because controls and architecture tend to be well-defined, and the processes by which they are kept up to date will be defined and will be the primary lever for further maturation. </span></span><span style="color: #ff0000;"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Securitysense''s "Toolkit: Risk Program Maturity Assessment 1.0" provides a full process-oriented framework that includes graphical reporting of information security, privacy, regulatory compliance and business continuity</span></span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="color: #ff0000;"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">programs (see Figure 2).</span></span></span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Figure 2. Strategic Plan Contents: Current State</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Controls Architecture Process</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Data</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Infrastructure</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Applications</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>People</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPSMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">N/A</span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: xx-small;"><b>Source: Securitysense (September 2008)</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>Current State</b></span></span>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Use the framework described in the previous section to document the current state of each element contained within the framework. A brief text section describes each entry and justifies the assessment. Organizations with mature risk assessment processes may reference the current risk register to provide an assessment of existing controls.</span></span></p>\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>Desired State</b></span></span>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Document the desired state for each element within the framework. Three years is not a long time to achieve any sort of cultural change, nor for a significant reduction in the overall level of risk. Using a maturity scale from zero through five, with steps of one-half for each of the framework elements, allows sufficient granularity to show, at a strategic level, what degree of progress is being attempted. Brief text descriptions contain the background for each target value. Securitysense recommends that a change in maturity level of no more than a "2" be attempted for any framework element in a three-year period, unless exceptional resources and executive support can be assured (see Figure 3 for an example based on Figure 1).</span></span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Figure 3. Strategic Plan Contents: Target State</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Controls Architecture Process</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Data</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Infrastructure</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Applications</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>People</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPSMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">N/A</span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The desired state may also identify controls and technology areas that require change, retirement or replacement, if those have already been identified.</span></span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>Gap Analysis</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">This section describes those elements of the framework that demonstrate variation between current and desired states (see Figure 4).</span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Figure 4. Strategic Plan Contents: Gap Analysis</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Controls Architecture Process</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPSMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">+2 +1 +1</span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPSMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">+2</span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPSMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">+2 +1 +1</span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Data</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Infrastructure</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Applications</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>People</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPSMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">N/A +1</span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>Prioritization Plan</b></span></span>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">There may be a natural order to resolving many of the issues identified via the gap analysis. Part of the three-year strategic plan should be guidance to tactical planners on how to prioritize the closure of those gaps, such that any natural order is optimized. Controls determine what should be achieved, but controls become meaningful only if the governance structure is functional. The IT organization needs direction via technical architecture to be efficient, but architecture requires guidance from controls. Operational processes related to technologies that are already in place depend, to some degree, on controls (what processes and technologies are needed) and architecture (which process elements and technologies are automated). As a result, a normal prioritization plan might be to start with governance, move to controls, then architecture and finally process. But this is a "greenfield" approach, and it may not be appropriate for organizations with variable levels of maturity in the current information security program or IT organizations in general. For example, a lack of maturity in strategic processes, such as risk assessment and security communications, which are not technology-dependent may demand earlier prioritization.</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Therefore, the method by which priorities will be assigned in the tactical plans requires some</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">strategic guidance. More-granular prioritization of work should be included in tactical (annual) planning documents, and should be based on criteria such as the relative risk impact, the cost, the mean time to value and the availability of resources.</span></span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>Roles and Responsibilities</b></span></span>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">This section describes who is responsible for delivering and who is responsible for approving each strategic and tactical deliverable that results from this strategic plan. There are four sets of organizational areas that need to be mapped to deliverables and action plans:</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY">• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The security office</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY">• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Lines of business (LOBs) or federation issues (responsibilities that reside with persons or departments </span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">that are affiliated with, but not reporting to, the central information security function)</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY">• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The IT organization</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY">• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Other business areas (typically, the functions that go on in headquarters, such as legal, HR and finance)</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The security office''s responsibilities should be easily extracted from the security charter. The authority, rights and obligations of LOB management and the IT organization should have been negotiated via the governance structure prior to, or as part of, the creation of this strategic plan. These authorities, rights and obligations are typically governed via some kind of information security steering committee. Other business areas may be surprised by their inclusion or may have expressed a need for involvement on their own, typically as a response to regulatory compliance needs.</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">One approach to documenting these roles and responsibilities that has been widely accepted by organization is the use of a responsible, accountable, consulted and informed (RACI) matrix. Once all these steps have been outlined, the executive summary can be written.</span></span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;', 'Security Strategy', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '398-revision-v1', '', '', '2013-08-29 00:53:38', '2013-08-29 00:53:38', '', 398, 'http://localhost/wordpress/?p=453', 0, 'revision', '', 0);
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` (`ID`, `post_author`, `post_date`, `post_date_gmt`, `post_content`, `post_title`, `post_excerpt`, `post_status`, `comment_status`, `ping_status`, `post_password`, `post_name`, `to_ping`, `pinged`, `post_modified`, `post_modified_gmt`, `post_content_filtered`, `post_parent`, `guid`, `menu_order`, `post_type`, `post_mime_type`, `comment_count`) VALUES
(449, 1, '2013-08-29 00:39:44', '2013-08-29 00:39:44', '<style type="text/css"><!--\r\n@page { margin: 0.79in } 		P { margin-bottom: 0.08in }\r\n--></style>\r\n<table width="603" border="0">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td><a href="http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/pdf-logo.jpg"><img class="alignnone  wp-image-439" alt="pdf-logo" src="http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/pdf-logo-300x300.jpg" width="51" height="51" /></a></td>\r\n<td>\r\n<h3><strong>2009-2011 Information Security Strategy for securitysense</strong></h3>\r\n</td>\r\n<td><a href="http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2009-2011-Information-Security-Strategy-for-securitysense.pdf"><img class="alignnone  wp-image-444" alt="download_iamge" src="http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/download_iamge.jpg" width="176" height="103" /></a></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>How to develop a IT/Information security strategy for your company?</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;">An information security strategic plan should include, at a minimum, an assessment of the current state of the program, a defined target state that is achievable within the three-year strategic planning window, a gap analysis and a road map for closing the gaps.</span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><b>Key Findings</b></span>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY">• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">A consistent framework can be defined that supports risk mitigation control objectives, architecture and </span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">process objectives, but the framework varies in scale and by the maturity level of the organization it''s </span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">being applied to.</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY">• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Small or immature organizations should focus on very simple frameworks.</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY">• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Consistent, incremental improvements are much more likely to succeed than rapidly forced changes.</span></span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><b>Recommendations</b></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Develop and document an information security strategic plan and use it to generate annual tactical </span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">plans that, when executed, move the overall maturity of the security program upward.</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Develop a process to review and refine the strategic plan annually.</span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><b>ANALYSIS</b></span>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Many organizations and security officers are approaching the creation of a strategic plan for information security for the first time, or have expressed a desire to use previously unimplemented best practices in creating the next iteration of one. Although there is no industry standard for the contents of such a plan, Securitysense has recommended organizations by using a model that has proved to be an effective communication tool with the numerous interested parties (including senior management), as well as a reasonable tracking mechanism for multiyear progress reports. While the model can be applied by organizations of any size and in any industry, the details vary based on the scale of the organization and the starting maturity level of the various effected organizational units.</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The information security strategic plan should not be viewed as a stand-alone document. It should exist as one part of a set of planning documents that start with a charter and a vision statement, but that also extends beyond the strategic plan into tactical and communications plans. Each of these has a role in providing context and action ability for the strategic plan. Organizations that have an established enterprise architecture (EA) function should leverage the existing EA disciplines, processes and standards to ensure that the strategic plan for information security is aligned with the EA strategy (see "Architecting Security: Different Approaches"). Securitysense generally considers three years to be an appropriate window for strategic planning for information security. The charter and vision statements deal with longer-term directions, while the tactical and communications plans specify single-year operational considerations and projects.</span></span></p>\r\n<span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The basic layout of the strategic plan is:</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Introduction and executive summary</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Strategic plan framework description</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Current state</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Desired state</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Gap analysis</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Prioritization plan</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Roles and responsibilities</span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>Introduction and Executive Summary</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The introduction should be written first, setting the purpose and scope of the document. The executive summary should be written last, showing only the final points of the document. The combination of executive summary and introduction should not exceed three pages, and, for most organizations, should be no more than two pages.</span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>Strategic Plan Framework Description</b></span></span>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The framework is the method by which the current state, desired state and gap analysis will be documented. An appropriate framework is one that can show overview (summarized) and detail (planning) information. The summary information should be expressed graphically. Frameworks should encompass controls, architecture and process elements to be complete.</span></span></p>\r\n<span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">For organizations with an established EA practice, an enterprise information security architecture (EISA) framework (see "The Structure and Content of an Information Security Architecture Framework") that aligns with the EA framework can act as an effective overall strategic security planning framework. Frameworks for this purpose can be derived from industry standards, from Securitysense research or from a combination of the two. </span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Some sources for framework structure and contents are:</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Controls</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">International Organization for Standardization (ISO)/International Electro technical</span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Commission (IEC) 27002</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Control Objectives for Information and Related Technology (COBIT)</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">U.S. National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) SP800-53</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Architecture</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">ISO10181</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">ISO13335</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Processes</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">ISO/IEC 27001</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Information Technology Infrastructure Library (ITIL)</span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">In addition, Securitysense research can provide significant examples and guidelines for constructing such a framework (see the Recommended Reading section below). Large, mature organizations will require more-complex, detailed frameworks that focus largely on processes. Smaller or less mature organizations will find that simple frameworks suffice, and that all details can be left to the tactical planning stage, but that balanced (perhaps, not equal) attention to the three areas of controls, architecture and processes is required. An example of a simple framework for a low maturity organization might be a three-by-four grid showing the state of controls, technical architecture and processes for data, infrastructure, applications and people/behavior. Each cell in the grid can be assessed or targeted (depending on whether it is the current state or desired state framework copy) on a typical numeric maturity scale of 0 through 5, or assigned a color code of red, yellow or green (see Figure 1).</span></span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nFig 1\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Larger or more-mature organizations will tend to focus more on process assessments, because controls and architecture tend to be well-defined, and the processes by which they are kept up to date will be defined and will be the primary lever for further maturation. </span></span><span style="color: #ff0000;"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Securitysense''s "Toolkit: Risk Program Maturity Assessment 1.0" provides a full process-oriented framework that includes graphical reporting of information security, privacy, regulatory compliance and business continuity</span></span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="color: #ff0000;"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">programs (see Figure 2).</span></span></span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Figure 2. Strategic Plan Contents: Current State</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Controls Architecture Process</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Data</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Infrastructure</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Applications</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>People</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPSMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">N/A</span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: xx-small;"><b>Source: Securitysense (September 2008)</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>Current State</b></span></span>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Use the framework described in the previous section to document the current state of each element contained within the framework. A brief text section describes each entry and justifies the assessment. Organizations with mature risk assessment processes may reference the current risk register to provide an assessment of existing controls.</span></span></p>\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>Desired State</b></span></span>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Document the desired state for each element within the framework. Three years is not a long time to achieve any sort of cultural change, nor for a significant reduction in the overall level of risk. Using a maturity scale from zero through five, with steps of one-half for each of the framework elements, allows sufficient granularity to show, at a strategic level, what degree of progress is being attempted. Brief text descriptions contain the background for each target value. Securitysense recommends that a change in maturity level of no more than a "2" be attempted for any framework element in a three-year period, unless exceptional resources and executive support can be assured (see Figure 3 for an example based on Figure 1).</span></span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Figure 3. Strategic Plan Contents: Target State</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Controls Architecture Process</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Data</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Infrastructure</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Applications</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>People</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPSMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">N/A</span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The desired state may also identify controls and technology areas that require change, retirement or replacement, if those have already been identified.</span></span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>Gap Analysis</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">This section describes those elements of the framework that demonstrate variation between current and desired states (see Figure 4).</span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Figure 4. Strategic Plan Contents: Gap Analysis</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Controls Architecture Process</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPSMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">+2 +1 +1</span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPSMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">+2</span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPSMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">+2 +1 +1</span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Data</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Infrastructure</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Applications</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>People</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPSMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">N/A +1</span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>Prioritization Plan</b></span></span>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">There may be a natural order to resolving many of the issues identified via the gap analysis. Part of the three-year strategic plan should be guidance to tactical planners on how to prioritize the closure of those gaps, such that any natural order is optimized. Controls determine what should be achieved, but controls become meaningful only if the governance structure is functional. The IT organization needs direction via technical architecture to be efficient, but architecture requires guidance from controls. Operational processes related to technologies that are already in place depend, to some degree, on controls (what processes and technologies are needed) and architecture (which process elements and technologies are automated). As a result, a normal prioritization plan might be to start with governance, move to controls, then architecture and finally process. But this is a "greenfield" approach, and it may not be appropriate for organizations with variable levels of maturity in the current information security program or IT organizations in general. For example, a lack of maturity in strategic processes, such as risk assessment and security communications, which are not technology-dependent may demand earlier prioritization.</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Therefore, the method by which priorities will be assigned in the tactical plans requires some</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">strategic guidance. More-granular prioritization of work should be included in tactical (annual) planning documents, and should be based on criteria such as the relative risk impact, the cost, the mean time to value and the availability of resources.</span></span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>Roles and Responsibilities</b></span></span>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">This section describes who is responsible for delivering and who is responsible for approving each strategic and tactical deliverable that results from this strategic plan. There are four sets of organizational areas that need to be mapped to deliverables and action plans:</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY">• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The security office</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY">• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Lines of business (LOBs) or federation issues (responsibilities that reside with persons or departments </span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">that are affiliated with, but not reporting to, the central information security function)</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY">• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The IT organization</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY">• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Other business areas (typically, the functions that go on in headquarters, such as legal, HR and finance)</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The security office''s responsibilities should be easily extracted from the security charter. The authority, rights and obligations of LOB management and the IT organization should have been negotiated via the governance structure prior to, or as part of, the creation of this strategic plan. These authorities, rights and obligations are typically governed via some kind of information security steering committee. Other business areas may be surprised by their inclusion or may have expressed a need for involvement on their own, typically as a response to regulatory compliance needs.</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">One approach to documenting these roles and responsibilities that has been widely accepted by organization is the use of a responsible, accountable, consulted and informed (RACI) matrix. Once all these steps have been outlined, the executive summary can be written.</span></span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;', 'Security Strategy', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '398-revision-v1', '', '', '2013-08-29 00:39:44', '2013-08-29 00:39:44', '', 398, 'http://localhost/wordpress/?p=449', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(447, 1, '2013-08-29 00:38:24', '2013-08-29 00:38:24', '<style type="text/css"><!--\r\n@page { margin: 0.79in } 		P { margin-bottom: 0.08in }\r\n--></style>\r\n<table width="603" border="0">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td><a href="http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/pdf-logo.jpg"><img class="alignnone  wp-image-439" style="margin-left: 2px; margin-right: 2px;" alt="pdf-logo" src="http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/pdf-logo-300x300.jpg" width="51" height="51" /></a></td>\r\n<td>\r\n<h3><strong>2009-2011 Information Security Strategy for securitysense</strong></h3>\r\n</td>\r\n<td><a href="http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2009-2011-Information-Security-Strategy-for-securitysense.pdf"><img class="alignnone  wp-image-444" alt="download_iamge" src="http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/download_iamge.jpg" width="176" height="103" /></a></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>How to develop a IT/Information security strategy for your company?</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;">An information security strategic plan should include, at a minimum, an assessment of the current state of the program, a defined target state that is achievable within the three-year strategic planning window, a gap analysis and a road map for closing the gaps.</span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><b>Key Findings</b></span>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY">• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">A consistent framework can be defined that supports risk mitigation control objectives, architecture and </span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">process objectives, but the framework varies in scale and by the maturity level of the organization it''s </span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">being applied to.</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY">• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Small or immature organizations should focus on very simple frameworks.</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY">• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Consistent, incremental improvements are much more likely to succeed than rapidly forced changes.</span></span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><b>Recommendations</b></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Develop and document an information security strategic plan and use it to generate annual tactical </span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">plans that, when executed, move the overall maturity of the security program upward.</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Develop a process to review and refine the strategic plan annually.</span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><b>ANALYSIS</b></span>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Many organizations and security officers are approaching the creation of a strategic plan for information security for the first time, or have expressed a desire to use previously unimplemented best practices in creating the next iteration of one. Although there is no industry standard for the contents of such a plan, Securitysense has recommended organizations by using a model that has proved to be an effective communication tool with the numerous interested parties (including senior management), as well as a reasonable tracking mechanism for multiyear progress reports. While the model can be applied by organizations of any size and in any industry, the details vary based on the scale of the organization and the starting maturity level of the various effected organizational units.</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The information security strategic plan should not be viewed as a stand-alone document. It should exist as one part of a set of planning documents that start with a charter and a vision statement, but that also extends beyond the strategic plan into tactical and communications plans. Each of these has a role in providing context and action ability for the strategic plan. Organizations that have an established enterprise architecture (EA) function should leverage the existing EA disciplines, processes and standards to ensure that the strategic plan for information security is aligned with the EA strategy (see "Architecting Security: Different Approaches"). Securitysense generally considers three years to be an appropriate window for strategic planning for information security. The charter and vision statements deal with longer-term directions, while the tactical and communications plans specify single-year operational considerations and projects.</span></span></p>\r\n<span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The basic layout of the strategic plan is:</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Introduction and executive summary</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Strategic plan framework description</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Current state</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Desired state</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Gap analysis</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Prioritization plan</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Roles and responsibilities</span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>Introduction and Executive Summary</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The introduction should be written first, setting the purpose and scope of the document. The executive summary should be written last, showing only the final points of the document. The combination of executive summary and introduction should not exceed three pages, and, for most organizations, should be no more than two pages.</span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>Strategic Plan Framework Description</b></span></span>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The framework is the method by which the current state, desired state and gap analysis will be documented. An appropriate framework is one that can show overview (summarized) and detail (planning) information. The summary information should be expressed graphically. Frameworks should encompass controls, architecture and process elements to be complete.</span></span></p>\r\n<span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">For organizations with an established EA practice, an enterprise information security architecture (EISA) framework (see "The Structure and Content of an Information Security Architecture Framework") that aligns with the EA framework can act as an effective overall strategic security planning framework. Frameworks for this purpose can be derived from industry standards, from Securitysense research or from a combination of the two. </span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Some sources for framework structure and contents are:</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Controls</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">International Organization for Standardization (ISO)/International Electro technical</span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Commission (IEC) 27002</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Control Objectives for Information and Related Technology (COBIT)</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">U.S. National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) SP800-53</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Architecture</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">ISO10181</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">ISO13335</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Processes</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">ISO/IEC 27001</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Information Technology Infrastructure Library (ITIL)</span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">In addition, Securitysense research can provide significant examples and guidelines for constructing such a framework (see the Recommended Reading section below). Large, mature organizations will require more-complex, detailed frameworks that focus largely on processes. Smaller or less mature organizations will find that simple frameworks suffice, and that all details can be left to the tactical planning stage, but that balanced (perhaps, not equal) attention to the three areas of controls, architecture and processes is required. An example of a simple framework for a low maturity organization might be a three-by-four grid showing the state of controls, technical architecture and processes for data, infrastructure, applications and people/behavior. Each cell in the grid can be assessed or targeted (depending on whether it is the current state or desired state framework copy) on a typical numeric maturity scale of 0 through 5, or assigned a color code of red, yellow or green (see Figure 1).</span></span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nFig 1\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Larger or more-mature organizations will tend to focus more on process assessments, because controls and architecture tend to be well-defined, and the processes by which they are kept up to date will be defined and will be the primary lever for further maturation. </span></span><span style="color: #ff0000;"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Securitysense''s "Toolkit: Risk Program Maturity Assessment 1.0" provides a full process-oriented framework that includes graphical reporting of information security, privacy, regulatory compliance and business continuity</span></span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="color: #ff0000;"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">programs (see Figure 2).</span></span></span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Figure 2. Strategic Plan Contents: Current State</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Controls Architecture Process</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Data</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Infrastructure</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Applications</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>People</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPSMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">N/A</span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: xx-small;"><b>Source: Securitysense (September 2008)</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>Current State</b></span></span>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Use the framework described in the previous section to document the current state of each element contained within the framework. A brief text section describes each entry and justifies the assessment. Organizations with mature risk assessment processes may reference the current risk register to provide an assessment of existing controls.</span></span></p>\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>Desired State</b></span></span>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Document the desired state for each element within the framework. Three years is not a long time to achieve any sort of cultural change, nor for a significant reduction in the overall level of risk. Using a maturity scale from zero through five, with steps of one-half for each of the framework elements, allows sufficient granularity to show, at a strategic level, what degree of progress is being attempted. Brief text descriptions contain the background for each target value. Securitysense recommends that a change in maturity level of no more than a "2" be attempted for any framework element in a three-year period, unless exceptional resources and executive support can be assured (see Figure 3 for an example based on Figure 1).</span></span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Figure 3. Strategic Plan Contents: Target State</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Controls Architecture Process</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Data</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Infrastructure</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Applications</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>People</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPSMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">N/A</span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The desired state may also identify controls and technology areas that require change, retirement or replacement, if those have already been identified.</span></span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>Gap Analysis</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">This section describes those elements of the framework that demonstrate variation between current and desired states (see Figure 4).</span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Figure 4. Strategic Plan Contents: Gap Analysis</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Controls Architecture Process</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPSMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">+2 +1 +1</span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPSMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">+2</span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPSMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">+2 +1 +1</span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Data</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Infrastructure</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Applications</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>People</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPSMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">N/A +1</span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>Prioritization Plan</b></span></span>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">There may be a natural order to resolving many of the issues identified via the gap analysis. Part of the three-year strategic plan should be guidance to tactical planners on how to prioritize the closure of those gaps, such that any natural order is optimized. Controls determine what should be achieved, but controls become meaningful only if the governance structure is functional. The IT organization needs direction via technical architecture to be efficient, but architecture requires guidance from controls. Operational processes related to technologies that are already in place depend, to some degree, on controls (what processes and technologies are needed) and architecture (which process elements and technologies are automated). As a result, a normal prioritization plan might be to start with governance, move to controls, then architecture and finally process. But this is a "greenfield" approach, and it may not be appropriate for organizations with variable levels of maturity in the current information security program or IT organizations in general. For example, a lack of maturity in strategic processes, such as risk assessment and security communications, which are not technology-dependent may demand earlier prioritization.</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Therefore, the method by which priorities will be assigned in the tactical plans requires some</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">strategic guidance. More-granular prioritization of work should be included in tactical (annual) planning documents, and should be based on criteria such as the relative risk impact, the cost, the mean time to value and the availability of resources.</span></span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>Roles and Responsibilities</b></span></span>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">This section describes who is responsible for delivering and who is responsible for approving each strategic and tactical deliverable that results from this strategic plan. There are four sets of organizational areas that need to be mapped to deliverables and action plans:</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY">• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The security office</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY">• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Lines of business (LOBs) or federation issues (responsibilities that reside with persons or departments </span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">that are affiliated with, but not reporting to, the central information security function)</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY">• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The IT organization</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY">• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Other business areas (typically, the functions that go on in headquarters, such as legal, HR and finance)</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The security office''s responsibilities should be easily extracted from the security charter. The authority, rights and obligations of LOB management and the IT organization should have been negotiated via the governance structure prior to, or as part of, the creation of this strategic plan. These authorities, rights and obligations are typically governed via some kind of information security steering committee. Other business areas may be surprised by their inclusion or may have expressed a need for involvement on their own, typically as a response to regulatory compliance needs.</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">One approach to documenting these roles and responsibilities that has been widely accepted by organization is the use of a responsible, accountable, consulted and informed (RACI) matrix. Once all these steps have been outlined, the executive summary can be written.</span></span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;', 'Security Strategy', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '398-revision-v1', '', '', '2013-08-29 00:38:24', '2013-08-29 00:38:24', '', 398, 'http://localhost/wordpress/?p=447', 0, 'revision', '', 0);
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` (`ID`, `post_author`, `post_date`, `post_date_gmt`, `post_content`, `post_title`, `post_excerpt`, `post_status`, `comment_status`, `ping_status`, `post_password`, `post_name`, `to_ping`, `pinged`, `post_modified`, `post_modified_gmt`, `post_content_filtered`, `post_parent`, `guid`, `menu_order`, `post_type`, `post_mime_type`, `comment_count`) VALUES
(450, 1, '2013-08-29 00:40:00', '2013-08-29 00:40:00', '<style type="text/css"><!--\r\n@page { margin: 0.79in } 		P { margin-bottom: 0.08in }\r\n--></style>\r\n<table width="539" border="0">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td><a href="http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/pdf-logo.jpg"><img class="alignnone  wp-image-439" alt="pdf-logo" src="http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/pdf-logo-300x300.jpg" width="51" height="51" /></a></td>\r\n<td>\r\n<h3><strong>2009-2011 Information Security Strategy for securitysense</strong></h3>\r\n</td>\r\n<td><a href="http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2009-2011-Information-Security-Strategy-for-securitysense.pdf"><img class="alignnone  wp-image-444" alt="download_iamge" src="http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/download_iamge.jpg" width="176" height="103" /></a></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>How to develop a IT/Information security strategy for your company?</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;">An information security strategic plan should include, at a minimum, an assessment of the current state of the program, a defined target state that is achievable within the three-year strategic planning window, a gap analysis and a road map for closing the gaps.</span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><b>Key Findings</b></span>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY">• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">A consistent framework can be defined that supports risk mitigation control objectives, architecture and </span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">process objectives, but the framework varies in scale and by the maturity level of the organization it''s </span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">being applied to.</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY">• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Small or immature organizations should focus on very simple frameworks.</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY">• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Consistent, incremental improvements are much more likely to succeed than rapidly forced changes.</span></span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><b>Recommendations</b></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Develop and document an information security strategic plan and use it to generate annual tactical </span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">plans that, when executed, move the overall maturity of the security program upward.</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Develop a process to review and refine the strategic plan annually.</span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><b>ANALYSIS</b></span>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Many organizations and security officers are approaching the creation of a strategic plan for information security for the first time, or have expressed a desire to use previously unimplemented best practices in creating the next iteration of one. Although there is no industry standard for the contents of such a plan, Securitysense has recommended organizations by using a model that has proved to be an effective communication tool with the numerous interested parties (including senior management), as well as a reasonable tracking mechanism for multiyear progress reports. While the model can be applied by organizations of any size and in any industry, the details vary based on the scale of the organization and the starting maturity level of the various effected organizational units.</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The information security strategic plan should not be viewed as a stand-alone document. It should exist as one part of a set of planning documents that start with a charter and a vision statement, but that also extends beyond the strategic plan into tactical and communications plans. Each of these has a role in providing context and action ability for the strategic plan. Organizations that have an established enterprise architecture (EA) function should leverage the existing EA disciplines, processes and standards to ensure that the strategic plan for information security is aligned with the EA strategy (see "Architecting Security: Different Approaches"). Securitysense generally considers three years to be an appropriate window for strategic planning for information security. The charter and vision statements deal with longer-term directions, while the tactical and communications plans specify single-year operational considerations and projects.</span></span></p>\r\n<span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The basic layout of the strategic plan is:</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Introduction and executive summary</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Strategic plan framework description</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Current state</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Desired state</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Gap analysis</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Prioritization plan</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Roles and responsibilities</span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>Introduction and Executive Summary</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The introduction should be written first, setting the purpose and scope of the document. The executive summary should be written last, showing only the final points of the document. The combination of executive summary and introduction should not exceed three pages, and, for most organizations, should be no more than two pages.</span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>Strategic Plan Framework Description</b></span></span>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The framework is the method by which the current state, desired state and gap analysis will be documented. An appropriate framework is one that can show overview (summarized) and detail (planning) information. The summary information should be expressed graphically. Frameworks should encompass controls, architecture and process elements to be complete.</span></span></p>\r\n<span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">For organizations with an established EA practice, an enterprise information security architecture (EISA) framework (see "The Structure and Content of an Information Security Architecture Framework") that aligns with the EA framework can act as an effective overall strategic security planning framework. Frameworks for this purpose can be derived from industry standards, from Securitysense research or from a combination of the two. </span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Some sources for framework structure and contents are:</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Controls</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">International Organization for Standardization (ISO)/International Electro technical</span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Commission (IEC) 27002</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Control Objectives for Information and Related Technology (COBIT)</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">U.S. National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) SP800-53</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Architecture</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">ISO10181</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">ISO13335</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Processes</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">ISO/IEC 27001</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Information Technology Infrastructure Library (ITIL)</span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">In addition, Securitysense research can provide significant examples and guidelines for constructing such a framework (see the Recommended Reading section below). Large, mature organizations will require more-complex, detailed frameworks that focus largely on processes. Smaller or less mature organizations will find that simple frameworks suffice, and that all details can be left to the tactical planning stage, but that balanced (perhaps, not equal) attention to the three areas of controls, architecture and processes is required. An example of a simple framework for a low maturity organization might be a three-by-four grid showing the state of controls, technical architecture and processes for data, infrastructure, applications and people/behavior. Each cell in the grid can be assessed or targeted (depending on whether it is the current state or desired state framework copy) on a typical numeric maturity scale of 0 through 5, or assigned a color code of red, yellow or green (see Figure 1).</span></span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nFig 1\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Larger or more-mature organizations will tend to focus more on process assessments, because controls and architecture tend to be well-defined, and the processes by which they are kept up to date will be defined and will be the primary lever for further maturation. </span></span><span style="color: #ff0000;"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Securitysense''s "Toolkit: Risk Program Maturity Assessment 1.0" provides a full process-oriented framework that includes graphical reporting of information security, privacy, regulatory compliance and business continuity</span></span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="color: #ff0000;"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">programs (see Figure 2).</span></span></span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Figure 2. Strategic Plan Contents: Current State</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Controls Architecture Process</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Data</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Infrastructure</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Applications</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>People</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPSMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">N/A</span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: xx-small;"><b>Source: Securitysense (September 2008)</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>Current State</b></span></span>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Use the framework described in the previous section to document the current state of each element contained within the framework. A brief text section describes each entry and justifies the assessment. Organizations with mature risk assessment processes may reference the current risk register to provide an assessment of existing controls.</span></span></p>\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>Desired State</b></span></span>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Document the desired state for each element within the framework. Three years is not a long time to achieve any sort of cultural change, nor for a significant reduction in the overall level of risk. Using a maturity scale from zero through five, with steps of one-half for each of the framework elements, allows sufficient granularity to show, at a strategic level, what degree of progress is being attempted. Brief text descriptions contain the background for each target value. Securitysense recommends that a change in maturity level of no more than a "2" be attempted for any framework element in a three-year period, unless exceptional resources and executive support can be assured (see Figure 3 for an example based on Figure 1).</span></span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Figure 3. Strategic Plan Contents: Target State</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Controls Architecture Process</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Data</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Infrastructure</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Applications</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>People</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPSMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">N/A</span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The desired state may also identify controls and technology areas that require change, retirement or replacement, if those have already been identified.</span></span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>Gap Analysis</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">This section describes those elements of the framework that demonstrate variation between current and desired states (see Figure 4).</span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Figure 4. Strategic Plan Contents: Gap Analysis</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Controls Architecture Process</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPSMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">+2 +1 +1</span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPSMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">+2</span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPSMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">+2 +1 +1</span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Data</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Infrastructure</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Applications</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>People</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPSMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">N/A +1</span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>Prioritization Plan</b></span></span>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">There may be a natural order to resolving many of the issues identified via the gap analysis. Part of the three-year strategic plan should be guidance to tactical planners on how to prioritize the closure of those gaps, such that any natural order is optimized. Controls determine what should be achieved, but controls become meaningful only if the governance structure is functional. The IT organization needs direction via technical architecture to be efficient, but architecture requires guidance from controls. Operational processes related to technologies that are already in place depend, to some degree, on controls (what processes and technologies are needed) and architecture (which process elements and technologies are automated). As a result, a normal prioritization plan might be to start with governance, move to controls, then architecture and finally process. But this is a "greenfield" approach, and it may not be appropriate for organizations with variable levels of maturity in the current information security program or IT organizations in general. For example, a lack of maturity in strategic processes, such as risk assessment and security communications, which are not technology-dependent may demand earlier prioritization.</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Therefore, the method by which priorities will be assigned in the tactical plans requires some</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">strategic guidance. More-granular prioritization of work should be included in tactical (annual) planning documents, and should be based on criteria such as the relative risk impact, the cost, the mean time to value and the availability of resources.</span></span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>Roles and Responsibilities</b></span></span>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">This section describes who is responsible for delivering and who is responsible for approving each strategic and tactical deliverable that results from this strategic plan. There are four sets of organizational areas that need to be mapped to deliverables and action plans:</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY">• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The security office</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY">• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Lines of business (LOBs) or federation issues (responsibilities that reside with persons or departments </span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">that are affiliated with, but not reporting to, the central information security function)</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY">• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The IT organization</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY">• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Other business areas (typically, the functions that go on in headquarters, such as legal, HR and finance)</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The security office''s responsibilities should be easily extracted from the security charter. The authority, rights and obligations of LOB management and the IT organization should have been negotiated via the governance structure prior to, or as part of, the creation of this strategic plan. These authorities, rights and obligations are typically governed via some kind of information security steering committee. Other business areas may be surprised by their inclusion or may have expressed a need for involvement on their own, typically as a response to regulatory compliance needs.</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">One approach to documenting these roles and responsibilities that has been widely accepted by organization is the use of a responsible, accountable, consulted and informed (RACI) matrix. Once all these steps have been outlined, the executive summary can be written.</span></span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;', 'Security Strategy', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '398-revision-v1', '', '', '2013-08-29 00:40:00', '2013-08-29 00:40:00', '', 398, 'http://localhost/wordpress/?p=450', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(448, 1, '2013-08-29 00:39:20', '2013-08-29 00:39:20', '<style type="text/css"><!--\r\n@page { margin: 0.79in } 		P { margin-bottom: 0.08in }\r\n--></style>\r\n<table width="603" border="0">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td><a href="http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/pdf-logo.jpg"><img class="alignnone  wp-image-439" style="margin-right: 2px;" alt="pdf-logo" src="http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/pdf-logo-300x300.jpg" width="51" height="51" /></a></td>\r\n<td>\r\n<h3><strong>2009-2011 Information Security Strategy for securitysense</strong></h3>\r\n</td>\r\n<td><a href="http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2009-2011-Information-Security-Strategy-for-securitysense.pdf"><img class="alignnone  wp-image-444" alt="download_iamge" src="http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/download_iamge.jpg" width="176" height="103" /></a></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>How to develop a IT/Information security strategy for your company?</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;">An information security strategic plan should include, at a minimum, an assessment of the current state of the program, a defined target state that is achievable within the three-year strategic planning window, a gap analysis and a road map for closing the gaps.</span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><b>Key Findings</b></span>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY">• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">A consistent framework can be defined that supports risk mitigation control objectives, architecture and </span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">process objectives, but the framework varies in scale and by the maturity level of the organization it''s </span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">being applied to.</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY">• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Small or immature organizations should focus on very simple frameworks.</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY">• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Consistent, incremental improvements are much more likely to succeed than rapidly forced changes.</span></span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><b>Recommendations</b></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Develop and document an information security strategic plan and use it to generate annual tactical </span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">plans that, when executed, move the overall maturity of the security program upward.</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Develop a process to review and refine the strategic plan annually.</span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><b>ANALYSIS</b></span>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Many organizations and security officers are approaching the creation of a strategic plan for information security for the first time, or have expressed a desire to use previously unimplemented best practices in creating the next iteration of one. Although there is no industry standard for the contents of such a plan, Securitysense has recommended organizations by using a model that has proved to be an effective communication tool with the numerous interested parties (including senior management), as well as a reasonable tracking mechanism for multiyear progress reports. While the model can be applied by organizations of any size and in any industry, the details vary based on the scale of the organization and the starting maturity level of the various effected organizational units.</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The information security strategic plan should not be viewed as a stand-alone document. It should exist as one part of a set of planning documents that start with a charter and a vision statement, but that also extends beyond the strategic plan into tactical and communications plans. Each of these has a role in providing context and action ability for the strategic plan. Organizations that have an established enterprise architecture (EA) function should leverage the existing EA disciplines, processes and standards to ensure that the strategic plan for information security is aligned with the EA strategy (see "Architecting Security: Different Approaches"). Securitysense generally considers three years to be an appropriate window for strategic planning for information security. The charter and vision statements deal with longer-term directions, while the tactical and communications plans specify single-year operational considerations and projects.</span></span></p>\r\n<span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The basic layout of the strategic plan is:</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Introduction and executive summary</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Strategic plan framework description</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Current state</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Desired state</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Gap analysis</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Prioritization plan</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Roles and responsibilities</span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>Introduction and Executive Summary</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The introduction should be written first, setting the purpose and scope of the document. The executive summary should be written last, showing only the final points of the document. The combination of executive summary and introduction should not exceed three pages, and, for most organizations, should be no more than two pages.</span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>Strategic Plan Framework Description</b></span></span>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The framework is the method by which the current state, desired state and gap analysis will be documented. An appropriate framework is one that can show overview (summarized) and detail (planning) information. The summary information should be expressed graphically. Frameworks should encompass controls, architecture and process elements to be complete.</span></span></p>\r\n<span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">For organizations with an established EA practice, an enterprise information security architecture (EISA) framework (see "The Structure and Content of an Information Security Architecture Framework") that aligns with the EA framework can act as an effective overall strategic security planning framework. Frameworks for this purpose can be derived from industry standards, from Securitysense research or from a combination of the two. </span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Some sources for framework structure and contents are:</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Controls</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">International Organization for Standardization (ISO)/International Electro technical</span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Commission (IEC) 27002</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Control Objectives for Information and Related Technology (COBIT)</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">U.S. National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) SP800-53</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Architecture</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">ISO10181</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">ISO13335</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Processes</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">ISO/IEC 27001</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Information Technology Infrastructure Library (ITIL)</span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">In addition, Securitysense research can provide significant examples and guidelines for constructing such a framework (see the Recommended Reading section below). Large, mature organizations will require more-complex, detailed frameworks that focus largely on processes. Smaller or less mature organizations will find that simple frameworks suffice, and that all details can be left to the tactical planning stage, but that balanced (perhaps, not equal) attention to the three areas of controls, architecture and processes is required. An example of a simple framework for a low maturity organization might be a three-by-four grid showing the state of controls, technical architecture and processes for data, infrastructure, applications and people/behavior. Each cell in the grid can be assessed or targeted (depending on whether it is the current state or desired state framework copy) on a typical numeric maturity scale of 0 through 5, or assigned a color code of red, yellow or green (see Figure 1).</span></span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nFig 1\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Larger or more-mature organizations will tend to focus more on process assessments, because controls and architecture tend to be well-defined, and the processes by which they are kept up to date will be defined and will be the primary lever for further maturation. </span></span><span style="color: #ff0000;"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Securitysense''s "Toolkit: Risk Program Maturity Assessment 1.0" provides a full process-oriented framework that includes graphical reporting of information security, privacy, regulatory compliance and business continuity</span></span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="color: #ff0000;"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">programs (see Figure 2).</span></span></span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Figure 2. Strategic Plan Contents: Current State</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Controls Architecture Process</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Data</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Infrastructure</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Applications</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>People</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPSMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">N/A</span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: xx-small;"><b>Source: Securitysense (September 2008)</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>Current State</b></span></span>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Use the framework described in the previous section to document the current state of each element contained within the framework. A brief text section describes each entry and justifies the assessment. Organizations with mature risk assessment processes may reference the current risk register to provide an assessment of existing controls.</span></span></p>\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>Desired State</b></span></span>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Document the desired state for each element within the framework. Three years is not a long time to achieve any sort of cultural change, nor for a significant reduction in the overall level of risk. Using a maturity scale from zero through five, with steps of one-half for each of the framework elements, allows sufficient granularity to show, at a strategic level, what degree of progress is being attempted. Brief text descriptions contain the background for each target value. Securitysense recommends that a change in maturity level of no more than a "2" be attempted for any framework element in a three-year period, unless exceptional resources and executive support can be assured (see Figure 3 for an example based on Figure 1).</span></span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Figure 3. Strategic Plan Contents: Target State</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Controls Architecture Process</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Data</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Infrastructure</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Applications</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>People</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPSMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">N/A</span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The desired state may also identify controls and technology areas that require change, retirement or replacement, if those have already been identified.</span></span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>Gap Analysis</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">This section describes those elements of the framework that demonstrate variation between current and desired states (see Figure 4).</span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Figure 4. Strategic Plan Contents: Gap Analysis</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Controls Architecture Process</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPSMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">+2 +1 +1</span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPSMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">+2</span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPSMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">+2 +1 +1</span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Data</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Infrastructure</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Applications</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>People</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPSMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">N/A +1</span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>Prioritization Plan</b></span></span>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">There may be a natural order to resolving many of the issues identified via the gap analysis. Part of the three-year strategic plan should be guidance to tactical planners on how to prioritize the closure of those gaps, such that any natural order is optimized. Controls determine what should be achieved, but controls become meaningful only if the governance structure is functional. The IT organization needs direction via technical architecture to be efficient, but architecture requires guidance from controls. Operational processes related to technologies that are already in place depend, to some degree, on controls (what processes and technologies are needed) and architecture (which process elements and technologies are automated). As a result, a normal prioritization plan might be to start with governance, move to controls, then architecture and finally process. But this is a "greenfield" approach, and it may not be appropriate for organizations with variable levels of maturity in the current information security program or IT organizations in general. For example, a lack of maturity in strategic processes, such as risk assessment and security communications, which are not technology-dependent may demand earlier prioritization.</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Therefore, the method by which priorities will be assigned in the tactical plans requires some</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">strategic guidance. More-granular prioritization of work should be included in tactical (annual) planning documents, and should be based on criteria such as the relative risk impact, the cost, the mean time to value and the availability of resources.</span></span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>Roles and Responsibilities</b></span></span>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">This section describes who is responsible for delivering and who is responsible for approving each strategic and tactical deliverable that results from this strategic plan. There are four sets of organizational areas that need to be mapped to deliverables and action plans:</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY">• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The security office</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY">• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Lines of business (LOBs) or federation issues (responsibilities that reside with persons or departments </span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">that are affiliated with, but not reporting to, the central information security function)</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY">• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The IT organization</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY">• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Other business areas (typically, the functions that go on in headquarters, such as legal, HR and finance)</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The security office''s responsibilities should be easily extracted from the security charter. The authority, rights and obligations of LOB management and the IT organization should have been negotiated via the governance structure prior to, or as part of, the creation of this strategic plan. These authorities, rights and obligations are typically governed via some kind of information security steering committee. Other business areas may be surprised by their inclusion or may have expressed a need for involvement on their own, typically as a response to regulatory compliance needs.</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">One approach to documenting these roles and responsibilities that has been widely accepted by organization is the use of a responsible, accountable, consulted and informed (RACI) matrix. Once all these steps have been outlined, the executive summary can be written.</span></span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;', 'Security Strategy', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '398-revision-v1', '', '', '2013-08-29 00:39:20', '2013-08-29 00:39:20', '', 398, 'http://localhost/wordpress/?p=448', 0, 'revision', '', 0);
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` (`ID`, `post_author`, `post_date`, `post_date_gmt`, `post_content`, `post_title`, `post_excerpt`, `post_status`, `comment_status`, `ping_status`, `post_password`, `post_name`, `to_ping`, `pinged`, `post_modified`, `post_modified_gmt`, `post_content_filtered`, `post_parent`, `guid`, `menu_order`, `post_type`, `post_mime_type`, `comment_count`) VALUES
(451, 1, '2013-08-29 00:40:17', '2013-08-29 00:40:17', '<style type="text/css"><!--\r\n@page { margin: 0.79in } 		P { margin-bottom: 0.08in }\r\n--></style>\r\n<table width="498" border="0">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td><a href="http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/pdf-logo.jpg"><img class="alignnone  wp-image-439" alt="pdf-logo" src="http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/pdf-logo-300x300.jpg" width="51" height="51" /></a></td>\r\n<td>\r\n<h3><strong>2009-2011 Information Security Strategy for securitysense</strong></h3>\r\n</td>\r\n<td><a href="http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2009-2011-Information-Security-Strategy-for-securitysense.pdf"><img class="alignnone  wp-image-444" alt="download_iamge" src="http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/download_iamge.jpg" width="176" height="103" /></a></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>How to develop a IT/Information security strategy for your company?</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;">An information security strategic plan should include, at a minimum, an assessment of the current state of the program, a defined target state that is achievable within the three-year strategic planning window, a gap analysis and a road map for closing the gaps.</span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><b>Key Findings</b></span>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY">• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">A consistent framework can be defined that supports risk mitigation control objectives, architecture and </span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">process objectives, but the framework varies in scale and by the maturity level of the organization it''s </span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">being applied to.</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY">• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Small or immature organizations should focus on very simple frameworks.</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY">• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Consistent, incremental improvements are much more likely to succeed than rapidly forced changes.</span></span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><b>Recommendations</b></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Develop and document an information security strategic plan and use it to generate annual tactical </span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">plans that, when executed, move the overall maturity of the security program upward.</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Develop a process to review and refine the strategic plan annually.</span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><b>ANALYSIS</b></span>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Many organizations and security officers are approaching the creation of a strategic plan for information security for the first time, or have expressed a desire to use previously unimplemented best practices in creating the next iteration of one. Although there is no industry standard for the contents of such a plan, Securitysense has recommended organizations by using a model that has proved to be an effective communication tool with the numerous interested parties (including senior management), as well as a reasonable tracking mechanism for multiyear progress reports. While the model can be applied by organizations of any size and in any industry, the details vary based on the scale of the organization and the starting maturity level of the various effected organizational units.</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The information security strategic plan should not be viewed as a stand-alone document. It should exist as one part of a set of planning documents that start with a charter and a vision statement, but that also extends beyond the strategic plan into tactical and communications plans. Each of these has a role in providing context and action ability for the strategic plan. Organizations that have an established enterprise architecture (EA) function should leverage the existing EA disciplines, processes and standards to ensure that the strategic plan for information security is aligned with the EA strategy (see "Architecting Security: Different Approaches"). Securitysense generally considers three years to be an appropriate window for strategic planning for information security. The charter and vision statements deal with longer-term directions, while the tactical and communications plans specify single-year operational considerations and projects.</span></span></p>\r\n<span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The basic layout of the strategic plan is:</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Introduction and executive summary</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Strategic plan framework description</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Current state</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Desired state</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Gap analysis</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Prioritization plan</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Roles and responsibilities</span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>Introduction and Executive Summary</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The introduction should be written first, setting the purpose and scope of the document. The executive summary should be written last, showing only the final points of the document. The combination of executive summary and introduction should not exceed three pages, and, for most organizations, should be no more than two pages.</span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>Strategic Plan Framework Description</b></span></span>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The framework is the method by which the current state, desired state and gap analysis will be documented. An appropriate framework is one that can show overview (summarized) and detail (planning) information. The summary information should be expressed graphically. Frameworks should encompass controls, architecture and process elements to be complete.</span></span></p>\r\n<span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">For organizations with an established EA practice, an enterprise information security architecture (EISA) framework (see "The Structure and Content of an Information Security Architecture Framework") that aligns with the EA framework can act as an effective overall strategic security planning framework. Frameworks for this purpose can be derived from industry standards, from Securitysense research or from a combination of the two. </span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Some sources for framework structure and contents are:</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Controls</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">International Organization for Standardization (ISO)/International Electro technical</span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Commission (IEC) 27002</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Control Objectives for Information and Related Technology (COBIT)</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">U.S. National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) SP800-53</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Architecture</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">ISO10181</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">ISO13335</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Processes</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">ISO/IEC 27001</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Information Technology Infrastructure Library (ITIL)</span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">In addition, Securitysense research can provide significant examples and guidelines for constructing such a framework (see the Recommended Reading section below). Large, mature organizations will require more-complex, detailed frameworks that focus largely on processes. Smaller or less mature organizations will find that simple frameworks suffice, and that all details can be left to the tactical planning stage, but that balanced (perhaps, not equal) attention to the three areas of controls, architecture and processes is required. An example of a simple framework for a low maturity organization might be a three-by-four grid showing the state of controls, technical architecture and processes for data, infrastructure, applications and people/behavior. Each cell in the grid can be assessed or targeted (depending on whether it is the current state or desired state framework copy) on a typical numeric maturity scale of 0 through 5, or assigned a color code of red, yellow or green (see Figure 1).</span></span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nFig 1\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Larger or more-mature organizations will tend to focus more on process assessments, because controls and architecture tend to be well-defined, and the processes by which they are kept up to date will be defined and will be the primary lever for further maturation. </span></span><span style="color: #ff0000;"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Securitysense''s "Toolkit: Risk Program Maturity Assessment 1.0" provides a full process-oriented framework that includes graphical reporting of information security, privacy, regulatory compliance and business continuity</span></span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="color: #ff0000;"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">programs (see Figure 2).</span></span></span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Figure 2. Strategic Plan Contents: Current State</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Controls Architecture Process</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Data</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Infrastructure</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Applications</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>People</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPSMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">N/A</span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: xx-small;"><b>Source: Securitysense (September 2008)</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>Current State</b></span></span>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Use the framework described in the previous section to document the current state of each element contained within the framework. A brief text section describes each entry and justifies the assessment. Organizations with mature risk assessment processes may reference the current risk register to provide an assessment of existing controls.</span></span></p>\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>Desired State</b></span></span>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Document the desired state for each element within the framework. Three years is not a long time to achieve any sort of cultural change, nor for a significant reduction in the overall level of risk. Using a maturity scale from zero through five, with steps of one-half for each of the framework elements, allows sufficient granularity to show, at a strategic level, what degree of progress is being attempted. Brief text descriptions contain the background for each target value. Securitysense recommends that a change in maturity level of no more than a "2" be attempted for any framework element in a three-year period, unless exceptional resources and executive support can be assured (see Figure 3 for an example based on Figure 1).</span></span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Figure 3. Strategic Plan Contents: Target State</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Controls Architecture Process</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Data</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Infrastructure</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Applications</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>People</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPSMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">N/A</span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The desired state may also identify controls and technology areas that require change, retirement or replacement, if those have already been identified.</span></span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>Gap Analysis</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">This section describes those elements of the framework that demonstrate variation between current and desired states (see Figure 4).</span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Figure 4. Strategic Plan Contents: Gap Analysis</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Controls Architecture Process</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPSMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">+2 +1 +1</span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPSMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">+2</span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPSMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">+2 +1 +1</span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Data</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Infrastructure</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Applications</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>People</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPSMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">N/A +1</span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>Prioritization Plan</b></span></span>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">There may be a natural order to resolving many of the issues identified via the gap analysis. Part of the three-year strategic plan should be guidance to tactical planners on how to prioritize the closure of those gaps, such that any natural order is optimized. Controls determine what should be achieved, but controls become meaningful only if the governance structure is functional. The IT organization needs direction via technical architecture to be efficient, but architecture requires guidance from controls. Operational processes related to technologies that are already in place depend, to some degree, on controls (what processes and technologies are needed) and architecture (which process elements and technologies are automated). As a result, a normal prioritization plan might be to start with governance, move to controls, then architecture and finally process. But this is a "greenfield" approach, and it may not be appropriate for organizations with variable levels of maturity in the current information security program or IT organizations in general. For example, a lack of maturity in strategic processes, such as risk assessment and security communications, which are not technology-dependent may demand earlier prioritization.</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Therefore, the method by which priorities will be assigned in the tactical plans requires some</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">strategic guidance. More-granular prioritization of work should be included in tactical (annual) planning documents, and should be based on criteria such as the relative risk impact, the cost, the mean time to value and the availability of resources.</span></span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>Roles and Responsibilities</b></span></span>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">This section describes who is responsible for delivering and who is responsible for approving each strategic and tactical deliverable that results from this strategic plan. There are four sets of organizational areas that need to be mapped to deliverables and action plans:</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY">• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The security office</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY">• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Lines of business (LOBs) or federation issues (responsibilities that reside with persons or departments </span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">that are affiliated with, but not reporting to, the central information security function)</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY">• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The IT organization</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY">• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Other business areas (typically, the functions that go on in headquarters, such as legal, HR and finance)</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The security office''s responsibilities should be easily extracted from the security charter. The authority, rights and obligations of LOB management and the IT organization should have been negotiated via the governance structure prior to, or as part of, the creation of this strategic plan. These authorities, rights and obligations are typically governed via some kind of information security steering committee. Other business areas may be surprised by their inclusion or may have expressed a need for involvement on their own, typically as a response to regulatory compliance needs.</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">One approach to documenting these roles and responsibilities that has been widely accepted by organization is the use of a responsible, accountable, consulted and informed (RACI) matrix. Once all these steps have been outlined, the executive summary can be written.</span></span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;', 'Security Strategy', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '398-revision-v1', '', '', '2013-08-29 00:40:17', '2013-08-29 00:40:17', '', 398, 'http://localhost/wordpress/?p=451', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(452, 1, '2013-08-29 00:41:49', '2013-08-29 00:41:49', '<style type="text/css"><!--\r\n@page { margin: 0.79in } 		P { margin-bottom: 0.08in }\r\n--></style>\r\n<table width="498" border="0">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td><a href="http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/pdf-logo.jpg"><img class="wp-image-439 alignleft" alt="pdf-logo" src="http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/pdf-logo-300x300.jpg" width="51" height="51" /></a></td>\r\n<td>\r\n<h3><strong>2009-2011 Information Security Strategy for securitysense</strong></h3>\r\n</td>\r\n<td><a href="http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2009-2011-Information-Security-Strategy-for-securitysense.pdf"><img class="wp-image-444 alignleft" alt="download_iamge" src="http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/download_iamge.jpg" width="176" height="103" /></a></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>How to develop a IT/Information security strategy for your company?</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;">An information security strategic plan should include, at a minimum, an assessment of the current state of the program, a defined target state that is achievable within the three-year strategic planning window, a gap analysis and a road map for closing the gaps.</span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><b>Key Findings</b></span>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY">• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">A consistent framework can be defined that supports risk mitigation control objectives, architecture and </span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">process objectives, but the framework varies in scale and by the maturity level of the organization it''s </span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">being applied to.</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY">• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Small or immature organizations should focus on very simple frameworks.</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY">• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Consistent, incremental improvements are much more likely to succeed than rapidly forced changes.</span></span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><b>Recommendations</b></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Develop and document an information security strategic plan and use it to generate annual tactical </span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">plans that, when executed, move the overall maturity of the security program upward.</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Develop a process to review and refine the strategic plan annually.</span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><b>ANALYSIS</b></span>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Many organizations and security officers are approaching the creation of a strategic plan for information security for the first time, or have expressed a desire to use previously unimplemented best practices in creating the next iteration of one. Although there is no industry standard for the contents of such a plan, Securitysense has recommended organizations by using a model that has proved to be an effective communication tool with the numerous interested parties (including senior management), as well as a reasonable tracking mechanism for multiyear progress reports. While the model can be applied by organizations of any size and in any industry, the details vary based on the scale of the organization and the starting maturity level of the various effected organizational units.</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The information security strategic plan should not be viewed as a stand-alone document. It should exist as one part of a set of planning documents that start with a charter and a vision statement, but that also extends beyond the strategic plan into tactical and communications plans. Each of these has a role in providing context and action ability for the strategic plan. Organizations that have an established enterprise architecture (EA) function should leverage the existing EA disciplines, processes and standards to ensure that the strategic plan for information security is aligned with the EA strategy (see "Architecting Security: Different Approaches"). Securitysense generally considers three years to be an appropriate window for strategic planning for information security. The charter and vision statements deal with longer-term directions, while the tactical and communications plans specify single-year operational considerations and projects.</span></span></p>\r\n<span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The basic layout of the strategic plan is:</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Introduction and executive summary</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Strategic plan framework description</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Current state</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Desired state</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Gap analysis</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Prioritization plan</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Roles and responsibilities</span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>Introduction and Executive Summary</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The introduction should be written first, setting the purpose and scope of the document. The executive summary should be written last, showing only the final points of the document. The combination of executive summary and introduction should not exceed three pages, and, for most organizations, should be no more than two pages.</span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>Strategic Plan Framework Description</b></span></span>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The framework is the method by which the current state, desired state and gap analysis will be documented. An appropriate framework is one that can show overview (summarized) and detail (planning) information. The summary information should be expressed graphically. Frameworks should encompass controls, architecture and process elements to be complete.</span></span></p>\r\n<span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">For organizations with an established EA practice, an enterprise information security architecture (EISA) framework (see "The Structure and Content of an Information Security Architecture Framework") that aligns with the EA framework can act as an effective overall strategic security planning framework. Frameworks for this purpose can be derived from industry standards, from Securitysense research or from a combination of the two. </span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Some sources for framework structure and contents are:</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Controls</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">International Organization for Standardization (ISO)/International Electro technical</span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Commission (IEC) 27002</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Control Objectives for Information and Related Technology (COBIT)</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">U.S. National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) SP800-53</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Architecture</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">ISO10181</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">ISO13335</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Processes</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">ISO/IEC 27001</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Information Technology Infrastructure Library (ITIL)</span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">In addition, Securitysense research can provide significant examples and guidelines for constructing such a framework (see the Recommended Reading section below). Large, mature organizations will require more-complex, detailed frameworks that focus largely on processes. Smaller or less mature organizations will find that simple frameworks suffice, and that all details can be left to the tactical planning stage, but that balanced (perhaps, not equal) attention to the three areas of controls, architecture and processes is required. An example of a simple framework for a low maturity organization might be a three-by-four grid showing the state of controls, technical architecture and processes for data, infrastructure, applications and people/behavior. Each cell in the grid can be assessed or targeted (depending on whether it is the current state or desired state framework copy) on a typical numeric maturity scale of 0 through 5, or assigned a color code of red, yellow or green (see Figure 1).</span></span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nFig 1\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Larger or more-mature organizations will tend to focus more on process assessments, because controls and architecture tend to be well-defined, and the processes by which they are kept up to date will be defined and will be the primary lever for further maturation. </span></span><span style="color: #ff0000;"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Securitysense''s "Toolkit: Risk Program Maturity Assessment 1.0" provides a full process-oriented framework that includes graphical reporting of information security, privacy, regulatory compliance and business continuity</span></span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="color: #ff0000;"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">programs (see Figure 2).</span></span></span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Figure 2. Strategic Plan Contents: Current State</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Controls Architecture Process</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Data</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Infrastructure</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Applications</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>People</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPSMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">N/A</span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: xx-small;"><b>Source: Securitysense (September 2008)</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>Current State</b></span></span>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Use the framework described in the previous section to document the current state of each element contained within the framework. A brief text section describes each entry and justifies the assessment. Organizations with mature risk assessment processes may reference the current risk register to provide an assessment of existing controls.</span></span></p>\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>Desired State</b></span></span>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Document the desired state for each element within the framework. Three years is not a long time to achieve any sort of cultural change, nor for a significant reduction in the overall level of risk. Using a maturity scale from zero through five, with steps of one-half for each of the framework elements, allows sufficient granularity to show, at a strategic level, what degree of progress is being attempted. Brief text descriptions contain the background for each target value. Securitysense recommends that a change in maturity level of no more than a "2" be attempted for any framework element in a three-year period, unless exceptional resources and executive support can be assured (see Figure 3 for an example based on Figure 1).</span></span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Figure 3. Strategic Plan Contents: Target State</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Controls Architecture Process</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Data</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Infrastructure</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Applications</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>People</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPSMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">N/A</span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The desired state may also identify controls and technology areas that require change, retirement or replacement, if those have already been identified.</span></span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>Gap Analysis</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">This section describes those elements of the framework that demonstrate variation between current and desired states (see Figure 4).</span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Figure 4. Strategic Plan Contents: Gap Analysis</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Controls Architecture Process</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPSMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">+2 +1 +1</span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPSMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">+2</span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPSMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">+2 +1 +1</span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Data</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Infrastructure</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Applications</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>People</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPSMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">N/A +1</span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>Prioritization Plan</b></span></span>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">There may be a natural order to resolving many of the issues identified via the gap analysis. Part of the three-year strategic plan should be guidance to tactical planners on how to prioritize the closure of those gaps, such that any natural order is optimized. Controls determine what should be achieved, but controls become meaningful only if the governance structure is functional. The IT organization needs direction via technical architecture to be efficient, but architecture requires guidance from controls. Operational processes related to technologies that are already in place depend, to some degree, on controls (what processes and technologies are needed) and architecture (which process elements and technologies are automated). As a result, a normal prioritization plan might be to start with governance, move to controls, then architecture and finally process. But this is a "greenfield" approach, and it may not be appropriate for organizations with variable levels of maturity in the current information security program or IT organizations in general. For example, a lack of maturity in strategic processes, such as risk assessment and security communications, which are not technology-dependent may demand earlier prioritization.</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Therefore, the method by which priorities will be assigned in the tactical plans requires some</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">strategic guidance. More-granular prioritization of work should be included in tactical (annual) planning documents, and should be based on criteria such as the relative risk impact, the cost, the mean time to value and the availability of resources.</span></span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>Roles and Responsibilities</b></span></span>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">This section describes who is responsible for delivering and who is responsible for approving each strategic and tactical deliverable that results from this strategic plan. There are four sets of organizational areas that need to be mapped to deliverables and action plans:</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY">• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The security office</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY">• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Lines of business (LOBs) or federation issues (responsibilities that reside with persons or departments </span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">that are affiliated with, but not reporting to, the central information security function)</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY">• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The IT organization</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY">• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Other business areas (typically, the functions that go on in headquarters, such as legal, HR and finance)</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The security office''s responsibilities should be easily extracted from the security charter. The authority, rights and obligations of LOB management and the IT organization should have been negotiated via the governance structure prior to, or as part of, the creation of this strategic plan. These authorities, rights and obligations are typically governed via some kind of information security steering committee. Other business areas may be surprised by their inclusion or may have expressed a need for involvement on their own, typically as a response to regulatory compliance needs.</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">One approach to documenting these roles and responsibilities that has been widely accepted by organization is the use of a responsible, accountable, consulted and informed (RACI) matrix. Once all these steps have been outlined, the executive summary can be written.</span></span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;', 'Security Strategy', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '398-revision-v1', '', '', '2013-08-29 00:41:49', '2013-08-29 00:41:49', '', 398, 'http://localhost/wordpress/?p=452', 0, 'revision', '', 0);
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` (`ID`, `post_author`, `post_date`, `post_date_gmt`, `post_content`, `post_title`, `post_excerpt`, `post_status`, `comment_status`, `ping_status`, `post_password`, `post_name`, `to_ping`, `pinged`, `post_modified`, `post_modified_gmt`, `post_content_filtered`, `post_parent`, `guid`, `menu_order`, `post_type`, `post_mime_type`, `comment_count`) VALUES
(454, 1, '2013-08-29 00:54:18', '2013-08-29 00:54:18', '<style type="text/css"><!--\r\n@page { margin: 0.79in } 		P { margin-bottom: 0.08in }\r\n--></style>\r\n<table width="498" border="0">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td><a><img class="wp-image-439 alignleft" alt="pdf-logo" src="http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/pdf-logo.jpg" width="51" height="51" /></a></td>\r\n<td>\r\n<h3 style="text-align: left;"><strong>2009-2011 Information Security Strategy for securitysense</strong></h3>\r\n</td>\r\n<td><a href="http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2009-2011-Information-Security-Strategy-for-securitysense.pdf"><img class="wp-image-444 alignleft" alt="download_iamge" src="http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/download_iamge.jpg" width="176" height="103" /></a></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>How to develop a IT/Information security strategy for your company?</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;">An information security strategic plan should include, at a minimum, an assessment of the current state of the program, a defined target state that is achievable within the three-year strategic planning window, a gap analysis and a road map for closing the gaps.</span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><b>Key Findings</b></span>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY">• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">A consistent framework can be defined that supports risk mitigation control objectives, architecture and </span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">process objectives, but the framework varies in scale and by the maturity level of the organization it''s </span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">being applied to.</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY">• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Small or immature organizations should focus on very simple frameworks.</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY">• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Consistent, incremental improvements are much more likely to succeed than rapidly forced changes.</span></span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><b>Recommendations</b></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Develop and document an information security strategic plan and use it to generate annual tactical </span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">plans that, when executed, move the overall maturity of the security program upward.</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Develop a process to review and refine the strategic plan annually.</span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><b>ANALYSIS</b></span>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Many organizations and security officers are approaching the creation of a strategic plan for information security for the first time, or have expressed a desire to use previously unimplemented best practices in creating the next iteration of one. Although there is no industry standard for the contents of such a plan, Securitysense has recommended organizations by using a model that has proved to be an effective communication tool with the numerous interested parties (including senior management), as well as a reasonable tracking mechanism for multiyear progress reports. While the model can be applied by organizations of any size and in any industry, the details vary based on the scale of the organization and the starting maturity level of the various effected organizational units.</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The information security strategic plan should not be viewed as a stand-alone document. It should exist as one part of a set of planning documents that start with a charter and a vision statement, but that also extends beyond the strategic plan into tactical and communications plans. Each of these has a role in providing context and action ability for the strategic plan. Organizations that have an established enterprise architecture (EA) function should leverage the existing EA disciplines, processes and standards to ensure that the strategic plan for information security is aligned with the EA strategy (see "Architecting Security: Different Approaches"). Securitysense generally considers three years to be an appropriate window for strategic planning for information security. The charter and vision statements deal with longer-term directions, while the tactical and communications plans specify single-year operational considerations and projects.</span></span></p>\r\n<span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The basic layout of the strategic plan is:</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Introduction and executive summary</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Strategic plan framework description</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Current state</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Desired state</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Gap analysis</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Prioritization plan</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Roles and responsibilities</span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>Introduction and Executive Summary</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The introduction should be written first, setting the purpose and scope of the document. The executive summary should be written last, showing only the final points of the document. The combination of executive summary and introduction should not exceed three pages, and, for most organizations, should be no more than two pages.</span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>Strategic Plan Framework Description</b></span></span>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The framework is the method by which the current state, desired state and gap analysis will be documented. An appropriate framework is one that can show overview (summarized) and detail (planning) information. The summary information should be expressed graphically. Frameworks should encompass controls, architecture and process elements to be complete.</span></span></p>\r\n<span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">For organizations with an established EA practice, an enterprise information security architecture (EISA) framework (see "The Structure and Content of an Information Security Architecture Framework") that aligns with the EA framework can act as an effective overall strategic security planning framework. Frameworks for this purpose can be derived from industry standards, from Securitysense research or from a combination of the two. </span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Some sources for framework structure and contents are:</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Controls</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">International Organization for Standardization (ISO)/International Electro technical</span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Commission (IEC) 27002</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Control Objectives for Information and Related Technology (COBIT)</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">U.S. National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) SP800-53</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Architecture</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">ISO10181</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">ISO13335</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Processes</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">ISO/IEC 27001</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Information Technology Infrastructure Library (ITIL)</span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">In addition, Securitysense research can provide significant examples and guidelines for constructing such a framework (see the Recommended Reading section below). Large, mature organizations will require more-complex, detailed frameworks that focus largely on processes. Smaller or less mature organizations will find that simple frameworks suffice, and that all details can be left to the tactical planning stage, but that balanced (perhaps, not equal) attention to the three areas of controls, architecture and processes is required. An example of a simple framework for a low maturity organization might be a three-by-four grid showing the state of controls, technical architecture and processes for data, infrastructure, applications and people/behavior. Each cell in the grid can be assessed or targeted (depending on whether it is the current state or desired state framework copy) on a typical numeric maturity scale of 0 through 5, or assigned a color code of red, yellow or green (see Figure 1).</span></span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nFig 1\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Larger or more-mature organizations will tend to focus more on process assessments, because controls and architecture tend to be well-defined, and the processes by which they are kept up to date will be defined and will be the primary lever for further maturation. </span></span><span style="color: #ff0000;"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Securitysense''s "Toolkit: Risk Program Maturity Assessment 1.0" provides a full process-oriented framework that includes graphical reporting of information security, privacy, regulatory compliance and business continuity</span></span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="color: #ff0000;"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">programs (see Figure 2).</span></span></span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Figure 2. Strategic Plan Contents: Current State</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Controls Architecture Process</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Data</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Infrastructure</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Applications</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>People</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPSMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">N/A</span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: xx-small;"><b>Source: Securitysense (September 2008)</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>Current State</b></span></span>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Use the framework described in the previous section to document the current state of each element contained within the framework. A brief text section describes each entry and justifies the assessment. Organizations with mature risk assessment processes may reference the current risk register to provide an assessment of existing controls.</span></span></p>\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>Desired State</b></span></span>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Document the desired state for each element within the framework. Three years is not a long time to achieve any sort of cultural change, nor for a significant reduction in the overall level of risk. Using a maturity scale from zero through five, with steps of one-half for each of the framework elements, allows sufficient granularity to show, at a strategic level, what degree of progress is being attempted. Brief text descriptions contain the background for each target value. Securitysense recommends that a change in maturity level of no more than a "2" be attempted for any framework element in a three-year period, unless exceptional resources and executive support can be assured (see Figure 3 for an example based on Figure 1).</span></span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Figure 3. Strategic Plan Contents: Target State</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Controls Architecture Process</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Data</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Infrastructure</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Applications</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>People</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPSMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">N/A</span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The desired state may also identify controls and technology areas that require change, retirement or replacement, if those have already been identified.</span></span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>Gap Analysis</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">This section describes those elements of the framework that demonstrate variation between current and desired states (see Figure 4).</span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Figure 4. Strategic Plan Contents: Gap Analysis</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Controls Architecture Process</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPSMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">+2 +1 +1</span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPSMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">+2</span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPSMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">+2 +1 +1</span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Data</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Infrastructure</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Applications</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>People</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPSMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">N/A +1</span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>Prioritization Plan</b></span></span>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">There may be a natural order to resolving many of the issues identified via the gap analysis. Part of the three-year strategic plan should be guidance to tactical planners on how to prioritize the closure of those gaps, such that any natural order is optimized. Controls determine what should be achieved, but controls become meaningful only if the governance structure is functional. The IT organization needs direction via technical architecture to be efficient, but architecture requires guidance from controls. Operational processes related to technologies that are already in place depend, to some degree, on controls (what processes and technologies are needed) and architecture (which process elements and technologies are automated). As a result, a normal prioritization plan might be to start with governance, move to controls, then architecture and finally process. But this is a "greenfield" approach, and it may not be appropriate for organizations with variable levels of maturity in the current information security program or IT organizations in general. For example, a lack of maturity in strategic processes, such as risk assessment and security communications, which are not technology-dependent may demand earlier prioritization.</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Therefore, the method by which priorities will be assigned in the tactical plans requires some</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">strategic guidance. More-granular prioritization of work should be included in tactical (annual) planning documents, and should be based on criteria such as the relative risk impact, the cost, the mean time to value and the availability of resources.</span></span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>Roles and Responsibilities</b></span></span>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">This section describes who is responsible for delivering and who is responsible for approving each strategic and tactical deliverable that results from this strategic plan. There are four sets of organizational areas that need to be mapped to deliverables and action plans:</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY">• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The security office</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY">• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Lines of business (LOBs) or federation issues (responsibilities that reside with persons or departments </span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">that are affiliated with, but not reporting to, the central information security function)</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY">• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The IT organization</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY">• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Other business areas (typically, the functions that go on in headquarters, such as legal, HR and finance)</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The security office''s responsibilities should be easily extracted from the security charter. The authority, rights and obligations of LOB management and the IT organization should have been negotiated via the governance structure prior to, or as part of, the creation of this strategic plan. These authorities, rights and obligations are typically governed via some kind of information security steering committee. Other business areas may be surprised by their inclusion or may have expressed a need for involvement on their own, typically as a response to regulatory compliance needs.</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">One approach to documenting these roles and responsibilities that has been widely accepted by organization is the use of a responsible, accountable, consulted and informed (RACI) matrix. Once all these steps have been outlined, the executive summary can be written.</span></span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;', 'Security Strategy', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '398-revision-v1', '', '', '2013-08-29 00:54:18', '2013-08-29 00:54:18', '', 398, 'http://localhost/wordpress/?p=454', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(456, 1, '2013-08-29 01:06:23', '2013-08-29 01:06:23', '<style type="text/css"><!--\r\n@page { margin: 0.79in } 		P { margin-bottom: 0.08in }\r\n--></style>\r\n<table width="498" border="0">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td><a><img class="wp-image-439 alignleft" alt="pdf-logo" src="http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/pdf-logo.jpg" width="51" height="51" /></a></td>\r\n<td>\r\n<h3 style="text-align: left;"><strong>2009-2011 Information Security Strategy for securitysense</strong></h3>\r\n</td>\r\n<td><a href="http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2009-2011-Information-Security-Strategy-for-securitysense.pdf"><img class="wp-image-444 alignleft" alt="download_iamge" src="http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/download_iamge.jpg" width="176" height="103" /></a></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>How to develop a IT/Information security strategy for your company?</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;">An information security strategic plan should include, at a minimum, an assessment of the current state of the program, a defined target state that is achievable within the three-year strategic planning window, a gap analysis and a road map for closing the gaps.</span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><b>Key Findings</b></span>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY">• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">A consistent framework can be defined that supports risk mitigation control objectives, architecture and </span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">process objectives, but the framework varies in scale and by the maturity level of the organization it''s </span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">being applied to.</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY">• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Small or immature organizations should focus on very simple frameworks.</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY">• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Consistent, incremental improvements are much more likely to succeed than rapidly forced changes.</span></span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><b>Recommendations</b></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Develop and document an information security strategic plan and use it to generate annual tactical </span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">plans that, when executed, move the overall maturity of the security program upward.</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Develop a process to review and refine the strategic plan annually.</span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><b>ANALYSIS</b></span>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Many organizations and security officers are approaching the creation of a strategic plan for information security for the first time, or have expressed a desire to use previously unimplemented best practices in creating the next iteration of one. Although there is no industry standard for the contents of such a plan, Securitysense has recommended organizations by using a model that has proved to be an effective communication tool with the numerous interested parties (including senior management), as well as a reasonable tracking mechanism for multiyear progress reports. While the model can be applied by organizations of any size and in any industry, the details vary based on the scale of the organization and the starting maturity level of the various effected organizational units.</span></span></p>\r\n<!--nextpage-->\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The information security strategic plan should not be viewed as a stand-alone document. It should exist as one part of a set of planning documents that start with a charter and a vision statement, but that also extends beyond the strategic plan into tactical and communications plans. Each of these has a role in providing context and action ability for the strategic plan. Organizations that have an established enterprise architecture (EA) function should leverage the existing EA disciplines, processes and standards to ensure that the strategic plan for information security is aligned with the EA strategy (see "Architecting Security: Different Approaches"). Securitysense generally considers three years to be an appropriate window for strategic planning for information security. The charter and vision statements deal with longer-term directions, while the tactical and communications plans specify single-year operational considerations and projects.</span></span></p>\r\n<span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The basic layout of the strategic plan is:</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Introduction and executive summary</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Strategic plan framework description</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Current state</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Desired state</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Gap analysis</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Prioritization plan</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Roles and responsibilities</span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>Introduction and Executive Summary</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The introduction should be written first, setting the purpose and scope of the document. The executive summary should be written last, showing only the final points of the document. The combination of executive summary and introduction should not exceed three pages, and, for most organizations, should be no more than two pages.</span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>Strategic Plan Framework Description</b></span></span>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The framework is the method by which the current state, desired state and gap analysis will be documented. An appropriate framework is one that can show overview (summarized) and detail (planning) information. The summary information should be expressed graphically. Frameworks should encompass controls, architecture and process elements to be complete.</span></span></p>\r\n<span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">For organizations with an established EA practice, an enterprise information security architecture (EISA) framework (see "The Structure and Content of an Information Security Architecture Framework") that aligns with the EA framework can act as an effective overall strategic security planning framework. Frameworks for this purpose can be derived from industry standards, from Securitysense research or from a combination of the two. </span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Some sources for framework structure and contents are:</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Controls</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">International Organization for Standardization (ISO)/International Electro technical</span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Commission (IEC) 27002</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Control Objectives for Information and Related Technology (COBIT)</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">U.S. National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) SP800-53</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Architecture</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">ISO10181</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">ISO13335</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Processes</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">ISO/IEC 27001</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Information Technology Infrastructure Library (ITIL)</span></span>\r\n<!--nextpage-->\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">In addition, Securitysense research can provide significant examples and guidelines for constructing such a framework (see the Recommended Reading section below). Large, mature organizations will require more-complex, detailed frameworks that focus largely on processes. Smaller or less mature organizations will find that simple frameworks suffice, and that all details can be left to the tactical planning stage, but that balanced (perhaps, not equal) attention to the three areas of controls, architecture and processes is required. An example of a simple framework for a low maturity organization might be a three-by-four grid showing the state of controls, technical architecture and processes for data, infrastructure, applications and people/behavior. Each cell in the grid can be assessed or targeted (depending on whether it is the current state or desired state framework copy) on a typical numeric maturity scale of 0 through 5, or assigned a color code of red, yellow or green (see Figure 1).</span></span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nFig 1\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Larger or more-mature organizations will tend to focus more on process assessments, because controls and architecture tend to be well-defined, and the processes by which they are kept up to date will be defined and will be the primary lever for further maturation. </span></span><span style="color: #ff0000;"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Securitysense''s "Toolkit: Risk Program Maturity Assessment 1.0" provides a full process-oriented framework that includes graphical reporting of information security, privacy, regulatory compliance and business continuity</span></span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="color: #ff0000;"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">programs (see Figure 2).</span></span></span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Figure 2. Strategic Plan Contents: Current State</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Controls Architecture Process</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Data</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Infrastructure</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Applications</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>People</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPSMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">N/A</span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: xx-small;"><b>Source: Securitysense (September 2008)</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>Current State</b></span></span>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Use the framework described in the previous section to document the current state of each element contained within the framework. A brief text section describes each entry and justifies the assessment. Organizations with mature risk assessment processes may reference the current risk register to provide an assessment of existing controls.</span></span></p>\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>Desired State</b></span></span>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Document the desired state for each element within the framework. Three years is not a long time to achieve any sort of cultural change, nor for a significant reduction in the overall level of risk. Using a maturity scale from zero through five, with steps of one-half for each of the framework elements, allows sufficient granularity to show, at a strategic level, what degree of progress is being attempted. Brief text descriptions contain the background for each target value. Securitysense recommends that a change in maturity level of no more than a "2" be attempted for any framework element in a three-year period, unless exceptional resources and executive support can be assured (see Figure 3 for an example based on Figure 1).</span></span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Figure 3. Strategic Plan Contents: Target State</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Controls Architecture Process</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Data</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Infrastructure</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Applications</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>People</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPSMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">N/A</span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The desired state may also identify controls and technology areas that require change, retirement or replacement, if those have already been identified.</span></span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>Gap Analysis</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">This section describes those elements of the framework that demonstrate variation between current and desired states (see Figure 4).</span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Figure 4. Strategic Plan Contents: Gap Analysis</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Controls Architecture Process</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPSMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">+2 +1 +1</span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPSMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">+2</span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPSMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">+2 +1 +1</span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Data</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Infrastructure</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Applications</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>People</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPSMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">N/A +1</span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>Prioritization Plan</b></span></span>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">There may be a natural order to resolving many of the issues identified via the gap analysis. Part of the three-year strategic plan should be guidance to tactical planners on how to prioritize the closure of those gaps, such that any natural order is optimized. Controls determine what should be achieved, but controls become meaningful only if the governance structure is functional. The IT organization needs direction via technical architecture to be efficient, but architecture requires guidance from controls. Operational processes related to technologies that are already in place depend, to some degree, on controls (what processes and technologies are needed) and architecture (which process elements and technologies are automated). As a result, a normal prioritization plan might be to start with governance, move to controls, then architecture and finally process. But this is a "greenfield" approach, and it may not be appropriate for organizations with variable levels of maturity in the current information security program or IT organizations in general. For example, a lack of maturity in strategic processes, such as risk assessment and security communications, which are not technology-dependent may demand earlier prioritization.</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Therefore, the method by which priorities will be assigned in the tactical plans requires some</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">strategic guidance. More-granular prioritization of work should be included in tactical (annual) planning documents, and should be based on criteria such as the relative risk impact, the cost, the mean time to value and the availability of resources.</span></span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>Roles and Responsibilities</b></span></span>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">This section describes who is responsible for delivering and who is responsible for approving each strategic and tactical deliverable that results from this strategic plan. There are four sets of organizational areas that need to be mapped to deliverables and action plans:</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY">• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The security office</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY">• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Lines of business (LOBs) or federation issues (responsibilities that reside with persons or departments </span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">that are affiliated with, but not reporting to, the central information security function)</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY">• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The IT organization</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY">• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Other business areas (typically, the functions that go on in headquarters, such as legal, HR and finance)</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The security office''s responsibilities should be easily extracted from the security charter. The authority, rights and obligations of LOB management and the IT organization should have been negotiated via the governance structure prior to, or as part of, the creation of this strategic plan. These authorities, rights and obligations are typically governed via some kind of information security steering committee. Other business areas may be surprised by their inclusion or may have expressed a need for involvement on their own, typically as a response to regulatory compliance needs.</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">One approach to documenting these roles and responsibilities that has been widely accepted by organization is the use of a responsible, accountable, consulted and informed (RACI) matrix. Once all these steps have been outlined, the executive summary can be written.</span></span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;', 'Security Strategy', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '398-revision-v1', '', '', '2013-08-29 01:06:23', '2013-08-29 01:06:23', '', 398, 'http://localhost/wordpress/?p=456', 0, 'revision', '', 0);
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` (`ID`, `post_author`, `post_date`, `post_date_gmt`, `post_content`, `post_title`, `post_excerpt`, `post_status`, `comment_status`, `ping_status`, `post_password`, `post_name`, `to_ping`, `pinged`, `post_modified`, `post_modified_gmt`, `post_content_filtered`, `post_parent`, `guid`, `menu_order`, `post_type`, `post_mime_type`, `comment_count`) VALUES
(455, 1, '2013-08-29 01:05:01', '2013-08-29 01:05:01', '<style type="text/css"><!--\r\n@page { margin: 0.79in } 		P { margin-bottom: 0.08in }\r\n--></style>\r\n<table width="498" border="0">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td><a><img class="wp-image-439 alignleft" alt="pdf-logo" src="http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/pdf-logo.jpg" width="51" height="51" /></a></td>\r\n<td>\r\n<h3 style="text-align: left;"><strong>2009-2011 Information Security Strategy for securitysense</strong></h3>\r\n</td>\r\n<td><a href="http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2009-2011-Information-Security-Strategy-for-securitysense.pdf"><img class="wp-image-444 alignleft" alt="download_iamge" src="http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/download_iamge.jpg" width="176" height="103" /></a></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>How to develop a IT/Information security strategy for your company?</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;">An information security strategic plan should include, at a minimum, an assessment of the current state of the program, a defined target state that is achievable within the three-year strategic planning window, a gap analysis and a road map for closing the gaps.</span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><b>Key Findings</b></span>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY">• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">A consistent framework can be defined that supports risk mitigation control objectives, architecture and </span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">process objectives, but the framework varies in scale and by the maturity level of the organization it''s </span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">being applied to.</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY">• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Small or immature organizations should focus on very simple frameworks.</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY">• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Consistent, incremental improvements are much more likely to succeed than rapidly forced changes.</span></span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><b>Recommendations</b></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Develop and document an information security strategic plan and use it to generate annual tactical </span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">plans that, when executed, move the overall maturity of the security program upward.</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Develop a process to review and refine the strategic plan annually.</span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><b>ANALYSIS</b></span>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Many organizations and security officers are approaching the creation of a strategic plan for information security for the first time, or have expressed a desire to use previously unimplemented best practices in creating the next iteration of one. Although there is no industry standard for the contents of such a plan, Securitysense has recommended organizations by using a model that has proved to be an effective communication tool with the numerous interested parties (including senior management), as well as a reasonable tracking mechanism for multiyear progress reports. While the model can be applied by organizations of any size and in any industry, the details vary based on the scale of the organization and the starting maturity level of the various effected organizational units.</span></span></p>\r\n<!--nextpage-->\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The information security strategic plan should not be viewed as a stand-alone document. It should exist as one part of a set of planning documents that start with a charter and a vision statement, but that also extends beyond the strategic plan into tactical and communications plans. Each of these has a role in providing context and action ability for the strategic plan. Organizations that have an established enterprise architecture (EA) function should leverage the existing EA disciplines, processes and standards to ensure that the strategic plan for information security is aligned with the EA strategy (see "Architecting Security: Different Approaches"). Securitysense generally considers three years to be an appropriate window for strategic planning for information security. The charter and vision statements deal with longer-term directions, while the tactical and communications plans specify single-year operational considerations and projects.</span></span></p>\r\n<span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The basic layout of the strategic plan is:</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Introduction and executive summary</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Strategic plan framework description</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Current state</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Desired state</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Gap analysis</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Prioritization plan</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Roles and responsibilities</span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>Introduction and Executive Summary</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The introduction should be written first, setting the purpose and scope of the document. The executive summary should be written last, showing only the final points of the document. The combination of executive summary and introduction should not exceed three pages, and, for most organizations, should be no more than two pages.</span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>Strategic Plan Framework Description</b></span></span>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The framework is the method by which the current state, desired state and gap analysis will be documented. An appropriate framework is one that can show overview (summarized) and detail (planning) information. The summary information should be expressed graphically. Frameworks should encompass controls, architecture and process elements to be complete.</span></span></p>\r\n<span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">For organizations with an established EA practice, an enterprise information security architecture (EISA) framework (see "The Structure and Content of an Information Security Architecture Framework") that aligns with the EA framework can act as an effective overall strategic security planning framework. Frameworks for this purpose can be derived from industry standards, from Securitysense research or from a combination of the two. </span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Some sources for framework structure and contents are:</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Controls</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">International Organization for Standardization (ISO)/International Electro technical</span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Commission (IEC) 27002</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Control Objectives for Information and Related Technology (COBIT)</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">U.S. National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) SP800-53</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Architecture</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">ISO10181</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">ISO13335</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Processes</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">ISO/IEC 27001</span></span>\r\n\r\n• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Information Technology Infrastructure Library (ITIL)</span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">In addition, Securitysense research can provide significant examples and guidelines for constructing such a framework (see the Recommended Reading section below). Large, mature organizations will require more-complex, detailed frameworks that focus largely on processes. Smaller or less mature organizations will find that simple frameworks suffice, and that all details can be left to the tactical planning stage, but that balanced (perhaps, not equal) attention to the three areas of controls, architecture and processes is required. An example of a simple framework for a low maturity organization might be a three-by-four grid showing the state of controls, technical architecture and processes for data, infrastructure, applications and people/behavior. Each cell in the grid can be assessed or targeted (depending on whether it is the current state or desired state framework copy) on a typical numeric maturity scale of 0 through 5, or assigned a color code of red, yellow or green (see Figure 1).</span></span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nFig 1\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Larger or more-mature organizations will tend to focus more on process assessments, because controls and architecture tend to be well-defined, and the processes by which they are kept up to date will be defined and will be the primary lever for further maturation. </span></span><span style="color: #ff0000;"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Securitysense''s "Toolkit: Risk Program Maturity Assessment 1.0" provides a full process-oriented framework that includes graphical reporting of information security, privacy, regulatory compliance and business continuity</span></span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="color: #ff0000;"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">programs (see Figure 2).</span></span></span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Figure 2. Strategic Plan Contents: Current State</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Controls Architecture Process</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Data</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Infrastructure</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Applications</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>People</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPSMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">N/A</span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: xx-small;"><b>Source: Securitysense (September 2008)</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>Current State</b></span></span>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Use the framework described in the previous section to document the current state of each element contained within the framework. A brief text section describes each entry and justifies the assessment. Organizations with mature risk assessment processes may reference the current risk register to provide an assessment of existing controls.</span></span></p>\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>Desired State</b></span></span>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Document the desired state for each element within the framework. Three years is not a long time to achieve any sort of cultural change, nor for a significant reduction in the overall level of risk. Using a maturity scale from zero through five, with steps of one-half for each of the framework elements, allows sufficient granularity to show, at a strategic level, what degree of progress is being attempted. Brief text descriptions contain the background for each target value. Securitysense recommends that a change in maturity level of no more than a "2" be attempted for any framework element in a three-year period, unless exceptional resources and executive support can be assured (see Figure 3 for an example based on Figure 1).</span></span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Figure 3. Strategic Plan Contents: Target State</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Controls Architecture Process</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Data</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Infrastructure</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Applications</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>People</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPSMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">N/A</span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The desired state may also identify controls and technology areas that require change, retirement or replacement, if those have already been identified.</span></span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>Gap Analysis</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">This section describes those elements of the framework that demonstrate variation between current and desired states (see Figure 4).</span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Figure 4. Strategic Plan Contents: Gap Analysis</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Controls Architecture Process</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPSMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">+2 +1 +1</span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPSMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">+2</span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPSMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">+2 +1 +1</span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Data</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Infrastructure</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>Applications</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPS-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><b>People</b></span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: TimesNewRomanPSMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">N/A +1</span></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>Prioritization Plan</b></span></span>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">There may be a natural order to resolving many of the issues identified via the gap analysis. Part of the three-year strategic plan should be guidance to tactical planners on how to prioritize the closure of those gaps, such that any natural order is optimized. Controls determine what should be achieved, but controls become meaningful only if the governance structure is functional. The IT organization needs direction via technical architecture to be efficient, but architecture requires guidance from controls. Operational processes related to technologies that are already in place depend, to some degree, on controls (what processes and technologies are needed) and architecture (which process elements and technologies are automated). As a result, a normal prioritization plan might be to start with governance, move to controls, then architecture and finally process. But this is a "greenfield" approach, and it may not be appropriate for organizations with variable levels of maturity in the current information security program or IT organizations in general. For example, a lack of maturity in strategic processes, such as risk assessment and security communications, which are not technology-dependent may demand earlier prioritization.</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Therefore, the method by which priorities will be assigned in the tactical plans requires some</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">strategic guidance. More-granular prioritization of work should be included in tactical (annual) planning documents, and should be based on criteria such as the relative risk impact, the cost, the mean time to value and the availability of resources.</span></span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-family: Arial-BoldMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>Roles and Responsibilities</b></span></span>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">This section describes who is responsible for delivering and who is responsible for approving each strategic and tactical deliverable that results from this strategic plan. There are four sets of organizational areas that need to be mapped to deliverables and action plans:</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY">• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The security office</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY">• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Lines of business (LOBs) or federation issues (responsibilities that reside with persons or departments </span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">that are affiliated with, but not reporting to, the central information security function)</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY">• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The IT organization</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY">• <span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Other business areas (typically, the functions that go on in headquarters, such as legal, HR and finance)</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The security office''s responsibilities should be easily extracted from the security charter. The authority, rights and obligations of LOB management and the IT organization should have been negotiated via the governance structure prior to, or as part of, the creation of this strategic plan. These authorities, rights and obligations are typically governed via some kind of information security steering committee. Other business areas may be surprised by their inclusion or may have expressed a need for involvement on their own, typically as a response to regulatory compliance needs.</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: ArialMT,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">One approach to documenting these roles and responsibilities that has been widely accepted by organization is the use of a responsible, accountable, consulted and informed (RACI) matrix. Once all these steps have been outlined, the executive summary can be written.</span></span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;', 'Security Strategy', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '398-revision-v1', '', '', '2013-08-29 01:05:01', '2013-08-29 01:05:01', '', 398, 'http://localhost/wordpress/?p=455', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(457, 1, '2013-08-29 01:16:44', '2013-08-29 01:16:44', '', 'Security Framework: Policy Procedure', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'security-framework-policy-procedure-development', '', '', '2013-08-29 08:28:14', '2013-08-29 08:28:14', '', 0, 'http://localhost/wordpress/?p=457', 2, 'nav_menu_item', '', 0),
(459, 1, '2013-08-29 01:19:54', '2013-08-29 01:19:54', '<style type="text/css"><!--\r\n@page { margin: 0.79in } 		H1 { margin-top: 0.33in; margin-bottom: 0in; color: #365f91; page-break-inside: avoid } 		H1.western { font-family: "Cambria", serif; font-size: 14pt } 		H1.cjk { font-family: "DejaVu Sans"; font-size: 14pt } 		H1.ctl { font-family: ; font-size: 14pt } 		P { margin-bottom: 0.08in } 		H2 { margin-top: 0.02in; margin-bottom: 0.02in; line-height: 100%; page-break-after: auto } 		H2.western { font-family: "Times New Roman", serif } 		H2.cjk { font-family: "Times New Roman" } 		H2.ctl { font-family: "Times New Roman" }\r\n--></style>\r\n<h2 align="JUSTIFY">Difference between Policy, Process, Procedure, Guideline and Standard</h2>\r\n<h1 align="JUSTIFY"><em><span style="color: #000000;"><span style="font-size: medium;">The terms ‘Policies’, ‘Processes’, and ‘Procedures’ are too </span></span></em><em><span style="color: #000000;"><span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;">often interchanged.  ‘Policies’, ‘Processes’, and ‘Procedures’ should be considered distinct types of documentation.</span></span></span></em><span style="color: #000000;"><span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;"> </span></span></span></h1>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;"><b>The researching and developing documentation requires understanding the distinctions between a Policy, a Procedure, or a Process. All address related subject matter, but at a different level and with different types of content.  Each type has a unique purpose that drives the content contained in each type of document.  Describing the distinctions using <em>who, what, where,</em> <em>when, why</em> and <em>how</em> often helps to understand and properly structure them. </b></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<h2 align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-size: large;">Policy </span></h2>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;">An information security policy consists of </span></span><span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;"><b>high level statements</b></span></span><span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;"> relating to the protection of information across the business and should be produced by senior management.</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="color: #00577d;"> </span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;">The policy outlines security roles and responsibilities, defines the scope of information to be protected, and provides a high level description of the controls that must be in place to protect information. In addition, it should make references to the standards and guidelines that support it. Businesses may have a single encompassing policy, or several specific policies that target different areas, such as an email policy or acceptable use policy. From a legal and compliance perspective, an information security policy is often viewed as a commitment from senior management to protect information. A documented policy is frequently a requirement to satisfy regulations or laws, such as those relating to privacy and finance. It should be viewed as a business mandate and must be driven from the top (i.e. senior management) downwards in order to be effective.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;"><b>Policies are the business rules and guidelines of a company that ensure consistency and compliance with the company’s strategic direction.  The Policies lay out the business rules under which a company, division, or department will operate.</b></span></span></p>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;"><b>Policies are the guidelines under which Procedures are developed.  There is not a one-to-one relationship between a Policy and a Procedure.  Policies are not part of the Procedure, because they cannot be properly structured.  However, the Procedure must reflect the business rules contained in the Policies. </b></span></span></p>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;"><b>Policies address <em>what</em> the Policy is and its classification,<em> who</em> is responsible for the execution and enforcement of the Policy, and <em>why</em> the Policy is required.  </b></span></span></p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h2 align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-size: large;">Process </span></h2>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;">Processes are related activities that produce a specific service or product (example, Procurement to Payment).  The majority of Processes cross departments or functional areas.  Each Process designates the connect points and where it crosses department lines.  The documentation presents the total Process.  It is helpful to be able to reference or drill down to the applicable Policy or Procedure for a Process step.  A Process map is a useful tool to graphically display the Process. </span></span></p>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;">Processes indicate where there is a separation of responsibilities and control points.  They are also very helpful to identify Policy and Procedure requirements.  Processes address </span></span><em><span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;"><b>who</b></span></span></em><span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;"> is responsible to perform the Process (department, division), </span></span><em><span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;"><b>what</b></span></span></em><span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;"> major functions are performed, and </span></span><em><span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;"><b>when</b></span></span></em><span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;"> the function is triggered.  </span></span></p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h2 align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-size: large;">Procedure </span></h2>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;">Procedures consist of </span></span><span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;"><b>step by step instructions</b></span></span><span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;"> to assist workers in implementing the various policies, standards and guidelines.</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="color: #00577d;"> </span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;">Whilst the policies, standards and guidelines consist of the controls that should be in place, a procedure gets down to specifics, explaining how to implement these controls in a step by step fashion. For example, a procedure could be written to explain how to install Windows securely, detailing each step that needs to be taken to harden/secure the operating system so that it satisfies the applicable policy, standards and guidelines.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;">Procedures define the specific instructions necessary to perform a task or part of a Process.  Procedures can take the form of a work instruction, a desk top Procedure, a quick reference guide, or a more detailed Procedure. </span></span></p>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;">Procedures usually are structured by subject (for example, system instructions, report instructions, or Process tasks).  A Procedure usually addresses only a single task.  This separation enables Procedure components to be compiled into special Procedure manuals for specific audiences, end users, and purposes.</span></span></p>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;">Procedures detail </span></span><em><span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;"><b>who</b></span></span></em><span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;"> performs the Procedure, </span></span><em><span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;"><b>what</b></span></span></em><span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;"> steps are performed, </span></span><em><span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;"><b>when</b></span></span></em><span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;"> the steps are performed, and </span></span><em><span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;"><b>how</b></span></span></em><span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;"> the Procedure is performed. </span></span></p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>Guidelines</b></span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="color: #00577d;"> </span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;">Guidelines consist of </span></span><span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;"><b>recommended,</b></span></span><span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;"><b>non-mandatory controls</b></span></span><span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;"> that help support standards or serve as a reference when no applicable standard is in place.  </span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="color: #00577d;"> </span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;">Guidelines should be viewed as best practices that are not usually requirements, but are strongly recommended. They could consist of additional recommended controls that support a standard, or help fill in the gaps where no specific standard applies. For example, a standard may require passwords to be 8 characters or more and a supporting guideline may state that it is best practice to also ensure the password expires after 30 days. In another example, a standard may require specific technical controls for accessing the internet securely and a separate guideline may outline the best practices for using the internet and managing your online presence.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<h1><span style="color: #000000;"><span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: x-large;">Standard</span></span></span></h1>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;">There are many definitions of a ''standard''. Very generally, a standard might simply be defined as <em>''a set of rules for ensuring quality''</em>.</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;">ISO/IEC Guide 2:1996, definition 3.2 defines a standard as:</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;"><em><span style="color: #000000;"><b>''A document established by consensus and approved by a recognized body that provides for common and repeated use, rules, guidelines or characteristics for activities or their results, aimed at the achievement of the optimum degree of order in a given context''</b></span></em><span style="color: #000000;"><i><b>.</b></i></span></span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;">Standards consist of specific</span></span><span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;"><b> low level</b></span></span><span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;"><b>mandatory controls</b></span></span><span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;"> that help enforce and support the information security policy.</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="color: #00577d;"> </span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;">Standards help to ensure security consistency across the business and usually contain security controls relating to the implementation of specific technology, hardware or software. For example, a password standard may set out rules for password complexity and a Windows standard may set out the rules for hardening Windows clients.</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;">In essence, a standard is an agreed way of doing something. It could be about making a product, managing a process, delivering a service or supplying materials – standards can cover a huge range of activities undertaken by organizations and used by their customers.</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;">Standards are the distilled wisdom of people with expertise in their subject matter and who know the needs of the organizations they represent – people such as manufacturers, sellers, buyers, customers, trade associations, users or regulators.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<h1></h1>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;', 'Policy, Process, Procedure, Guideline and Standard - What is the Difference?', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '411-revision-v1', '', '', '2013-08-29 01:19:54', '2013-08-29 01:19:54', '', 411, 'http://localhost/wordpress/?p=459', 0, 'revision', '', 0);
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` (`ID`, `post_author`, `post_date`, `post_date_gmt`, `post_content`, `post_title`, `post_excerpt`, `post_status`, `comment_status`, `ping_status`, `post_password`, `post_name`, `to_ping`, `pinged`, `post_modified`, `post_modified_gmt`, `post_content_filtered`, `post_parent`, `guid`, `menu_order`, `post_type`, `post_mime_type`, `comment_count`) VALUES
(462, 1, '2013-08-29 01:27:15', '2013-08-29 01:27:15', '<style type="text/css"><!--\r\n@page { margin: 0.79in } 		H1 { margin-top: 0.33in; margin-bottom: 0in; color: #365f91; page-break-inside: avoid } 		H1.western { font-family: "Cambria", serif; font-size: 14pt } 		H1.cjk { font-family: "DejaVu Sans"; font-size: 14pt } 		H1.ctl { font-family: ; font-size: 14pt } 		P { margin-bottom: 0.08in } 		H2 { margin-top: 0.02in; margin-bottom: 0.02in; line-height: 100%; page-break-after: auto } 		H2.western { font-family: "Times New Roman", serif } 		H2.cjk { font-family: "Times New Roman" } 		H2.ctl { font-family: "Times New Roman" }\r\n--></style>\r\n<h2 align="JUSTIFY">Difference between Policy, Process, Procedure, Guideline and Standard</h2>\r\n<span style="font-size: medium;">The terms ‘Policies’, ‘Processes’, and ‘Procedures’ are too </span><span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;">often interchanged.  ‘Policies’, ‘Processes’, and ‘Procedures’ should be considered distinct types of documentation.</span></span>\r\n\r\n<span style="font-size: medium;">The researching and developing documentation requires understanding the distinctions between a Policy, a Procedure, or a Process. All address related subject matter, but at a different level and with different types of content. Each type has a unique purpose that drives the content contained in each type of document. Describing the distinctions using who, what, where, when, why and how often helps to understand and properly structure them. </span>\r\n<h2 align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-size: large;">Policy </span></h2>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;">An information security policy consists of </span></span><span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;"><b>high level statements</b></span></span><span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;"> relating to the protection of information across the business and should be produced by senior management.</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="color: #00577d;"> </span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;">The policy outlines security roles and responsibilities, defines the scope of information to be protected, and provides a high level description of the controls that must be in place to protect information. In addition, it should make references to the standards and guidelines that support it. Businesses may have a single encompassing policy, or several specific policies that target different areas, such as an email policy or acceptable use policy. From a legal and compliance perspective, an information security policy is often viewed as a commitment from senior management to protect information. A documented policy is frequently a requirement to satisfy regulations or laws, such as those relating to privacy and finance. It should be viewed as a business mandate and must be driven from the top (i.e. senior management) downwards in order to be effective.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;"><b>Policies are the business rules and guidelines of a company that ensure consistency and compliance with the company’s strategic direction.  The Policies lay out the business rules under which a company, division, or department will operate.</b></span></span></p>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;"><b>Policies are the guidelines under which Procedures are developed.  There is not a one-to-one relationship between a Policy and a Procedure.  Policies are not part of the Procedure, because they cannot be properly structured.  However, the Procedure must reflect the business rules contained in the Policies. </b></span></span></p>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;"><b>Policies address <em>what</em> the Policy is and its classification,<em> who</em> is responsible for the execution and enforcement of the Policy, and <em>why</em> the Policy is required.  </b></span></span></p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<!--nextpage-->\r\n<h2 align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-size: large;">Process </span></h2>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;">Processes are related activities that produce a specific service or product (example, Procurement to Payment).  The majority of Processes cross departments or functional areas.  Each Process designates the connect points and where it crosses department lines.  The documentation presents the total Process.  It is helpful to be able to reference or drill down to the applicable Policy or Procedure for a Process step.  A Process map is a useful tool to graphically display the Process. </span></span></p>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;">Processes indicate where there is a separation of responsibilities and control points.  They are also very helpful to identify Policy and Procedure requirements.  Processes address </span></span><em><span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;"><b>who</b></span></span></em><span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;"> is responsible to perform the Process (department, division), </span></span><em><span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;"><b>what</b></span></span></em><span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;"> major functions are performed, and </span></span><em><span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;"><b>when</b></span></span></em><span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;"> the function is triggered.  </span></span></p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h2 align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-size: large;">Procedure </span></h2>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;">Procedures consist of </span></span><span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;"><b>step by step instructions</b></span></span><span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;"> to assist workers in implementing the various policies, standards and guidelines.</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="color: #00577d;"> </span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;">Whilst the policies, standards and guidelines consist of the controls that should be in place, a procedure gets down to specifics, explaining how to implement these controls in a step by step fashion. For example, a procedure could be written to explain how to install Windows securely, detailing each step that needs to be taken to harden/secure the operating system so that it satisfies the applicable policy, standards and guidelines.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;">Procedures define the specific instructions necessary to perform a task or part of a Process.  Procedures can take the form of a work instruction, a desk top Procedure, a quick reference guide, or a more detailed Procedure. </span></span></p>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;">Procedures usually are structured by subject (for example, system instructions, report instructions, or Process tasks).  A Procedure usually addresses only a single task.  This separation enables Procedure components to be compiled into special Procedure manuals for specific audiences, end users, and purposes.</span></span></p>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;">Procedures detail </span></span><em><span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;"><b>who</b></span></span></em><span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;"> performs the Procedure, </span></span><em><span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;"><b>what</b></span></span></em><span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;"> steps are performed, </span></span><em><span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;"><b>when</b></span></span></em><span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;"> the steps are performed, and </span></span><em><span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;"><b>how</b></span></span></em><span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;"> the Procedure is performed. </span></span></p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: large;"><b>Guidelines</b></span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="color: #00577d;"> </span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;">Guidelines consist of </span></span><span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;"><b>recommended,</b></span></span><span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;"><b>non-mandatory controls</b></span></span><span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;"> that help support standards or serve as a reference when no applicable standard is in place.  </span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="color: #00577d;"> </span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;">Guidelines should be viewed as best practices that are not usually requirements, but are strongly recommended. They could consist of additional recommended controls that support a standard, or help fill in the gaps where no specific standard applies. For example, a standard may require passwords to be 8 characters or more and a supporting guideline may state that it is best practice to also ensure the password expires after 30 days. In another example, a standard may require specific technical controls for accessing the internet securely and a separate guideline may outline the best practices for using the internet and managing your online presence.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<h1><span style="color: #000000;"><span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: x-large;">Standard</span></span></span></h1>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;">There are many definitions of a ''standard''. Very generally, a standard might simply be defined as <em>''a set of rules for ensuring quality''</em>.</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;">ISO/IEC Guide 2:1996, definition 3.2 defines a standard as:</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;"><em><span style="color: #000000;"><b>''A document established by consensus and approved by a recognized body that provides for common and repeated use, rules, guidelines or characteristics for activities or their results, aimed at the achievement of the optimum degree of order in a given context''</b></span></em><span style="color: #000000;"><i><b>.</b></i></span></span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;">Standards consist of specific</span></span><span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;"><b> low level</b></span></span><span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;"><b>mandatory controls</b></span></span><span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;"> that help enforce and support the information security policy.</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="color: #00577d;"> </span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;">Standards help to ensure security consistency across the business and usually contain security controls relating to the implementation of specific technology, hardware or software. For example, a password standard may set out rules for password complexity and a Windows standard may set out the rules for hardening Windows clients.</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;">In essence, a standard is an agreed way of doing something. It could be about making a product, managing a process, delivering a service or supplying materials – standards can cover a huge range of activities undertaken by organizations and used by their customers.</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;">Standards are the distilled wisdom of people with expertise in their subject matter and who know the needs of the organizations they represent – people such as manufacturers, sellers, buyers, customers, trade associations, users or regulators.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<h1></h1>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;', 'Policy, Process, Procedure, Guideline and Standard - What is the Difference?', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '411-revision-v1', '', '', '2013-08-29 01:27:15', '2013-08-29 01:27:15', '', 411, 'http://localhost/wordpress/?p=462', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(463, 1, '2013-08-29 01:44:34', '2013-08-29 01:44:34', '', 'BCM(Business Continuity Management)', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'bcmbusiness-continuity-management', '', '', '2013-08-29 08:28:14', '2013-08-29 08:28:14', '', 0, 'http://localhost/wordpress/?p=463', 14, 'nav_menu_item', '', 0),
(466, 1, '2013-08-29 01:49:23', '2013-08-29 01:49:23', '', 'Securitysense  BCM Policy v1.0', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', 'securitysense-bcm-policy-v1-0', '', '', '2013-08-29 01:49:23', '2013-08-29 01:49:23', '', 0, 'http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/Securitysense-BCM-Policy-v1.0.pdf', 0, 'attachment', 'application/pdf', 0),
(467, 1, '2013-08-29 01:50:34', '2013-08-29 01:50:34', '<style type="text/css"><!--\r\n@page { margin: 0.79in }\r\n		P { margin-bottom: 0.08in }\r\n		A:link { so-language: zxx }\r\n--></style>\r\n<table width="498" border="0">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td><a><img alt="pdf-logo" src="http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/pdf-logo.jpg" width="51" height="51" /></a></td>\r\n<td>\r\n<h3><strong>Securitysense Business Continuity Policy</strong></h3>\r\n</td>\r\n<td><a href="http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/Securitysense-BCM-Policy-v1.0.pdf"><img alt="download_iamge" src="http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/download_iamge.jpg" width="176" height="103" /></a></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<a name="Definitions"></a> <span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;"><b>A Definition of Business Continuity Management</b></span></span>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="color: #000000;"><span style="font-family: Trebuchet MS,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Business Continuity Management is an holistic management process that identifies potential impacts that threaten an organization and provides a framework for building resilience and the capability for an effective response that safeguards the interests of its key stakeholders, reputation, brand and value creating activities. BCM must be owned and fully integrated into the organization as an embedded management process.</span></span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="color: #000000;"><span style="font-family: Trebuchet MS,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">BCM aims to improve an organization</span></span></span><span style="color: #000000;"><span style="font-family: Trebuchet MS,serif;"><span style="font-size: xx-small;">’</span></span></span><span style="color: #000000;"><span style="font-family: Trebuchet MS,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">s resilience. By identifying, in advance, the potential impacts of a wide variety of sudden disruptions to the organization</span></span></span><span style="color: #000000;"><span style="font-family: Trebuchet MS,serif;"><span style="font-size: xx-small;">’</span></span></span><span style="color: #000000;"><span style="font-family: Trebuchet MS,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">s ability to succeed it is able to prioritize the efforts of various other specialists aiming to achieve resilience in their areas of expertise such as security, facilities and IT. While concerned with all scales of resilience, BCM is particularly concerned with developing organization-wide resilience allowing an organization to survive the loss of part or all of its operational capability. It should also look at surviving significant losses of resources such as staff or equipment. Because an organization</span></span></span><span style="color: #000000;"><span style="font-family: Trebuchet MS,serif;"><span style="font-size: xx-small;">’</span></span></span><span style="color: #000000;"><span style="font-family: Trebuchet MS,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">s BCM resilience depends on its management and operational staff as well as technology and geographical diversity, this resilience must be developed throughout the organization from senior management to shop floor and across all sites and the supply chain. </span></span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="color: #000000;"><span style="font-family: Trebuchet MS,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The driver for this organizational resilience is the responsibility the senior management have for the long-term interests of the staff, customers and all those who depend on the organization in some way. Whilst it may be possible to calculate the financial losses of disruption the most significant impact is usually in damaged reputation or loss of trust that results from a mismanaged incident. </span></span></span><span style="font-family: Trebuchet MS,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Conversely a well-managed incident can enhance the reputation of the</span></span><span style="font-family: Trebuchet MS,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">organization and its management team.</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;">Business Continuity Management means ensuring the continuity or uninterrupted provision of operations and services.  Business Continuity Management is an on-going process with several different but complementary elements. Planning for business continuity is a comprehensive process that includes disaster recovery, business recovery, business resumption, and contingency planning as shown below.</span></span></p>\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"> <a href="http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/BCP.gif"><img class="size-medium wp-image-374 aligncenter" alt="BCP" src="http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/BCP-300x128.gif" width="438" height="186" /></a></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;">As described above, Business Continuity Management is meant to have a very broad meaning and is often used as an all-encompassing term to describe an integrated and enterprise-wide process that should include the following in alphabetical order: </span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><span style="font-family: Verdana,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">accident prevention</span></span></li>\r\n	<li><a href="http://www.davislogic.com/business_continuity_planning.htm"><span style="color: #0000ff;"><span style="font-family: Verdana,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><span style="text-decoration: underline;">business impact analysis</span></span></span></span></a></li>\r\n	<li><span style="font-family: Verdana,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">business recovery</span></span></li>\r\n	<li><span style="font-family: Verdana,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">business resumption planning</span></span></li>\r\n	<li><a href="http://www.davislogic.com/command.htm"><span style="color: #0000ff;"><span style="font-family: Verdana,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><span style="text-decoration: underline;">command centers</span></span></span></span></a><span style="font-family: Verdana,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"> </span></span></li>\r\n	<li><a href="http://www.davislogic.com/computer_security.htm"><span style="color: #0000ff;"><span style="font-family: Verdana,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><span style="text-decoration: underline;">computer security</span></span></span></span></a></li>\r\n	<li><a href="http://www.davislogic.com/contingency%20planning.htm"><span style="color: #0000ff;"><span style="font-family: Verdana,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><span style="text-decoration: underline;">contingency planning</span></span></span></span></a></li>\r\n	<li><a href="http://www.davislogic.com/event_management.htm"><span style="color: #0000ff;"><span style="font-family: Verdana,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><span style="text-decoration: underline;">crisis communication</span></span></span></span></a></li>\r\n	<li><a href="http://www.davislogic.com/emergency.htm"><span style="color: #0000ff;"><span style="font-family: Verdana,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><span style="text-decoration: underline;">crisis management</span></span></span></span></a></li>\r\n	<li><a href="http://www.davislogic.com/dr.htm"><span style="color: #0000ff;"><span style="font-family: Verdana,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><span style="text-decoration: underline;">disaster recovery</span></span></span></span></a></li>\r\n	<li><a href="http://www.davislogic.com/emergency.htm"><span style="color: #0000ff;"><span style="font-family: Verdana,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><span style="text-decoration: underline;">emergency management and response</span></span></span></span></a></li>\r\n	<li><a href="http://www.davislogic.com/event_management.htm"><span style="color: #0000ff;"><span style="font-family: Verdana,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><span style="text-decoration: underline;">event management</span></span></span></span></a></li>\r\n	<li><span style="font-family: Verdana,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">exercising and training</span></span></li>\r\n	<li><span style="font-family: Verdana,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">information security</span></span></li>\r\n	<li><span style="font-family: Verdana,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">mitigation planning</span></span></li>\r\n	<li><span style="font-family: Verdana,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">project management and quality control</span></span></li>\r\n	<li><span style="font-family: Verdana,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">risk control</span></span></li>\r\n	<li><span style="font-family: Verdana,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">risk financing and insurance</span></span></li>\r\n	<li><span style="font-family: Verdana,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">risk management</span></span></li>\r\n	<li><span style="font-family: Verdana,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">safety and security</span></span></li>\r\n	<li><a href="http://www.davislogic.com/warez.html"><span style="color: #0000ff;"><span style="font-family: Verdana,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><span style="text-decoration: underline;">software management</span></span></span></span></a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;">Business Continuity Management therefore, is a comprehensive process to ensure the continuation and improvement of business in the face of whatever challenges your firm may face. Continuity planning requires that these many processes be used together, to create a complete continuity plan. The plan must be maintained and updated as business processes change. Continuity plans must be tested.  Table top drills and functional exercises are generally used to make sure that to ensure that they will work.</span></span></p>', 'Business Continuity Management- What is it?', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '373-revision-v1', '', '', '2013-08-29 01:50:34', '2013-08-29 01:50:34', '', 373, 'http://localhost/wordpress/?p=467', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(468, 1, '2013-08-29 01:51:54', '2013-08-29 01:51:54', '<style type="text/css"><!--\r\n@page { margin: 0.79in } 		P { margin-bottom: 0.08in } 		A:link { so-language: zxx }\r\n--></style>\r\n<table width="498" border="0">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td><a><img alt="pdf-logo" src="http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/pdf-logo.jpg" width="51" height="51" /></a></td>\r\n<td>\r\n<h3 style="text-align: left;"><strong>Securitysense Business Continuity Policy</strong></h3>\r\n</td>\r\n<td><a href="http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/Securitysense-BCM-Policy-v1.0.pdf"><img alt="download_iamge" src="http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/download_iamge.jpg" width="176" height="103" /></a></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<a name="Definitions"></a> <span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;"><b>A Definition of Business Continuity Management</b></span></span>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="color: #000000;"><span style="font-family: Trebuchet MS,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Business Continuity Management is an holistic management process that identifies potential impacts that threaten an organization and provides a framework for building resilience and the capability for an effective response that safeguards the interests of its key stakeholders, reputation, brand and value creating activities. BCM must be owned and fully integrated into the organization as an embedded management process.</span></span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="color: #000000;"><span style="font-family: Trebuchet MS,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">BCM aims to improve an organization</span></span></span><span style="color: #000000;"><span style="font-family: Trebuchet MS,serif;"><span style="font-size: xx-small;">’</span></span></span><span style="color: #000000;"><span style="font-family: Trebuchet MS,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">s resilience. By identifying, in advance, the potential impacts of a wide variety of sudden disruptions to the organization</span></span></span><span style="color: #000000;"><span style="font-family: Trebuchet MS,serif;"><span style="font-size: xx-small;">’</span></span></span><span style="color: #000000;"><span style="font-family: Trebuchet MS,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">s ability to succeed it is able to prioritize the efforts of various other specialists aiming to achieve resilience in their areas of expertise such as security, facilities and IT. While concerned with all scales of resilience, BCM is particularly concerned with developing organization-wide resilience allowing an organization to survive the loss of part or all of its operational capability. It should also look at surviving significant losses of resources such as staff or equipment. Because an organization</span></span></span><span style="color: #000000;"><span style="font-family: Trebuchet MS,serif;"><span style="font-size: xx-small;">’</span></span></span><span style="color: #000000;"><span style="font-family: Trebuchet MS,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">s BCM resilience depends on its management and operational staff as well as technology and geographical diversity, this resilience must be developed throughout the organization from senior management to shop floor and across all sites and the supply chain. </span></span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="color: #000000;"><span style="font-family: Trebuchet MS,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">The driver for this organizational resilience is the responsibility the senior management have for the long-term interests of the staff, customers and all those who depend on the organization in some way. Whilst it may be possible to calculate the financial losses of disruption the most significant impact is usually in damaged reputation or loss of trust that results from a mismanaged incident. </span></span></span><span style="font-family: Trebuchet MS,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">Conversely a well-managed incident can enhance the reputation of the</span></span><span style="font-family: Trebuchet MS,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">organization and its management team.</span></span></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;">Business Continuity Management means ensuring the continuity or uninterrupted provision of operations and services.  Business Continuity Management is an on-going process with several different but complementary elements. Planning for business continuity is a comprehensive process that includes disaster recovery, business recovery, business resumption, and contingency planning as shown below.</span></span></p>\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"> <a href="http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/BCP.gif"><img class="size-medium wp-image-374 aligncenter" alt="BCP" src="http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/BCP-300x128.gif" width="438" height="186" /></a></p>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;">As described above, Business Continuity Management is meant to have a very broad meaning and is often used as an all-encompassing term to describe an integrated and enterprise-wide process that should include the following in alphabetical order: </span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><span style="font-family: Verdana,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">accident prevention</span></span></li>\r\n	<li><a href="http://www.davislogic.com/business_continuity_planning.htm"><span style="color: #0000ff;"><span style="font-family: Verdana,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><span style="text-decoration: underline;">business impact analysis</span></span></span></span></a></li>\r\n	<li><span style="font-family: Verdana,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">business recovery</span></span></li>\r\n	<li><span style="font-family: Verdana,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">business resumption planning</span></span></li>\r\n	<li><a href="http://www.davislogic.com/command.htm"><span style="color: #0000ff;"><span style="font-family: Verdana,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><span style="text-decoration: underline;">command centers</span></span></span></span></a><span style="font-family: Verdana,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"> </span></span></li>\r\n	<li><a href="http://www.davislogic.com/computer_security.htm"><span style="color: #0000ff;"><span style="font-family: Verdana,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><span style="text-decoration: underline;">computer security</span></span></span></span></a></li>\r\n	<li><a href="http://www.davislogic.com/contingency%20planning.htm"><span style="color: #0000ff;"><span style="font-family: Verdana,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><span style="text-decoration: underline;">contingency planning</span></span></span></span></a></li>\r\n	<li><a href="http://www.davislogic.com/event_management.htm"><span style="color: #0000ff;"><span style="font-family: Verdana,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><span style="text-decoration: underline;">crisis communication</span></span></span></span></a></li>\r\n	<li><a href="http://www.davislogic.com/emergency.htm"><span style="color: #0000ff;"><span style="font-family: Verdana,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><span style="text-decoration: underline;">crisis management</span></span></span></span></a></li>\r\n	<li><a href="http://www.davislogic.com/dr.htm"><span style="color: #0000ff;"><span style="font-family: Verdana,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><span style="text-decoration: underline;">disaster recovery</span></span></span></span></a></li>\r\n	<li><a href="http://www.davislogic.com/emergency.htm"><span style="color: #0000ff;"><span style="font-family: Verdana,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><span style="text-decoration: underline;">emergency management and response</span></span></span></span></a></li>\r\n	<li><a href="http://www.davislogic.com/event_management.htm"><span style="color: #0000ff;"><span style="font-family: Verdana,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><span style="text-decoration: underline;">event management</span></span></span></span></a></li>\r\n	<li><span style="font-family: Verdana,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">exercising and training</span></span></li>\r\n	<li><span style="font-family: Verdana,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">information security</span></span></li>\r\n	<li><span style="font-family: Verdana,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">mitigation planning</span></span></li>\r\n	<li><span style="font-family: Verdana,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">project management and quality control</span></span></li>\r\n	<li><span style="font-family: Verdana,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">risk control</span></span></li>\r\n	<li><span style="font-family: Verdana,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">risk financing and insurance</span></span></li>\r\n	<li><span style="font-family: Verdana,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">risk management</span></span></li>\r\n	<li><span style="font-family: Verdana,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;">safety and security</span></span></li>\r\n	<li><a href="http://www.davislogic.com/warez.html"><span style="color: #0000ff;"><span style="font-family: Verdana,serif;"><span style="font-size: small;"><span style="text-decoration: underline;">software management</span></span></span></span></a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p align="JUSTIFY"><span style="font-family: Times New Roman,serif;"><span style="font-size: medium;">Business Continuity Management therefore, is a comprehensive process to ensure the continuation and improvement of business in the face of whatever challenges your firm may face. Continuity planning requires that these many processes be used together, to create a complete continuity plan. The plan must be maintained and updated as business processes change. Continuity plans must be tested.  Table top drills and functional exercises are generally used to make sure that to ensure that they will work.</span></span></p>', 'Business Continuity Management- What is it?', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '373-revision-v1', '', '', '2013-08-29 01:51:54', '2013-08-29 01:51:54', '', 373, 'http://localhost/wordpress/?p=468', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
